<FIRST>r i PM-SAfrica-Play     02-14 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SAfrica-Play,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Johannesburg Critics Applaud U.S. Play With Racial Theme</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Driving Miss Daisy,'' a
prize-winning American play about an elderly white woman and her
black chauffeur, has opened here to rave reviews from critics
delighted by its low-key handling of racial friction.
   With the exception of one critic who found the script too bland,
black and white reviewers from pro-government and opposition
newspapers praised the play and the production.
   ``Driving Miss Daisy'' opened last week at the Market Theater,
which for the past decade has been Johannesburg's main showplace for
multiracial drama and has featured many militantly anti-apartheid
works.
   Barry Ronge, a critic for the Sunday Times, said the 1988
Pulitzer Prize-winning play by Alfred Uhry ``is about whites and
blacks interacting without anger and threat, a rare sight on the
Market's stages.''
   ``The audience's relief at seeing a play and not another harangue
was palpable,'' wrote Ronge, who is white.
   Writing in a Sunday Times' supplement for black readers, black
critic Ezra Mantini described it as a masterpiece ``with lots of
laughter and no reveling in anger or outcry.''
   A review in The Star, Johannesburg's largest-circulation daily,
said: ``Our playwrights could learn a lot from the effect of
subtlety and understatement'' in Uhry's handling of racial tension.
   The play depicts the evolving relationship between Daisy Werthan,
an elderly white aristocrat in Atlanta, and Hoke Coleburn, hired as
her chauffeur when she is no longer able to drive herself.
   The initial discomfort felt between the two gradually transforms
into deep friendship.
   A review in The Sowetan, the country's largest-selling black
daily, said the play ``is sure to win many theatergoers' hearts with
its easily recognizable and universal truth that racial discord
makes no sense at all.''
   The Sowetan's critic, Victor Metsoamere, said the bond that grows
between Hoke and Miss Daisy ``is bound to take a
hunndred-and-never-mind years to be cultivated in South Africa.''
   ``This is because of the unnerving charades of South Africa's
ultra-right wing groups who squirm no end at the black man's
extended hand of friendship,'' Metsoamere wrote.
   Two pro-government newspapers, The Citizen and Beeld, also
praised the production. Beeld, an Afrikaans-language daily, echoed
The Star in suggesting that playwrights should emulate Uhry's
indirect approach to political issues.
   The only mildly negative review come from the financial newspaper
Business Day, which praised the production but described the play as
``very sweet, entirely innocuous and utterly inconsequential.''
   ``It is the theatrical equivalent of greeting card philosophy,
designed to appeal to everyone, offend no one and contribute little
to the sum of human knowledge,'' wrote Business Day's Robert Grieg.
   Two of South Africa's best-known actors, John Kani and Annabel
Linder, play the leads in ``Driving Miss Daisy.''
   Kani last year became the first black to play Othello in a
professional production in South Africa, starring at the Market
under the direction of Janet Suzman, the South African-born actress
based in London.
   The director of ``Driving Miss Daisy'' is another white woman,
Janice Honeyman, whose previous production at the Market was a
highly praised enactment of African folk tales.
   Ms. Honeyman told the anti-apartheid weekly newspaper New Nation
the message of ``Driving Miss Daisy'' is that ``people are people.''
   ``They can relate to each other and enjoy each other's company,
and give to each other and teach each other without all the other
stuff that we're subjected to all the time in this God-forsaken
country,'' she said.
   ``There are going to be people coming here (to the Market) and
saying, `I'd forgotten that someone of another color can be my best
friend,''' she said.
</TEXT>
