<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--BunglingBandit     02-14 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Bungling Bandit,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bungling Bandit Pleads Guilty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DERIDDER, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bungling bandit who used a can of carrots
as a weapon after dropping his gun while attempting to hold up a
convenience store pleaded guilty to armed robbery.
   Charles A. Foggie didn't get any money after he and an accomplice
hit store owner Clyde Hunt on the head with the carrots, prosecutor
Asa Skinner said Monday. Before fleeing, they did take the pistol
Hunt had used to try to defend himself, making the armed robbery
charge possible, Skinner said.
   Jeffery Ennels, 22, is scheduled for trial later this year on an
armed robbery count in the Oct. 31 holdup.
   Ennels and Foggie, 26, are soldiers stationed at nearby Fort Polk.
   Hunt easily identified Foggie as his assailant, according to
Skinner.
   ``He had known him a long time and said he was a regular
customer. And they had no disguises,'' Skinner added.
   Judge Ted Broyles set an April 20 sentencing date for Foggie.
</TEXT>
