<HEAD>Suspect Being Questioned in Three Slayings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st and last grafs to CORRECT that women was close family
friend not relative.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT GIBSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suspect was questioned Monday in the
butcher-knife deaths and sexual assaults of an elderly woman and her
daughter, and in the strangulation two weeks ago of a friend of the
victims.
   A 28-year-old man was taken into custody Sunday night but had not
been charged, Claiborne County Sheriff Frank Davis said Monday. He
said the suspect was not related to the victims.
   The bodies of Mary Bell Simmons, 88, and her daughter, Georgia
Mae Thomas, 58, were found in the bedroom of Simmons' home Sunday by
another daughter of Simmons. Both women appeared to have been
sexually assaulted and stabbed in the chest with a butcher knife
found near the bed.
   Authorities believe the women had been dead about one hour before
they were found.
   Davis said bloodhounds led authorities to an area near the
suspect's home, several blocks from where the bodies of Simmons and
Thomas were found.
   Davis said he believes the Sunday homicides are related to the
death of a close friend of the women's family, Bertha Peterson, 47,
who was strangled, beaten and sexually assaulted in her home across
town Jan. 29.
</TEXT>
