<FIRST>r w PM-CentralAmericaReport     02-14 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central America Report,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Region Needs $10 Billion over 5 Years to Restore Growth, Panel Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Central American nations need $2 billion
annually over the next five years as part of a strategy to restore
economic growth in the region after a decade of war, an independent
commission says.
   The report, released Monday by the International Commission for
Central American Recovery and Development, said at least $850
million should be earmarked during the first three years on such
urgent needs as caring for refugees and displaced persons.
   It said more than 160,000 Central Americans _ mostly Nicaraguans,
Salvadorans and Guatemalans _ have died over the past decade and
violence has uprooted between 2 million and 3 million others.
   ``Central America is caught in a vicious cycle in which war
thwarts development and the lack of development fuels war,'' said
Sonia Picado of Costa Rica, commission co-chairman, in a statement.
``The challenge is for the world to invest as generously in peace
and development in Central America as it has in supporting our armed
forces.''
   The 47 commission members from 20 countries in North and South
America, Europe and Asia recommended:
   _A $500 million increase to $2 billion annually in external
financial aid over the next five years to help Central America
achieve and sustain growth of 5.5 percent.
   _Full international support for peace and democracy as envisioned
in the Central American peace plan signed by the region's five
presidents in 1987. Military aid to rebel forces in the region
should be suspended.
   _Nations complying with the peace agreement should not be denied
financial or trade benefits because of ideology.
   _Outside aid to finance the revival of the Central American
Common Market and the creation of other regional institutions.
   _Unilateral trade concessions, lower tariffs and higher quotas on
Central American exports for at least a decade.
   _Measures to ease the region's debt burden.
   The commission, funded by private donations, was co-chaired by
Arthur Levitt Jr., chairman and chief executive officer of the
American Stock Exchange, and Ms. Picado, executive director of the
Inter-American Institute of Human Rights.
   Sen. Terry Sanford, D-N.C., had proposed formation of the
commission two years ago.
   Copies of the report were delivered Monday to Central America's
five presidents, who were meeting in El Salvador in a renewed effort
to achieve a peaceful settlement of area conflicts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
