<FIRST>r w PM-Kemp     02-14 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kemp,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Visits Atlanta, Has Dinner with Coretta King</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Kemp was taking his first close-up look at
urban America today as secretary of Housing and Urban Development
with a side trip to a civil rights shrine and a promise to bring
``new life and new hope'' into inner cities.
   The former professional football player has been on the job for
more than a week, but he was formally sworn in Monday at a ceremony
presided over by President Bush.
   Kemp was beginning a two-day tour of Atlanta, visiting housing
projects, renewal programs, interim housing for the homeless, and
privately financed developments aimed at low- and moderate-income
families.
   Andrew Young, Atlanta's black, Democratic mayor, invited Kemp and
was leading his tour today.
   Kemp also planned to tour the Martin Luther King Jr. Center in
Atlanta, across the street from the slain civil rights leader's
grave, and to dine privately with King's widow, Coretta Scott King.
   Kemp recalled King's ``audacious faith'' in the future when he
accepted the appointment as secretary last month. He quoted King
again Monday in the ceremony before HUD employees in Washington,
saying the top concern at the department will be for public housing
residents, the poor and homeless, and struggling home buyers.
   ``Our job is to give them what Dr. King called a stake in the
American dream, a helping hand, and the equality of opportunity to
build a better future for themselves and their children,'' Kemp said.
   ``Our mission is to inject oxygen and seed corn and new life and
new hope into those distressed inner cities,'' Kemp said. ``This is
a compassionate society, and we will be compassionate at HUD.''
   Bush made the first visit by a president to the HUD building
since Jimmy Carter a dozen years ago. The president watched as his
former rival for the Republican presidential nomination was
administered the oath of office by Justice Sandra Day O'Connor.
   ``Jack's a man of ideas, and I've made clear I want him to apply
his creativity and energy to the area of housing and urban policy,
which are one of the most important and challenging issues in
America today,'' Bush said.
   Bush said his administration will push for urban enterprise
zones, using tax incentives to encourage job-creating business in
inner cities, and look for ways to improve public housing and make
home ownership available to tenants.
   ``I believe that given a chance, economic freedom can bring a
revival to the inner city, and it can create jobs and housing and
dignity for every citizen,'' Bush said.
   The references to football were frequent as Kemp invited a pair
of friends to join him for the ceremony _ Washington Redskins coach
Joe Gibbs, and Gene Upshaw, president of the National Football
League Players Association. Kemp was head of the players union in
the old AFL.
   Gibbs brought a football and tossed it to Kemp, who tossed it to
Bush as hundreds of HUD workers watched. There were no
incompletions, but the passes hardly covered one yard.
   Kemp, thanking Bush for his remarks, said, ``I particularly liked
the part, Mr. President, about a kinder, gentler quarterback.''
</TEXT>
