<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 0128EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TreasuryBills     02-14 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Short-Term T-Bills Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed in the latest auction, with rates on six-month
bills climbing to the highest level in nearly four years.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills
Monday at an average discount rate of 8.49 percent, down from 8.57
percent last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 8.54 percent, up from 8.53 percent
last week.
   The rates for six-month bills were the highest since April 8,
1985, when they averaged 8.56 percent. The rates for three-month
bills were the lowest since they averaged 8.33 percent on Jan. 30.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.80 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,785.40 and 9.05 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,568.30.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages rose to 9.15 percent
last week, up from 9.05 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
