<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     02-14 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Fly II' and `Three Fugitives' Lead Box Office Derby</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Fly II,'' a slimy sequel about the son of
mutated mad scientist Seth Brundle, swept into the No. 1 box office
spot ahead of the bank robbery farce ``Three Fugitives.''
   In its first weekend, ``The Fly II'' took in $6.8 million,
compared with $5.1 million for ``Three Fugitives,'' an oddball
comedy starring Nick Nolte and Martin Short.
   ``Rain Man,'' coupling Dustin Hoffman and Tom Cruise as an
unlikely brother duo, was in third place with $4.5 million. The film
has earned $102.2 million in nine weeks of release and is expected
to capture several Oscar nominations on Wednesday.
   The pairing of Bette Midler and Barbara Hershey in ``Beaches''
took fourth place with $3.7 million and Tom Selleck's ``Her Alibi''
was No. 5 with a $3.4 million take.
   ``Cousins,'' with ``Cheers'' TV star Ted Danson and Isabella
Rossellini, debuted in sixth with a $3 million gross even though it
was showing on only one-third the number of screens showing ``The
Fly II.''
   Another sibling picture, ``Twins,'' with Arnold Schwarzenegger
and Danny DeVito as brothers separated at birth, was seventh at $2.9
million.
   In eighth was ``Who's Harry Crumb?'' in ninth was ``Tap'' and
rounding out the Top 10 was ``Working Girl,'' another favorite for
Oscar contention.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``The Fly II,'' 20th Century Fox, $6.8 million, 1,524 screens,
$4,430 per screen, $6.8 million, one week.
   2. ``Three Fugitives,'' Disney, $5.1 million, 1,374 screens,
$3,709 per screen, $20.1 million, three weeks.
   3. ``Rain Man,'' United Artists, $4.5 million, 1,573 screens,
$2,886 per screen, $102.2 million, nine weeks.
   4. ``Beaches,'' Disney, $3.7 million, 1,122 screens, $3,304 per
screen, $30.9 million, eight weeks.
   5. ``Her Alibi,'' Warner Bros., $3.4 million, 1,429 screens,
$2,409 per screen, $9.7 million, two weeks.
   6. ``Cousins,'' Paramount, $3.0 million, 535 screens, $5,681 per
screen, $3.0 million, one week.
   7. ``Twins,'' Universal, $2.9 million, 1,512 screens, $1,895 per
screen, $94.4 million, 10 weeks.
   8. ``Who's Harry Crumb?'' Tri-Star, $2.3 million, 1,198 screens,
$1,932 per screen, $7.0 million, two weeks.
   9. ``Tap,'' Tri-Star, $2.2 million, 585 screens, $3,790 per
screen, $2.2 million, one week.
   10. ``Working Girl,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.1 million, 1,100
screens, $1,918 per screen, $44.5 million, eight weeks.
