<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     02-14 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official: No Negotiations on Marcos Return Until U.S. Charges Resolved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippine justice secretary today
ruled out any talks on the return of Ferdinand Marcos until the
ailing former president resolves criminal charges pending against
him in the United States.
   Marcos, in exile in Hawaii since he was ousted in a February 1986
popular uprising, has asked to be allowed to come home ``to die.''
President Corazon Aquino has refused to allow the return, citing
national security concerns.
   The deposed president and his wife, Imelda, were indicted in
October on federal racketeering charges for allegedly embezzling
more than $100 million from the Philippine treasury, funneling much
of it to foreign bank accounts and using it to buy prime New York
City real estate.
   Because of his ill health, Marcos has not been arraigned. In
January, he was admitted to a hospital in Honolulu for respiratory
ailments.
   Marcos, 71, was reported in guarded condition Monday in the
intensive care unit of Honolulu's St. Francis Medical Center.
   ``It is difficult to talk about the return of Marcos while he
faces criminal charges in the United States,'' Justice Secretary
Sedfrey Ordonez said in a television interview. ``In case he is
absolved, then we can talk about the issue of his coming home.''
   ``If the decision of the American court is that Marcos is not
guilty, then that's the time to discuss if he can really come
back,'' Ordonez said.
   Last week, Mateo Caparas, chairman of the Presidential Commission
on Good Government, confirmed that he met ``supposed
representatives'' of Marcos in the United States but said he ended
the talks after learning they were not authorized to speak for the
deposed leader.
   Caparas' commission is trying to recover up to $10 billion that
Mrs. Aquino's government claims Marcos plundered during his 20-year
rule. Marcos faces 39 civil suits in Manila but no criminal charges
have been filed.
   Ordonez said criminal charges would automatically be dropped if
the ailing Marcos were to die, but that the government can still sue
the estate.
</TEXT>
