<HEAD>Fire At Naval Station Injures Five</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with fire controlled, details of
injuries. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `Three people...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEONARDO, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire on a barge late Monday night at the
Naval Weapons Station Earle injured five men, one seriously, before
it was brought under control early Tuesday, officials said.
   The five civilians were on ``a jack-up rig,'' used to probe the
bottom of Raritan Bay, said Gary Potterfield, a spokesman for the
weapons handling station. ``They jumped off the barge _ one of them
was injured seriously,'' he said.
   It remained unclear how the fire started on the barge, which
officials said measured 40 feet by 80 feet and was about 100 yards
off a pier.
   The blaze was controlled early Tuesday and everybody was
accounted for, Navy spokesman Scott Kalbach said.
   The five injured men worked for the Hans Padron surveying
company, Kalbach said, though he did not know where the company is
based or how it could be reached for comment.
   The Coast Guard was alerted at 10:50 p.m. and the fire was
brought under control before 12:30 a.m., said spokesman Jeff
Nickerson. He said the Coast Guard dispatched five vessels to fight
the blaze.
   ``The Navy is fighting the fire from the pier and the Coast Guard
from the water side,'' he said. ``Everyone in the water was
recovered and accounted for.''
   The Riverview Medical Center was treating one man for burns over
30 to 40 percent of his body, said Araxy Moosa, a night supervisor
at the Red Bank hospital.
   Three people were taken to Bayshore Community Hospital in
Holmdel, said nursing supervisor Martha Krieger. She said they were
brought in around midnight and she did not know their condition nor
their injuries.
   Winter said he believed victims may have been taken to Monmouth
Medical Center, but a nursing supervisor there would not give out
any information.
   About 700 civilians and about 400 military people work at the
base, which is used to load and unload weapons, Potterfield said.
</TEXT>
