<FIRST>r a PM-NewspaperClosed     02-14 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspaper Closed,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duquesne Student Leaders Shut Down Campus Paper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Duquesne University's campus newspaper has been
shut down by the student government in a dispute reportedly
resulting from a birth control advertisement.
   The decision was made because of ``serious concerns'' unrelated
to the Duke's editorial content, said Happy Meltzer, president of
the Roman Catholic school's student government.
   But an attorney for the paper, Joel A. Klein, said, ``As far as
we know it is over the ad. It's a form of censorship. But it's more
than censorship. I see it as the latest attempt to gain control of
the student newspaper, so it is no longer an independent voice of
the students.''
   Editors recently refused Meltzer's request to pull an ad by
Family Planning Services regarding confidential contraceptive
counseling. Meltzer said Monday the ad was inappropriate because it
conflicted with the mission of the Roman Catholic college.
   The Student Government Association appropriates funds to various
student organizations. This year, it gave $10,000 to the Duke, which
also generates money through advertising.
   In 1984, the university administration suspended the Duke because
of an April Fool's Day parody that included references to sexual
acts and sex organs.
   ``Student government really got on the bandwagon then trying to
repress the paper,'' Klein said. ``It's been simmering ever since.
They're using the ad as a pretext to go after the paper on the
larger issue of control, part of which is its independent checking
account.''
   Ann Rago, a Duquesne spokeswoman, said the university has nothing
to do with the controversy because it is a conflict among students.
</TEXT>
