<FIRST>r i PM-NicaraguanCanal     02-14 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaraguan Canal,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Group To Visit Managua To Study Building Canal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese construction industry officials and
academics will visit Nicaragua next month to study prospects for
building a canal linking the Atlantic and Pacific oceans,
Nicaragua's envoy to Tokyo said today.
   From 10 to 12 builders will go to Nicaragua, including
representatives of several major construction firms who are ``very
much interested in the project,'' Jorge Huezo, the Nicaraguan
ambassador to Japan, told reporters during a briefing at the embassy.
   Huezo declined to identify the Japanese firms, but said they were
among the four or five companies involved in a feasibility study. He
said about 20 university professors have also expressed interest in
the study.
   Finance Minister William Hupper of Nicaragua announced Friday
that ountry planned to build a canal and welcomed the
``collaboration of any and all'' governments, institutions and
private companies.
   Hupper estimated that the feasibility study would take about
three years to complete and that construction of canal would require
10 more years.
   On Monday, an official of Japan's Foreign Ministry said private
Japanese firms have been holding talks with the leftist Sandinista
government.
   He said, however, that the Japanese government will ``not
consider participation in the Nicaraguan canal project on a
governmental level'' because it is working with the United States
and Panama on a project to construct a second Panama canal.
   Under an agreement signed in 1985, the three countries will
complete studies on alternatives to the Panama Canal by September
1990.
   At the turn of the century, Nicaragua was considered as a
possible canal site, but Panama was finally chosen. The United
States has a lease on the Panama Canal until 1999.
</TEXT>
