<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Winds     02-14 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Winds,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane-Force Winds Lash Northern England, Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane-force winds that lashed
northern Britain and Northern Ireland damaged homes and blocked
roads with overturned trucks and uprooted trees, police reported.
   In some of the strongest turbulence since a hurricane swept
southern England on Oct. 16, 1987, causing the deaths of 17 people,
the winds Monday night gusted up to 99 mph.
   There were no reports of deaths from the high winds, and workmen
began clearing up the damage as they subsided early today.
   In the northern English city of Manchester, the winds damaged
part of a soccer stadium and the roofs of dozens of homes,
Manchester police reported.
   Overturned trucks blocked the M1, one of Britain's main highways,
for several hours near the city of Wakefield in northern England.
   In the hilly Lake District of northwest England, fallen trees
blocked roads, parts of the town of Barrow and the village of
Glenridding were flooded, and trucks were blown over on the M6 and
A66 freeways.
   In northeast England, police stopped large trucks and other
high-sided vehicles crossing the world's longest cable suspension
bridge over the Humber estuary for several hours because of the
danger of them being blown off.
   The main span of the bridge measures 4,626 feet.
   In Scotland, the strong winds disrupted ferry services.
   In Northern Ireland, police said several homes and other
buildings were damaged by gales.
   Meteorologists at the Malin Head weather station at the northern
tip of Ireland said they recorded gusts of up to 99 mph.
</TEXT>
