<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     02-14 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Head Downward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen in Tokyo
Tuesday because of concern over possible interest rate hikes, while
the stock market edged downward in mixed trading, dealers said.
   The dollar ended the day's trading at 127.20 yen, down 1.10 yen
from Monday's closing of 128.30 yen. It opened at 127.68 yen and
ranged between 127.00 and 127.82 yen during the day.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which declined 146.67 points Monday, fell a slight
2.43 points or less than 0.01 percent, closing at 31,982.98.
   Dealers said the U.S. currency eased in Tokyo following a similar
decline Monday in New York, where it closed at 128.08 yen, down from
Friday's finish of 128.68 yen.
   ``Many market players are taking a cautious position'' regarding
dollar transactions, said a dealer with the Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo.
   The trend will likely continue until Friday's release of U.S.
merchandise trade figures for December, he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
