<FIRST>u a AM-EcclesiaTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0671 02-14 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecclesia Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0671,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Go On Trial in Beating Death of 8-Year-Old</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS one graf after 9th graf, `The four ...' to UPDATE with
one juror questioned, potential jurors given questionnaire; picks up 10th
graf, `Defense attorneys ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began Monday in the trial
of four members of the Ecclesia Athletic Association accused of
beating to death the 8-year-old daughter of the group's leader.
   The three men and one woman are charged with manslaughter in the
Oct. 13 death of Dayna Broussard, daughter of Eldridge Broussard Jr.
   Broussard founded the religious-athletic camp at a rural house
southeast of Portland. He also ran the Watts Christian Center in Los
Angeles.
   Prosecutors say they plan to present evidence that Dayna was
struck hundreds of times, slammed against a wall and floor, and hung
out a window on the night she died.
   Defense attorneys have not disclosed what their arguments will
consist of.
   Fifty-three other children at the camp were taken into state
custody after Dayna's death, and authorities said many of them were
subjected to ritualistic whippings with a paddle or electrical cord
while the others were forced to watch.
   The children were removed from a sparsely furnished farmhouse
after Ecclesia members delivered Dayna's body to a fire station.
   Broussard, 35, denied that the children were beaten or abused,
saying they were only spanked. He was in Los Angeles at the time of
his daughter's death and was not charged.
   The four defendants are Willie K. Chambers, 35, Brian J. Brinson,
30, Frederick P. Doolittle, 38, and Constance Z. Jackson, 37.
   Only one prospective juror was questioned Monday and he will be
asked to return Tuesday when the process resumes. Potential jurors
were asked to respond to a 12-page questionnaire asking if they are
prejudiced against any religious beliefs or have any philosophy
regarding physical discipline of children, among other things.
   Defense attorneys wanted to interview some of the children, but
the Oregon Supreme Court last week rejected their requests to speak
with the youths. The state's high court gave no explanation for its
ruling, saying only that details would be released later.
   The Supreme Court ruling could cause problems for the defense,
particularly since the prosecution plans to use 10 of the children
as witnesses, attorneys said Monday.
   ``In 25 years of law practice ... I have never started a trial
when I have been prevented from interviewing the witnesses,'' said
Ron Thom, who represents Brinson.
   Broussard announced last month that he was leaving for a 40-day
spiritual retreat and would be unavailable until March 12.
   Defense attorneys said Monday they knew Broussard would be gone
and they don't expect his absence to affect their case.
   Attorneys say they expect the trial to last about six weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
