<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 0323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Paraguay     02-14 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paraguay,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition: Gov't Should Delay Election To Allow More Campaigning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders have threatened to
boycott scheduled May 1 elections if the new military government
does not postpone the balloting to give them time to organize.
   Early elections ``do not allow the serious participation of our
parties on the basis of equality of opportunities without any
discrimination,'' said an opposition petition filed with the
government Monday.
   The petition also calls for creation of an independent panel to
reform electoral law.
   Gen. Andres Rodriguez called the election shortly after he ousted
Gen. Alfredo Stroessner in a bloody Feb. 3 coup, ending nearly 35
years of authoritarian rule. Rodriguez is the presidential candidate
of the ruling Colorado Party, which has ruled Paraguay since 1947.
   The two-page petition stops short of suggesting an election
schedule, though opposition leaders have said they need at least six
months and perhaps as much as two years to prepare.
   ``If all of our conditions are rejected, it would be impossible
to participate even if we wanted to because none of us are on voter
registration lists,'' said Domingo Laino of the Authentic Radical
Liberal Party.
   Laino said he expected a reply within one week.
   The May 1 election date is based on a constitutional clause
calling for elections within three months of the resignation,
disability or death of a president.
   Laino, Paraguay's most popular opposition leader, and leaders of
the Revolutionary Febrerista and Christian Democrat parties argue
that since Stroessner was deposed by coup, that clause does not
apply.
   Laino was exiled under Stroessner and his party banned, along
with the Christian Democrats.
   Opposition leaders say they need time to register their voters
and campaign to have any chance to unseat the rich, well-entrenched
Colorado Party.
   The provisional government has indicated that voter lists might
be updated before the election but so far has not said unequivocally
that it would do so, and if so, how or when.
   An unofficial U.S. delegation led by Robert White, who was U.S.
ambassador to Paraguay under the Carter administration, left
Asuncion Monday after meeting with opposition leaders and members of
the provisional government.
   ``I think we're going to see in Paraguay one group that honestly
wants democracy, and another group that would prefer the status quo
continued in one way or another _ Stroessnerism without
Stroessner,'' White said.
   Said former Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt: ``I think not only for
the United States but for all the international community the
question that will be most frequently asked is, will there be real
electoral and institutional reforms before the elections.''
   U.S. Ambassador Timothy Towell met for more than an hour Monday
with Rodriguez. Afterwards, Towell told reporters, ``We will work
together to achieve these goals: democracy and the respect for
international norms of human rights.''
   At least 50 troops were reported killed in the coup, which sent
Stroessner into Brazilian exile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
