<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 0328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-14 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen today
following rumors that the United States wants a cheaper dollar to
help cut its trade deficit, traders said, and stock prices dipped
slightly.
   The dollar closed at 127.20 yen, down 1.10 yen from Monday's
close of 128.30 yen. It opened at 127.68 yen and traded in a range
of 127.00-127.82 yen.
   Japanese press reports that an unidentified U.S. Senate Banking
Committee member had said the dollar should fall to 120 yen to
improve U.S. trade figures prompted a wave of panic selling early in
the day, said Kaneo Ogino, a trader at Goldman Sachs.
   ``There was a panic as bankers sold dollars to protect their
positions,'' Ogino said.
   Later reports quoting unidentified sources in the committee as
denying the comments failed to relieve bearish sentiment in the
Tokyo market, he said.
   Traders said the currency market also was mired in confusion over
the possibility of U.S. or European interest rate hikes.
   ``Many market players are taking a cautious position'' toward the
dollar that probably will continue until Friday's release of U.S.
merchandise trade figures for December, said a dealer with the
Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 146.67-point loser Monday, fell 2.43 points, or
less than 0.01 percent, closing at 31,982.98.
   Stock price movements were mixed due to uncertainty over
developments in the so-called Recruit scandal, traders said. On
Monday, prosecutors arrested four people, including Hiromasa Ezoe,
founder of information services conglomerate Recruit Co., on
suspicion of having given or received bribes.
   Ezoe allegedly sold tens of thousands of unlisted shares of
Recruit Cosmos, a real estate subsidiary of Recruit, at bargain
prices to politicians, their aides, business leaders and other
select people. The purchasers profited when over-the-counter trading
in the Recruit Cosmos shares began and prices skyrocketed.
   The scandal has rocked the government of Prime Minister Noboru
Takeshita.
</TEXT>
