<FIRST>r a PM-TransplantSweethearts     02-14 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transplant Sweethearts,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transplant Sweethearts Engaged On National TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who became sweethearts
through heart transplants will share their engagement with millions
tonight on national television.
   Don Homrich, 28, used a moving billboard in New York's Times
Square to propose to Terri Nelson on Sunday _ to the glare of
television cameras for Fox Broadcasting Co.'s ``A Current Affair.''
   ``We're hoping that by letting everyone in on this it will help
other people with heart disease,'' said Homrich, 28. ``Some feel
that life's over and we hope that through this it'll give people
hope about the future.''
   The couple, who were featured on the show last month, had agreed
to let camera crews in on their short trip to New York for a
follow-up story. But Nelson, 30, said the proposal was a complete
surprise.
   ``All of a sudden I looked up and saw the sign that said,
``Terri, will you marry me?' When I got over the shock I said
`yes','' Nelson said in a telephone interview Monday.
   The couple met in 1987 after Nelson's heart transplant. Homrich,
who received a new heart in 1984, called Nelson to encourage her to
come to a local organ donor support group.
   Both suffered from cardiomyopathy, a degenerative heart condition
that enlarges, overworks and weakens the organ.
   The couple have not yet set a date for the wedding.
</TEXT>
