<FIRST>r a PM-ColombianJudge     02-14 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombian Judge,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Defends Report On Colombian Jurist's Whereabouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who fled Colombia after receiving death
threats from leaders of a major drug cartel has become Detroit's
worst-kept secret in the three days since a newspaper disclosed she
was living here.
   An executive with The Detroit News, which first reported on
Sunday that Consuelo Sanchez-Duran had been relocated here, said the
public's right to know outweighed any potential threat to the judge.
   Sanchez's cover was blown further in today's editions of the
Detroit Free Press. The newspaper said she has worked under her own
name as Colombia's consul general in the Detroit suburb of
Southfield since October, shortly after she and her husband Augusto
arrived in Detroit.
   The Free Press also identified her current residence by name.
   The News on Monday identified the Southfield apartment complex
where Sanchez originally stayed but did not specifically identify
the Detroit residence to which she was moved last week.
   Sanchez fled Colombia after issuing a murder charge against Pablo
Escobar Gaviria. According to the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration, Escobar heads the Medellin cartel, blamed for
smuggling most of the cocaine that reaches the United States.
   Escobar has not been tried. Law enforcement officials who
requested anonymity say he has offered a $1 million murder contract
for Sanchez. Members of the cartel are suspected of carrying out
dozens of killings in Latin America and the United States.
   A letter from the Medellin cartel published in August in
Colombian newspapers threatened Sanchez if she signed the arrest
warrant.
   ``We are capable of executing you anywhere on this planet,'' the
letter said. ``There is no place you can hide.''
   The U.S. State Department declined to comment on whether Sanchez
would be relocated in the wake of the reports.
   Frank Matthews, director of security awareness for the Bureau of
Diplomatic Security, also said he could not comment on whether
action would be taken against tne News' sources, which it said were
some of the 70 local off-duty police officers hired to guard Sanchez.
   A spokeswoman at the Colombian embassy in Washington who declined
identification had no comment Monday on the News' reports or whether
that nation's government would ask that Sanchez be relocated.
   Roberto Castro, vice consul of the Colombian consulate in
Southfield, told the Free Press that Sanchez went to work Monday but
was not allowed to discuss anything except consulate business.
   Robert Giles, executive editor of the News, defended the
newspaper's reports.
   ``You balance whatever the presumed risk to the judge against
whether the community needs to know about this ... and there was no
question'' to run the story, he said.
   In reporting on Sanchez's current whereabouts, Giles said: ``We
recognized that many of the people in the current Detroit location
already knew she was there.''
   The newspaper's case was stated more bluntly by columnist Pete
Waldmeir, under whose byline both the Sunday and Monday reports were
published.
   ``I figure that if I can find out where she is by making two or
three phone calls, somebody with a million-dollar incentive sure ...
can,'' Waldmeir wrote in reference to the bounty reportedly offered
by Escobar.
   Sanchez ordered Escobar and 15 others arrested and charged with
murder in the Dec. 17, 1987 slaying of Guillermo Cano, owner of the
Bogota daily newspaper El Espectador.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
