<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 0530EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     02-14 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shops Close In Sinhalese Heartland After Death Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many shops in Colombo and southern Sri
Lanka did not open today after Sinhalese extremists issued death
threats and called a two-day strike in an effort to disrupt
Wednesday's parliamentary election.
   ``I didn't want to take a risk,'' said a Colombo grocer who kept
his shop shuttered after leaflets appeared in the capital on Monday
threatening death to anyone who ignored the strike.
   In Anuradhapura, 100 miles northeast of Colombo, police shot and
killed at least four Sinhalese extremists and arrested 11 others who
tried to set fire to buses, military officials said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   They identified the dead men as members of the People's
Liberation Front, the ultra-nationalist Sinhalese group whose name
appeared on the death-threat leaflets.
   In Colombo, the few big department stores remained open, but
small shops _ whose owners faced the greatest personal losses and
threats _ generally heeded the strike call.
   Residents of the Sinhalese heartland east and south of the
capital said business was at a standstill in their towns. All those
who spoke asked not to be identified out of fear for their safety.
   Contacted by telephone, they said shops were closed in a string
of coastal towns and villages stretching from Colombo to Moratuwa
down to Galle on the southwest tip of the island and east to
Tangalle.
   Many privately owned buses stopped running, while
government-operated ones stayed on the roads.
   The government has blamed the People's Liberation Front for the
slayings of more than 800 people since the election campaign started
Jan. 6.
   Another 200 people also died in election-related violence blamed
on minority Tamil separatists and unknown elements.
   The victims have included 14 of the 1,396 people running for the
225 parliament seats.
   The front says their fellow Sinhalese who dominate the government
and military have made too many concessions to the Tamil minority.
   Tamil guerrillas, whose separatist campaign has claimed 8,500
lives since 1983, say there haven't been enough concessions.
   The Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of the
Indian Ocean island country's 16 million people.
   Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhists, account for 75 percent.
There also are small communities of Moslems, who claim descent from
Arab traders, and Christians whose ancestors included Dutch and
Portuguese colonists.
</TEXT>
