<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-14 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain, Thunderstorms Over Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms drenched sections of the South and
Midwest today, causing major floods and forcing people from their
homes, as snow or freezing rain fell in the West and Northeast.
   The heaviest of the storms that began Monday along the lower Ohio
and middle Mississippi valleys was in Kentucky, where up to 7 inches
of rain fell. Lousiville got 2.13 inches of rain, breaking the
record for the date of 2.12 inches set in 1874.
   Homes near Shepherdsville, Ky., about 30 miles south of
Louisville, were evacuated late Monday, and highways in surrounding
Bullitt and adjacent Nelson counties were closed by high water.
Motorists were urged not to try to cross water-covered roads.
   Flash flood watches were in effect across the state today, as
well as in Illinois, Indiana, Ohio and West Virginia.
   In Texarkana, Ark., high water in low-lying areas trapped several
people in their homes Monday night and washed a car off a road.
   Nearly 3\ inches of rain fell in Evansville, Ind., in 24 hours,
flooding downtown streets. In southeast Illinois, many secondary
roads were covered with water.
   Showers and thunderstorms also fell today in western Tennessee,
eastern Texas and western Pennsylvania.
   Freezing rain fell in the Lehigh and Susquehanna valleys of
Pennsylvania and in New York.
   Scattered snow fell across New England, the eastern slopes of the
Colorado Rockies, southeast Wyoming, the Nebraska Panhandle and
southwest Montana.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
eastern Texas to the lower Mississippi Valley, southern Missouri,
the Ohio Valley, the central Appalachians and the middle and
northern Atlantic Coast; and snow in northern Maine, the northern
and central Rockies and the western sections of the northern and
central Plains.
   Highs were expected to be in the teens from western Montana and
Wyoming to North Dakota and northern Minnesota; the 20s and 30s from
the central Rockies to the central Plains, South Dakota, southern
Minnesota, the middle Mississippi Valley, and the upper Great Lakes;
the 60s in extreme Southern California and southwest Arizona; the
60s and 70s from southwest Texas to the lower Mississippi Valley,
the Tennessee Valley, the Gulf Coast and the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast; the 80s in south central Texas and the Florida
peninsula; and the 40s and 50s in the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 4
degrees below zero at International Falls, Minn., to 75 degrees at
Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 62 partly cloudy; Boston 39 rain; Charleston, S.C.
62 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 40 drizzle; Cleveland 39 rain; Detroit
36 foggy; Miami 72 fair; New York 46 rain; Philadelphia 44 rain;
Pittsburgh 45 rain; Portland, Maine 34 snow; Washington 37 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 17 cloudy; Chicago 29 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
43 cloudy; Denver 22 snow; Des Moines 16 fair; Indianapolis 34
cloudy; Kansas City 25 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 8 partly cloudy;
Nashville 61 thunderstorms; New Orleans 68 foggy; St. Louis 33 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 26 partly cloudy; Anchorage 21 foggy; Las
Vegas 35 fair; Los Angeles 43 fair; Phoenix 48 fair; Salt Lake City
20 snow; San Diego 47 fair; San Francisco 44 fair; Seattle 31 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 32 snow; Toronto 36 cloudy.
 
</TEXT>
