<FIRST>r a PM-SupportSuit     02-14 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Support Suit,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Welcomes Child Support Suit Filed Against Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Attorney General Jim Mattox said he
welcomed a lawsuit accusing his office of being lax in enforcing
child support laws, a problem he blames on the Legislature.
   ``The lawsuit raises many of the same issues that we have raised
over the past several years,'' Mattox said Monday after the
class-action suit was filed in Dallas by the Association for
Children for Enforcement of Support.
   ``We have more than 370,000 cases in the system and the
Legislature has given us the money to handle less than half of
them,'' he said in a statement. ``When they give us the money, we'll
do the job.''
   But members of the child advocacy group said Maddox is the one
who should be doing the job already.
   ``After many attempts to get Jim Mattox to follow the law, our
members are still not receiving the service they are entitled to
receive,'' said Lynda Milot Benson, president of the group's Texas
chapter.
   Benson said Mattox is responsible for locating parents,
establishing paternity for children born out of wedlock and
collecting child support.
   ``He doesn't do any of that,'' Benson said. ``The laws are in
place to get help and it's past time that these laws be followed.''
   Steve Levine, a spokesman for Mattox, said the attorney general's
office has asked for $63.4 million in fiscal year 1990 and $62.3
million the next year for the program. That would be an increase
from the current $39.8 million.
</TEXT>
