<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-14 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in early European trading today.
Gold prices rose.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market was weighing the
likelihood of higher U.S. interest rates, which would support the
dollar, against the possibility of a higher U.S. trade deficit.
   Trade figures for December are scheduled to be released on
Friday. The trade gap stood at $11 billion in November.
   ``The market is unsure whether the deficit will contract or
expand,'' said a dealer at a major European bank in Frankfurt.
   Traders in Frankfurt and Milan, Italy, said a hike in the U.S.
prime rate Friday to 11 percent continues to fuel expectations of
further rises in U.S. interest rates.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 1.10 yen to close at 127.20. It was unchanged in
later London trading.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.8617 West German marks, down from 1.8705
   _1.5815 Swiss francs, down from 1.5895
   _6.3325 French francs, down from 6.3650
   _2.1140 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1120
   _1,357.25 Italian lire, down from 1,362.50
   _1.1845 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1868
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7592, more expensive for
buyers than $1.7495 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $385.75 a troy ounce, up
from $384.25 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $385.65.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $385.60, up from $383.75 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.02 to close at a bid $387.66.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.83 a troy ounce,
up from Monday's $5.79.
</TEXT>
