<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Jetson     02-14 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Jetson,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Was George Jetson's Voice Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George O'Hanlon, who became the voice of the
cartoon world's man of the future, George Jetson, after
unsuccessfully auditioning for the role of Fred Flintstone, died
after a stroke. He was 76.
   The actor and writer died Saturday at St. Joseph Medical Center
in suburban Burbank, Hanna-Barbera Productions Inc. announced Monday.
   O'Hanlon had just finished recording his role as George in
``Jetsons: The Movie,'' a full-length cartoon from Universal
Pictures and Hanna-Barbera scheduled for release this fall.
   ``George loved doing the Jetsons. He just sounded great in our
latest sessions,'' Hanna-Barbera President Joe Barbera said in a
statement. ``I know he would feel very proud of his work in the
movie.''
   The film is based on ``The Jetsons,'' the popular 1960s cartoon
situation comedy about a futuristic family.
   ``George Jetson was an average man. He has trouble with his boss,
he has problems with his kids, and so on,'' O'Hanlon once said.
``The only difference is that he lives in the next century.''
   O'Hanlon originally tried out for the Flintstone role, but Alan
Reed got the part. Barbera, looking later for the voice of the
Jetson patriarch, remembered O'Hanlon's audition.
   Although the ``The Jetsons'' only ran from 1962-1963, it
developed a loyal folllowing. In 1985, 41 new episodes were
commissioned for syndication and O'Hanlon became Jetson again.
   O'Hanlon's other credits include the roles of the TV commentator
in ``Rocky'' and William Bendix's next-door neighbor on ``The Life
of Riley.'' He also wrote for the Jackie Gleason Show for two years.
   He is survived by his wife, Nancy; his son, George Jr.; daughter,
Laurie, and one granddaughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
