<FIRST>r a PM-LILCO     02-14 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-LILCO,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlement Appears Near After Judge Clears The Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators for the Long Island Lighting Co. and
its 1 million customers were close today to an agreement under which
ratepayers would drop a racketeering suit in exchange for smaller
rate increases over the next 10 years.
   However, it was uncertain whether the proposed settlement would
include the closing of the controversial Shoreham nuclear power
plant.
   ``We have not reached a settlement but we made excellent
progress,'' said Joseph McDonnell, a LILCO spokesman, late Monday
night after 10{ hours of talks.
   He said negotiators at the federal courthouse in Brooklyn were
``very close'' to an agreement and would meet again this afternoon.
   A federal judge last week dismissed a racketeering lawsuit filed
by Suffolk County against LILCO, but on Monday he granted the
ratepayers the right to sue the utility as a class. That cleared the
way for the ratepayers' attorney, Judith Vladeck, to accept a
settlement.
   The class certification was ``a useful step'' in the negotiation
process, Vladeck said during a break in the talks.
   U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein noted that, should his
dismissal be overturned on appeal, LILCO would be liable to pay the
ratepayers at least $4 billion in damages and ``will be forced into
bankruptcy since its assets will not suffice to pay the judgment.''
   The settlement talks centered on a proposal to reduce planned
increases in electric rates by $400 million over the next decade.
   Weinstein had previously severed the ratepayers' case from the
trial of Suffolk's suit, which ended Dec. 5 with a jury finding that
LILCO lied to state officials to obtain rate increases and awarding
the county $22.8 million in damages.
   Weinstein on Saturday dismissed Suffolk's suit and the jury award
on the grounds that the racketeering statute did not apply to the
case.
   An agreement between LILCO and its customers would lessen the
leverage Suffolk County could wield in its negotiations with LILCO
over whether to appeal Weinstein's ruling.
   The county hoped to use the threat of a bankrupting damage award
to force LILCO to close its $5.4 billion Shoreham nuclear power
plant.
   Lawyers for Suffolk County arrived at the Brooklyn courthouse
late Monday, fueling speculation that an agreement to close the
plant was near.
   The Suffolk County Legislature was scheduled to discuss the
proposed settlement today.
   Any settlement to close the plant would require the approval of
Gov. Mario Cuomo.
   The governor had proposed last year to buy the troubled Shoreham
plant for $1 and dismantle it and allow LILCO a rate increase of 63
percent over 10 years in return. However, state legislators refused
to go along with Cuomo's deal, saying it was too expensive for
consumers and too generous to LILCO.
   Cuomo on Monday issued a statement saying he would require the
rate-saving proposal ``be adopted and that the Legislature would not
impede other portions of the agreement'' for the settlement to win
his approval.
   Construction on Shoreham, located 60 miles east of Manhattan,
began in 1973 and was completed a decade later, but state and county
authorities have refused to draw up emergency evacuation plans that
would help the plant win an operating license from the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission.
</TEXT>
