<FIRST>u a PM-Solomons-Quake     02-14 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Solomons-Quake,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquake Hits Solomon Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake measuring 6.6 on the
Richter scale shook the Solomon Islands in the South Pacific Ocean,
the National Earthquake Information Center reported today.
   Geophysicist Bill Schmieder said there were no reports on damage
or injuries in the hours following the quake at 11:20 p.m. MST
Monday.
   A statement released by the National Earthquake Center said the
quake occurred in the Solomons, about 1300 miles north of Brisbane,
Australia.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight damage
in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage, 6
severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of
tremendous damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
