<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 0935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-WaterCrisis     02-14 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water Crisis,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water Emergency Declared in Philly Suburbs, Hotel Fire May Have Strained
Pump</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIXVILLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials declared a water emergency
early today and urged residents not to turn on their taps after two
water pumps broke and left the borough's 10 million-gallon reservoir
perilously low.
   The emergency affected some 20,000 people in Phoenixville and in
Upper Providence, East Pikeland and Schuylkill townships, all
Philadelphia suburbs, said Borough Manager Bill Herman, who declared
the emergency at 3:15 a.m. after the water level dropped to just a
foot above intake channels.
   A hotel fire early Friday that killed two people and injured 13
others may have led to the emergency, Herman said. One water pump
had burned out a week ago, before the fire, and the second one
burned out Monday morning, probably because of the strain of
fighting the hotel fire.
   More than 200 firefighters from 26 fire companies battled
Friday's blaze at the Wall Block Inn, using up an estimated 5
million to 6 million gallons of water. Officials said at the time
that the water flow was so slow, partly because of freezing weather,
that a nearby canal had to be tapped to battle the blaze.
   Herman said another fire could deplete the reservoir in 15 to 30
minutes and urged people who can still draw water from their taps to
avoid doing so.
   ``If the system is bone dry and we have a fire, obviously there's
some real problems,'' he said.
   A replacement pump was being flown in from Memphis, Tenn., and
was expected to be on line by this afternoon.
   ``It's going to have to work like the devil to get the reservoir
to a point where we're going to feel comfortable,'' Herman said.
   Tanker trucks were set up at three sites today to provide water
to residents and Herman said others were being arranged.
</TEXT>
