<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0451 02-14 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0451,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Says Rebel Proposal Risks Coup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to clarify. Pickup 5th graf pvs `The Farabundo...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COSTA DEL SOL, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte
could provoke a military coup if he accepts a proposal by leftist
guerrillas to postpone next month's presidential election, the
defense minister said.
   ``If the president retains power beyond the end of his term, the
armed forces would be obliged to depose him _ either the armed
forces or the legislative assembly,'' Defense Minister Gen. Carlos
Vides Casanova told reporters Monday.
   Duarte should not extend his term to accommodate the rebel
proposal for elections in September, Vides said at this seaside
resort, where five Central American presidents began a two-day
summit Monday.
   The insurgents issued the proposal on Jan. 24. Duarte said the
following day that he would not remain in power under any
circumstances beyond June 1, when his term ends.
   The Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said it would
participate in the election if the balloting is delayed from March
19 to September and certain security conditions are met.
   The rebels, pitted in a 9-year-old war against the U.S.-backed
government, previously had rejected the five national elections held
this decade as anti-democratic and part of a U.S.-sponsored
counterinsurgency campaign.
   The government has described postponement of the election as
unconstitutional.
   Asked Monday if the elections could be postponed until September,
Vides said, ``They cannot.''
   Asked if acceptance of the plan could divide the armed forces, he
said: ``That danger exists. Then the entire democratic process that
has cost so much could be broken.''
   A broad spectrum of political parties and labor organizations has
said last week that there are constitutional means to postpone the
election _ and the United States has called the rebel proposal a
positive step.
   Duarte's own Christian Democratic Party has said elections could
be legally postponed and an interim president named by the
legislature if a political consensus to do so exists.
   But the rightist Arena party, which is favored to win the
election, and the armed forces continue to cite what they say are
constitutional injunctions against postponing elections.
   ``If the Constitution is violated, we would be serving up on a
silver platter an opportunity that could destroy the entire
democratic process we have worked for,'' said Vides.
   Rebel chiefs may visit San Salvador late this week to talk with
representatives of the country's political parties, who have
expressed a willingness to do so.
   The war has claimed the lives of 65,000 people.
</TEXT>
