<FIRST>r a PM-NYAssembly-Reagan     02-14 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NY Assembly-Reagan,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Assembly Refuses To Honor Reagan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York state's Democrat-controlled Assembly
has rejected, after rancorous debate, a resolution honoring former
President Reagan and his wife, Nancy, for their eight years in the
White House.
   ``He made selfishness the national byword,'' said Democratic
Assemblyman Anthony Genovesi. ``He made it legitimate for people to
say `I don't give a damn, I'm not my brother's keeper.'''
   Genovesi's remarks, which drew hisses from Republicans, echoed
other Democrats who said Reagan's America left out the homeless, the
poor and organized labor.
   ``I'm glad he's no longer president,'' said Assemblyman Edward
Sullivan, also a Democrat. ``I can't commend him for his years in
office.''
   Monday's vote was 78 to 58. Only two Democrats voted for the
resolution.
   The resolution, sponsored by Assembly Minority Leader Clarence
Rappleyea, said ``mere words cannot express the debt owed nor may
brief phrases make manifest the leadership rendered.''
   Assembly Majority Leader James Tallon of Binghamton implored
Rappleyea to water down his resolution.
   Tallon said Democrats wish the Reagans a peaceful retirement,
``but in my opinion and in the opinion of many of my colleagues, a
number of the things that were carried out (in Reagan's
administration) were not great successes in the United States.''
   Republicans derided the Democrats for voting against the
resolution, noting that New York state voters twice supported Reagan
in general elections.
   ``Ronald Reagan was a leader who stuck to his guns, who made us
all feel better and made the country feel good about itself,'' said
Republican Assemblyman John Faso. ``I don't think anyone can
disagree that the health of this nation is much better than when he
took office.''
   ``If there was ever any doubt that the Democrats represent the
liberal fringe, the defeat of this resolution honoring the eight
years of the Reagan administration proves it,'' Rappleyea said.
</TEXT>
