<FIRST>r a PM-TicketSchool     02-14 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ticket School,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Traffic Agents Brush Up On ABC's of Ticket Writing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When a recent study showed that more than 13
percent of traffic tickets were dismissed because they were
illegible or incomplete, transportation officials saw the writing on
the wall:
   Penmanship classes for traffic agents.
   ``I'm not going to be satisfied until we have a perfect record _
10 out of 10 summonses that are processible and collectible,''
Transportation Commissioner Ross Sandler said in today's Daily News.
   Deputy Transportation Commissioner Samuel Schwartz said a recent
study of 1,000 tickets picked at random showed that 13.5 percent
were illegible or key information required on the ticket was
inaccurate or omitted. The city lost $5 million last year when such
tickets were dismissed.
   Traffic enforcement agents, who issued 7 million parking tickets
in 1988, have been attending remedial handwriting classes, and
officials may give the same training to police officers, sanitation
workers and employees in 14 other agencies, who together wrote
another 5 million tickets last year.
   In addition, Mayor Edward I. Koch has ordered the department to
come up with cash bonuses for those who write the fewest invalid
summonses and to find a way to punish those with a high error rate.
   Joseph Bilello, who teaches at the Transportation Department's
training academy, said he focuses on the use of ``pre-kindergarten
block lessons'' in the classroom.
</TEXT>
