<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HitlerPaintings     02-14 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hitler Paintings,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Children Of Hitler's Personal Photographer To Get Art</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Army must return four watercolor
paintings by Adolf Hitler to the children of Hitler's personal
photographer, a man found guilty of war profiteering, a federal
judge has ruled.
   U.S. District Judge Lynn N. Hughes also ordered the federal
government to return two archives containing hundreds of photographs
to the familyof photographer Heinrich Hoffman Sr., who died in 1957.
   Two of the watercolors most likely will be returned to Hoffman's
family in Germany, while the remaining pair will remain in Houston
as part of the collection of Billy F. Price, an art investor who has
been battling the government over their ownership for years.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Frank Conforti said the government has
contended the watercolors legally belong to the United States under
a U.S.-German treaty signed after World War II.
   But Hughes ruled Thursday that the government failed to prove it
had a legal claim on the watercolors or photographs.
   ``Equal justice under law protects people without exceptions for
those people whose father's politics were wrong,'' Hughes said.
   Hitler gave one of the watercolors to Hoffman in 1936 as a 50th
birthday present. Hoffman purchased the others in the 1930s and
early 1940s.
   U.S. forces discovered them in May 1945 in a German castle where
Hoffman had stored them during the war. They were mistakenly
identified as German government property and seized.
   After the war, Hoffman was found guilty at the Nuremberg war
crimes trials of war profiteering.
   Price traced the ownership of the watercolors in 1982. The
photographer's children, Henriette Hoffman Von Schirach and Heinrich
Hoffman Jr., agreed to convey a portion of their value to Price for
help in retrieving them.
   Price said all of Hitler's drawings and paintings should be
studied for clues to his personality and motivation.
   ``He was not a simple man. He was very complicated,'' Price said.
``I'm not going to let people just say Hitler was a monster and
sweep him under the rug. I'm going to pull him out, shake him off
and study this man.''
   Another hearing is scheduled March 14 to discuss damages and
property possession.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
