<FIRST>r a PM-HousingPrices     02-14 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Prices,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Prices Highest in Northeast and West, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Median home prices were highest in New York and
lowest in Cleveland in 1988, according to the 13th annual home
buyers' survey by the Chicago Title and Trust Co.
   Overall, U.S. housing prices were highest in the Northeast and
the far West, and lower in the South and the Midwest, the survey
found.
   Chicago Title and Trust, the nation's leading insurer of property
titles, reported that the median home price in the Northeast last
year was $151,300, while in the West it was $141,400.
   By contrast, the median price in the South was just $88,400, and
the Midwest median price was $93,600.
   New York City was the most expensive individual market, with a
median home price of $192,600, according to the study released last
week.
   John Pfister, Chicago Title vice president and manager of market
research, said that in the more expensive housing markets in the
Northeast and the West Coast, home buyers are generally older and
have higher combined incomes than their counterparts in less
expensive housing markets.
   For all U.S. markets included in the survey, the median price
rose 23 percent last year, from $99,260 to $121,910.
   The study found median home prices were highest in New York,
$192,600; San Francisco, $179,700; Orange County, Calif., $168,100;
Boston $165,100; and Los Angeles $162,500.
   At the low end were: Cleveland, $76,800; Memphis, $77,900;
Orlando, Fla., $83,000 and Seattle-Tacoma, $85,600.
</TEXT>
