<FIRST>r i PM-Ershad-Plane     02-14 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ershad-Plane,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bangladesh Leader Arrives After Reported Plane Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a plane carrying President Hussain
Muhammad Ershad of Bangladesh to his first official visit in Britain
reported suspected hydraulic problems today, but the craft landed
safely.
   Fire engines lined the runway as the Bangladesh Biman DC-10 jet
landed smoothly and taxied to the VIP area.
   The 59-year-old president, looking unconcerned, emerged smiling
in bright winter sunshine.
   Ershad said at a lunch at the Foreign Press Association in London
later today that as his plane, which delivered a month ago, took off
from Dubai, the pilot advised him that the hydraulic system had
developed a problem.
   ``He asked me if we should go back to Dubai or to London. I said
go on to London. God has been very kind, he landed us safely,'' said
Ershad.
   The former army general, who took power in a March 1982 coup,
leads one of the world's poorest countries, a onetime British colony.
   He is scheduled to have lunch with Queen Elizabeth II and hold
talks with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and Foreign Secretary
Sir Geoffrey Howe during his four-day visit.
   Ershad was met at Heathrow Airport by a representative of the
queen, Viscount Long, and Foreign Office Minister Lord Glenarthur.
</TEXT>
