<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-MailHoard     02-14 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mail Hoard,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Mail Carrier Gets 1 Year, 1 Day For Undelivered Mail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former mail carrier whose home was
stacked with tons of undelivered junk mail was sentenced today to a
year and a day in federal prison of failing to deliver two
first-class letters.
   William Ryan, 59, of Milton, told the court that he felt he
couldn't deliver all the mail assigned to him on his rural route and
started leaving a few pieces in his car every day.
   ``Things just seemed to snowball,'' Ryan told U.S. District Judge
Roger Vinson.
   The first-class letters were discovered among nearly 500,000
pieces of mostly advertising brochures, catalogues, sweepstakes
offers, give-aways and other so-called junk mail found heaped in and
around his home last August.
   The mail was found heaped inside Ryan's Florida Panhandle home,
about 30 miles northeast of Pensacola, in a shed, his yard and a
wooded area nearby after postal authorities received a tip.
   The mail dated back three years, about the time that Ryan, a
15-year postal employee, had been working a rural route in Escambia
County out of the main post office in Pensacola.
   Postal inspectors said about 500 pieces of first-class mail were
among the mainly third-class items. Ryan was charged with failing to
deliver 10 first-class letters. Five of those contained tax notices
from the Escambia property appraiser; the other five were
voter-registration renewal cards from the county elections
supervisor.
   Ryan was allowed to plead guilty to two of the counts and, in
exchange, prosecutors dropped the other eight. For the two counts,
he could have received up to 10 years in prison and been fined up to
$500,000.
   The judge also placed Ryan on probation for three years once the
prison sentence is completed. And he ordered him to pay $2,991.94 in
restitution to the Postal Service for the cost of maintenance
personnel, use of a bulldozer, forklift and trucks and other
expenses of recovering, sorting and delivering, returning or
destroying the tons of mail he failed to deliver.
   Vinson also imposed a $100 special assessment, but disallowed
$10,974 in restitution for the salaries of postal supervisory
personnel assigned to the case.
   Assistant Public Defender Tom Keith argued for leniency, saying
Ryan never before had been in trouble with the law, cooperated with
investigators and didn't have the ability to pay a large amount in
restitution or fines because he was fired from his postal service
job after his arrest.
   ``I'm very sorry for what happened,'' the defendant told Vinson.
``It's been a bad year last year for me.''
   Postal authorities say they don't keep records on such things,
but one inspector said the nearly 500,000 pieces may have been the
largest-ever case of undelivered mail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
