<FIRST>r a PM-Bhopal-Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0530 02-14 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bhopal-Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0530,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts: Bhopal Settlement Won't Hurt Union Carbide</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE late-morning price and give payment
date; Picks up 5th graf, `More than ...'; SUBS 10th graf, `Union Carbide
...' to CORRECT to $350 million, sted $300 million; A version also moved
on the financial wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp.'s $470 million
settlement with the Indian government over the 1984 Bhopal gas leak
met with approval today from financial analysts and Wall Street.
   ``Psychologically, it's terrific. Financially, it's reasonable,''
said Leslie Ravitz, a research director for Solomon Brothers Inc. in
New York. ``This relieves the pressure on Union Carbide and the
stigma.''
   Union Carbide's stock price soared $2.12{ to $31.25 a share in
late-morning New York Stock Exchange trading today on news of the
settlement.
   The Supreme Court of India, sitting in New Delhi, today ordered
the $470 million payment by March 31 to settle charges resulting
from the leak of deadly methyl isocyanate at the Bhopal pesticide
plant, which is operated by Union Carbide's Indian subsidiary.
   More than 3,300 people died as a result of the Dec. 2, 1984 leak
_ the world's worst industrial disaster.
   In a statement from the company's Danbury headquarters, Union
Carbide Chairman Robert D. Kennedy said, ``We are pleased that this
will now provide for the care and rehabilitation of the victims and
their families and a fair resolution of all issues.''
   ``The alternative,'' added company spokesman Earl J. Slack, ``is
litigation that probably would have extended into the next century
with the final outcome that would be completely irrelevant to the
interests of the affected people in Bhopal and a continuing drain on
Carbide.''
   Union Carbide said it would take a charge against 1988 earnings
but that it would not exceed 50 cents a share.
   Slack said Union Carbide stands by its contention that sabotage
by a disgruntled employee caused the gas leak. The Indian government
had claimed that the company's negligence led to the disaster.
   Union Carbide had offered to pay $350 million as early as 1986,
but even though that settlement was accepted by the U.S. courts it
was rejected in India.
   The Indian government, which sued the chemical giant for $3
billion, had been seeking about $600 million in a settlement.
   ``I think it's a decision that was pretty much anticipated,''
James Wilbur, a vice president with Smith Barney, Harris Upham and
Co. Inc. in New York, said of the settlement. ``You didn't need a
slide rule to figure out what the settlement would be.''
   Wilbur said Union Carbide has set aside $200 million toward the
settlement and had $250 million in insurance coverage, leaving it at
risk for another $20 million as a result of today's settlement.
   ``The risk is minimal,'' he said.
   Today's settlement comes on the heels of a good year for Union
Carbide. In the year ended Dec. 31, Union Carbide earned $720
million, or $5.31 a share, on revenue of $8.32 billion. That
compared to 1987 earnings of $231 million, or $1.76 a share, on
revenue of $6.91 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
