<DOCNO> AP890214-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Iran-Britain     02-14 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Britain,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Briton Sentenced On Iranian Spying Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Briton jailed in Iran for more than
three years on spying charges has been sentenced, Iran's official
Islamic Republic News Agency said today.
   The report did not specify the penalty against Roger Cooper, 52,
but quoted Iranian Intelligence Minister Mohammad Rey-Shahri as
saying a ``heavy ruling'' had been issued.
   Cooper, a businessman who had worked in Iran for more than 30
years, still faced a final judgment, Rey-Shahri said. He did not
elaborate and it was unclear whether the sentence might be revised.
   Rey-Shahri also announced that 2,600 political prisoners will be
released from Iranian jails, IRNA said in the report monitored in
Nicosia.
   He said Cooper confessed to spying and ``nothing could halt this
case.''
   Cooper worked in key Iranian government agencies since 1958 and
began spying for Britain in 1966, Rey-Shahri said.
   Cooper was arrested in November 1985, and his continued detention
has been a source of tension between Britain and Iran. British
officials have said better relations depended in part on resolution
of the case.
   Rey-Shahri, reiterating comments by Interior Minister Ali Akbar
Mohtashemi, said British statements on the case were ``illegal and
an interference in the country's internal affairs.''
   Britain withdrew all its diplomats from Tehran and only one
Iranian envoy remained in London after a dispute that began when
British police arrested an Iranian envoy on shoplifting charges in
May 1987.
   Iranian Revolutionary Guards then kidnapped and assaulted a
British diplomat.
   Britain reopened its embassy in Tehran Dec. 9.
   Rey-Shahri said the release of political prisoners is part of the
amnesty Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini granted to mark
the 10th anniversary of the Islamic revolution.
   He said 3,500 counterrevolutionaries were held in jail before the
anniversary and that 900 will remain there.
   Amnesty International and other human rights groups say there are
far more political prisoners that the government's figure of 3,500.
   The Iraqi-based Mujahedeen Khalq, the main Iranian opposition
group, says 140,000 people have been arrested on political charges
since 1981.
</TEXT>
