<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0497 02-14 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0497,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Convoy Reaches Kabul as Last Soviets Departing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with Foreign Ministry details on convoys,
fighting, editing to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convoy carrying urgently needed food and fuel to
Kabul arrived in the Afghan capital after breaking through guerrilla
strongholds on the Salang Highway with the help of Afghan soldiers,
Tass said today.
   Vadim Perfilev, a Foreign Ministry spokesman, said the Soviet
troop withdrawal was exactly on schedule and the last Soviet
soldiers would be out of Afghanistan by Wednesday, the deadline set
in a U.N.-mediated agreement.
   ``As of Feb. 15, not a single Soviet soldiers will be on Afghan
territory,'' Perfilev told a news briefing.
   The Soviets entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the
Afghan army fight Moslem insurgents. At the height of the Soviet
involvement, there were an estimated 115,000 Red Army troops in
Afghanistan.
   Since the second stage of Soviet withdrawal began in January,
more than 45,000 soldiers have left Afghanistan, the official news
agency Tass said.
   The last contingent of troops, led by Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov, was
expected to cross the bridge linking the town of Khairaton with the
Soviet city of Termez just before noon Wednesday, the Soviet
newspaper Trud said.
   As the remaining Soviet troops moved northward on the Salang
Highway toward home, a column of Afghan trucks loaded with
Soviet-supplied food and fuel reached Kabul on Monday from the
north, Tass said in a dispatch from Kabul.
   ``The trucks, which broke through the Salang Pass, delivered
wheat, rice, kerosene and petrol to the capital.''
   Perfilev said the first convoy included 150 fuel trucks and that
an additional 300 were on the way to Kabul. The Afghan capital is
ringed by Moslem guerrillas, and is short on supplies of food and
fuel.
   The Afghan news agency Bakhtar also said Afghan forces were able
to clear a passage for the Soviet convoy. An official Afghan report
said the Soviet shipments to Kabul would continue despite the troop
pullout.
   ``Recently, the Kabul-Khairaton road was under constant attack by
rebels from the Ahmad Shah Masud group,'' Tass said. ``The
operations which have been carried out by Afghan army units recently
significantly weakened the Masud militants' activity,'' the news
agency said.
   Soviet aircraft also were bringing supplies to Kabu, Eduard
Kudryavtsev, a Foreign Ministry official, said today. ``Yesterday,
four Soviet planes flew from Tashkent to Kabul with a shipment of 75
tons of supplies,'' he said.
   A U.N. airlift of food to the Afghan capital has been suspended
because transport crews fear for their safety.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
