<DOCNO> AP890214-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-VeteransHospitals     02-14 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Veterans Hospitals,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>DAV Calls for Closer VA-Military Hospital Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Disabled American Veterans today proposed a
closer alliance between hospitals run by the Veterans Administration
and the military services to save money and improve care.
   Some 300 installations in the VA, Army, Navy and Air Force health
systems have made 1,800 local agreements to share facilities under
1982 legislation. This represents ``just the tip of a mammoth,
cost-effective iceberg,'' DAV National Commander Billy E. Kirby told
a joint hearing of the House and Senate Veterans Affairs committees.
   Both the military and the veterans systems ``are in deep
trouble,'' Kirby said.
   ``Years of below-inflation, less-than-current-service budgets,
combined with rising beneficiary demands'' means that beds go
unused, staff quits and ``care is rationed,'' he said.
   VA officials testified last fall they will fall $600 million to
$1 billion short in their medical budget for the current fiscal
year, a little over $10 billion for 172 hospitals and hundreds of
other facilities. The military services spend about $8 billion
operating 130 hospitals in the United States and hundreds of other
facilities around the world, plus $2 billion in paying civilian
doctors and others.
   From the map, ``is it not obvious to all that from the standpoint
of the proximity of VA and military treatment facilities and their
beneficiaries, the two systems enjoy a potential to operate more
efficiently through sharing of resources, mutual support and
integration of planning and operations?'' Kirby said.
   ``Rather than settling for locally initiated ad hoc agreements,
the more ambitious of which often encounter bureaucratic resistance,
we propose the creation of a new nationwide Veterans
Administration-Department of Defense health care alliance,'' he said.
   ``Two huge medical systems which presently go their own way in
purchasing everything from CAT scans to tongue depressors, from
laundry services to public utilities, certainly could benefit from
single-source contracting and common purchases,'' the DAV leader
said.
   Combining the patients of the two systems, the older males of the
VA system with the younger, serving men and women and their
families, should help staff recruiting, he suggested.
</TEXT>
