<DOCNO> AP890214-0083 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Balloonist     02-14 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Balloonist,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Balloonist Embarks On Trans-Pacific Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOKOHAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With winds gently rocking his balloon and
tiny gondola, Fumio Niwa rose into the nighttime sky early Wednesday
on what he hopes will be the first solo balloon flight across the
Pacific.
   Niwa plans to ride high altitude winds across the ocean to North
America in about four days.
   His goal is San Diego, sister city of his home town of Yokohama,
but weather reports said the normally easterly high altitude winds
had veered to the north and were likely to take him toward Alaska.
   ``My long dream of crossing the Pacific is coming true today,''
Niwa said. ``I still wonder if it's really possible. The jetstream
is bending strangely, but America is big, so I think I'll make it _
somewhere.''
   The huge orange and blue balloon has no maneuvering ability, so
its direction depends entirely on the wind.
   Niwa, 38, says he's making the 5,000-mile flight to test the
high-tech helium balloon and enclosed gondola he designed himself.
   The balloonist, who quit his job in a computer company in
November to prepare for the flight, estimates it will cost about
$540,000. He hopes to earn most of that from a future book and
public appearances.
   Niwa has about 1,000 hours of ballooning experience, but most of
that is in hot-air balloons and none outside Japan.
</TEXT>
