<FIRST>u a PM-INSEviction 1stLd-Writethru a0501 02-14 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-INS Eviction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0501,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>INS Moving Amnesty Applicants Out of South Texas Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with INS moving out amnesty applicants
out of Harlingen; Picks up 4th graf, `INS officials ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Immigration and Naturalization
Service will stop processing amnesty applicants in a building which
city officials cloed last week because of health and safety
violations, an INS official said today.
   Armed with bolt cutters and a temporary restraining order, INS
officials on Monday returned to the former furniture store where the
agency processes more than 2,000 political asylum applicants weekly.
   Officials in this small South Texas town have complained that
refugees, most of them from Central America, had left the building
and surrounding area cluttered with litter and human waste.
   INS District Director Omer G. Sewell said today the agency would
no longer process asylum applications in Harlingen and would handle
the south Texas cases at the INS detention center in brushland about
25 miles from town.
   Candidates seeking amnesty under the 1986 immigration reform law
will continue to be served at the Harlingen building, he said.
   ``We want to be good citizens in this community as well,'' Sewell
said.
   The new asylum office will open Wednesday at the agency's Port
Isabel Service Processing Center, a minimum-security facility where
425 undocumented aliens were detained Tuesday pending action such as
deportation.
   INS officials cut through the chains and padlocks on the doors
Monday afternoon after U.S. District Judge Filemon Vela in
Brownsville set aside a 3-day-old state court order evicting the
federal agency. Friday's eviction was ordered after Harlingen
officials sued to shut down the office for fire and health
violations.
   The INS successfully moved the Harlingen lawsuit from state to
federal court Monday and filed its own federal lawsuit against the
city.
   Vela said he set aside the state court order because it
``prohibits the functions and operations of an agency of the federal
government.''
   The judge also barred Harlingen, 25 miles north of Brownsville,
from interfering with INS business but said the agency still must
follow state and local health and fire regulations. He set a hearing
in the case for Feb. 21.
   Harlingen City Manger Gavino Sotelo said the city would comply
with the order, but added, ``The conditions at the center remain the
same as they were before. There is trash; there is human waste. If
this goes on, we might have to close it all over again.''
   Harlingen Mayor Bill Card added, ``If it had been operated in a
responsible way before, it would have never been closed.''
   City officials promised to monitor the office and make regular
inspections.
   Sewell said barring the INS from the 9,852-square-foot building
not only shut down the political asylum process but also made it
impossible to serve legalization candidates under the Immigration
Reform and Control Act of 1986.
   Vela said the state court's restraining order issued Friday
interfered with the INS' compliance with a federal temporary
restraining order he issued Jan. 9. That order mandated the INS to
allow political asylum applicants to pursue their claims to refugee
status at their intended U.S. destinations after checking in with
the INS in Harlingen.
   With the Harlingen office closed, immigrants could not obtain
documents allowing them passage through U.S. Border Patrol
checkpoints to leave southern Texas.
   Hundreds of immigrants in the center's parking lot appeared
puzzled by the legal maneuverings.
   ``We didn't know what was going to happen,'' said Juan Hernandez
from El Salvador. ``We were just told to wait.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
