<FIRST>u a PM-TennFlooding 1stLd-Writethru a0543 02-14 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tenn Flooding, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0543,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heavy Rains Hit Tennessee; One Woman Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lede to clarify that woman killed was not in western
Tennessee; SUBS 4th graf, `Emergency workers ...' to CORRECT that only
55, sted 70 hospital patients evacuated; SUBS penultimate graf with 2 grafs
with further evacuations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains flooded roads in Tennessee
today, closing schools, forcing the evacuation of residents and
hospital patients and killing one woman swept from her car by
rushing water, authorities said.
   More than 3 inches of rain fell between midnight and dawn in
Nashville and surrounding counties. Forecasters said the rain would
continue through tonight.
   About 4 feet of water stood in the Lebanon town square after
Sinking Creek overran its banks, police dispatcher Bob Harrison said.
   Emergency workers evacuated all 55 patients from McFarland-Humana
Hospital in Lebanon, just east of Nashville, after electricity to
the building was shut off, said Glenna Hunt of the Wilson County
Civil Defense agency.
   The power was disconnected after heavy rain seeped inside
transformers outside the building, she said. Patients were taken to
surrounding hospitals in DeKalb and Davidson counties.
   A woman who ignored police warnings not to cross flooded state
Highway 231 in Lebanon became stuck amid the flood waters about 7
a.m., Wilson County sheriff Terry Ashe said. She tried to get out of
her car, was swept away and drowned.
   Rush-hour traffic became snarled as water built up on highways
leading into Nashville.
   ``The major problems are centered around Interstate 40 east near
Lebanon, and parts of Interstate 24,'' said Highway Patrol
dispatcher Melody Land. ``There's a lot of water in the road,
several stalled cars.''
   Water was reported in some first-floor apartments in Nashville
and a mudslide was reported in the Bellevue area in western Davidson
County.
   In Jackson, two families were evacuated from their homes near
Cane Creek. Flash flood watches were issued for the western
two-thirds of Tennessee.
   At least 64 other people left their homes because of rising
water, said Danny Newton, chief of operations for the Tennessee
Emergency Management Agency.
   ``We have some low-lying areas with creeks in them and they built
close to them; and it normally floods when we get a rain,'' Newton
said. ``Most everybody is used to this and does it on their own
without reporting it to anybody.''
   Public schools were closed in Wilson County because of the threat
of flooding, but schools in the metropolitan Nashville area remained
open, authorities said.
</TEXT>
