<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1309EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BennettFinances     02-14 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett Finances,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bennett, Nominee for Drug Czar, Struck It Rich Outside Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William J. Bennett, President Bush's nominee to
become drug czar, struck it rich on the lecture circuit after
resigning as education secretary last September, picking up $15,000
to $20,000 per speech.
   ``I had a good few months in the private sector, the best three
to four months I ever had,'' Bennett said. ``I was told it would
have been a very good year for me.''
   If the Senate confirms Bush's nomination of Bennett to become
director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy, Bennett will
be paid $99,500 a year.
   Bennett ``turned down $1.5 million in lectures in 1989'' when
Bush nominated him last month, according to a lecture-circuit
industry source who requested anonymity.
   Bennett reported having a savings account worth less than $1,001
on Sept. 20 when he resigned as education secretary.
   Bennett and his wife, Elayne, who are expecting a second child,
live with their 5-year-old son, John, in a rented home in nearby
Montgomery County, Md. He says that ``we can't buy a house where we
want to live on these salaries.''
   During the past few months, Bennett was earning $15,000 to
$20,000 per speech for a total of ``about $150,000 to $200,000,
which was just getting his feet wet,'' said Don Walker, president of
the New York-based Harry Walker Agency, which got 30 percent of the
fees.
   ``Well, we had a good Christmas,'' Bennett said, reflecting on
the likelihood that he'll be taking home a lot less this year _ his
government salary.
   His earnings during the past few months should be reflected in
the latest financial disclosure form he submitted to the White House
counsel's office. But the form has not yet been made public. Such
forms give only ranges, not exact figures.
   According to Bennett's most recent publicly released form,
covering 1988 up to Sept. 20, indicates in addition to the savings
account that Bennett and his wife had checking accounts of less than
$1,001 apiece, a retirement annuity worth $50,001 to $100,000, an
undisclosed salary for his wife from Georgetown University funded by
a foundation based there, and a brokerage account worth $1,001 to
$5,000.
   That brokerage account is with the San Francisco office of Bear
Stearns &amp; Co., the same office that handled many lucrative one-day
trades for now-indicted W. Franklyn Chinn, who was managing money
for former Attorney General Edwin Meese III when Meese and Bennett
were in Reagan's Cabinet.
   ``Oh God, no!'' Bennett said when asked whether he knew of the
connection between that office and Chinn, who is awaiting trial on
racketeering charges in the Wedtech defense contracting scandal. ``I
didn't know that.''
   Bennett said his account was in that office because his broker,
Reed Freyermuth, is a college friend.
   Bennett's financial disclosure forms for the past few years
reveal that he had 18 one-day or two-day stock trades handled by
that office, including three involving stocks traded the same day by
Chinn for Meese.
   Bear Stearns had an underwriting position in all three of those
new issues of stock, making it likely that many of the firm's
customers would have been guided toward them.
   Trade in British Airways stock on Feb. 11, 1987, earned Bennett
$101 to $1,000, while Meese got $12,571. Microsoft Inc. stock deals
on March 13, 1986, earned Bennett another $101 to $1,000, while
Meese got $1,550, and trading in Morgan Stanley Co. on March 21,
1986, earned Bennett $1,001 to $2,500 while Meese received $1,322.
The information on Meese was provided by his attorneys to the
independent counsel investigating the then-attorney general.
   Bennett, who got on the phone to answer questions about his
finances just a few minutes after an aide was asked about the
one-day trades and Chinn, said Freyermuth handled it all.
   ``I am an idiot about this stuff,'' Bennett said. ``I gave him
the enormous sums you're looking at and said, `Do what you can.'''
   Freyermuth said that although there were ``no major killings,
unfortunately,'' his friend of almost 30 years came out all right
financially.
   ``Every one of those trades was profitable, and I always charged
him the bare bones, most minimum commissions,'' he said.
   While out of office, Bennett became president of The Madison
Center, a policy group he created with $500,000 in start-up funds
from The Lynde and Harry Bradley Foundation of Milwaukee.
   Bennett also signed a contract with Simon and Schuster to write
two books, but he'll only have time to complete one if he gets the
drug director job, said his attorney, Bob Barnett of Williams &amp;
Connolly. Barnett would not reveal the contract's value.
</TEXT>
