<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Britain-Plane     02-14 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Britain-Plane,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Lands Safely With One Engine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A warning light prompted the pilot of a British
Airways Boeing 757 jetliner with 40 people aboard to turn off an
engine, but the plane landed safely using its other engine, the
airline said Tuesday.
   A small temperature rise in the right-hand engine turned on the
fire-warning light during Monday's flight, the airline said. As a
result, the pilot shut down the engine as the plane approached
London's Heathrow Airport.
   Flight 391 from Brussels landed safely, powered only by the
left-hand engine, the spokeswoman said.
   Engineers found no incorrect wiring or other faults in the
right-hand engine, the spokeswoman said. She said the cause of the
temperature increase was unknown.
   Authorities ordered a check of wiring in several types of
aircraft after a Boeing 737 crashed last month in central England
and killed 47 people. The crash, whose cause in still under
investigation, led to speculation that a warning light could have
led the pilot to unnecessarily shut off an engine.
</TEXT>
