<FIRST>r w AM-BarbaraBush     02-14 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Visits Nursing Home on Valentine's Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Barbara Bush paid a Valentine's Day
visit Tuesday to a nursing home, left a handmade valentine for each
patient and said that President Bush is ``a good man and he won't
let you down.''
   The residents of the nursing home for the elderly and terminally
ill gave her a giant poster-board valentine: ``To Mrs. Bush. Always
the first lady in our hearts.''
   Leaving a signed, handmade valentine for each patient, she told a
group of them who gathered to chat with her: ``That really means I
love you all.''
   Mrs. Bush is a board member at the non-profit Washington Home and
was a volunteer there while Bush was in Congress in the 1960s.
   Sitting with a group of elderly patients in a sunlit room while
reporters and board members looked on, Mrs. Bush answered questions
about her new life in the White House.
   Asked how she liked being first lady, she replied: ``I'm not
really sure I am the first lady of the land but I love being married
to the president.
   ``I love my house, and I love my life so I feel pretty good.''
   On what she hoped to accomplish, she mentioned her efforts to
improve literacy in the country and said she would soon set up a
foundation to promote that cause. She said it would focus on
literacy in the family because parents ``aren't parenting as much
any more as they might be or should be.''
   She also mentioned another goal: ``I hope I'll make people care
more about one another. I think that's very important.''
   On another favorite subject, her family, Mrs. Bush said she would
be going to Denver this week to visit a new grandchild, Ashley, who
was born last week to Neil and Sharon Bush.
   When one man wished success for the president, Mrs. Bush replied:
   ``I appreciate that and remember, his success is yours and my
success, too. ... He's a good man and he won't let you down.''
   Mrs. Bush also commented on her recent visit to Ottawa for her
husband's first foreign trip as president.
   She mentioned visiting a school with Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney's wife, Mila, whom she called ``a very young, beautiful
good friend.''
   She enjoyed the trip, she said, ``but more important, I think the
two husbands really had a chance to talk.''
   Mrs. Bush raved about living in the White House and said she
likes the way it was decorated by Nancy Reagan, so she will not be
making major changes except to redo Franklin Pierce's old office to
be Bush's office.
   Mrs. Bush noted that she is remotely related to Pierce, who was
president in 1853-57.
   ``It's the most beautiful house you could possibly believe,'' she
said. ``It's filled with beautiful paintings, lovely furniture and
bright sunshine. If you couldn't be happy in the White House, you
just couldn't be happy anyplace.''
   She greeted about two dozen patients individually.
   Oe elderly man, Nathan Scott, wanted to show her two letters he
said he had received from Bush last year. One, dated Oct. 31,
thanked him for donating to Bush's campaign fund. The other, from
July, thanked him for a donation helping to retire the debt of one
of Bush's rivals for the Republican nomination, Sen. Bob Dole of
Kansas.
   Mrs. Bush glanced at the letters and quipped, ``He wrote you and
asked you for money? You ought to scold him.''
</TEXT>
