bouquet.
   The prince received the flowers with more dipolmacy than a gift
presented him later in the day. When 80-year-old sculptor Sam
Tonkiss gave Charles a bust, he thanked him and asked: ``By the way,
who is it of?''
   ``It's your wife, sir,'' Tonkiss said. The artist later told
reporters, ``It was a little embarrassing, but I think he was quite
pleased.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arthur Ashe says young blacks entering the sports
world today will not face the blatant discrimination he endured
during his two-decade tennis career. But he says there are still
subtle pressures.
   ``You're going to feel sociologically out of place,'' he said.
``You're going to go through culture shock. You'll be around people
whose behavioral norms are unlike anything you've experienced in a
black neighborhood.''
   The 45-year-old retired tennis star was in Atlanta for a sporting
goods show last week and to promote his new book, ``A Hard Road To
Glory: A History of the African-American Athlete.''
</TEXT>
