<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan-Kabul 2ndLd-Writethru a0546 02-14 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Kabul, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0546,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last Soviet Soldiers Leave Kabul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs ``Reporters watched..'' to clarify.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last Red Army soldiers climbed
aboard giant miitary transport planes and flew home tonight, a
Soviet officer said, leaving Afghan armed forces to defend the
embattled capital alone for the first time in nine years.
   Just hours before the Soviets departed, Moslem guerrillas fired
five rockets into Kabul, killing four children and an adult, and
hitting Kabul airport, according to official reports.
   Reporters watched as at least 80 Soviet soldiers boarded giant
Il-76 planes. Earlier, it had been thought only about 40 Soviet
troops remained in Kabul the day before the Wednesday deadline set
under a U.N.-sponsored agreement for the withdrawal of the Red Army.
   Lt. Col. Pytor Sardarchuk declined to say exactly how many troops
were leaving. ``All those who are left'' were going, he said.
   Then he turned to reporters watching the final departure, shook
their hands and said ``goodbye.''
   Earlier, Moslem guerrillas launched their first attack in more
than a month on Kabul airport, the capital's key link with the
outside world.
   The rockets came crashing down near a runway, but no one was
injured, Soviet soldiers said after the attack.
   They were stationed at the airport, guarding military transports
delivering food and other supplies to the besieged capital.
   Radio Kabul said one of the rockets exploded in a bazaar where
dozens of people were lining up to buy bread. The blast killed four
children and an old man, it said.
   Moscow sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to support
the Marxist government's battle against Moslem guerrillas. At one
point, the Kremlin had an estimated 115,00 troops in Afghanistan.
   Besides the small contingent of soldiers who flew out tonight,
several thousand Red Army troops were approaching the Soviet border,
Soviet diplomats said. They spoke on condition of anonymity.
   With the Soviet departure over, Kabul was generally quiet. There
were few rockets whizzing back and forth, and the markets were
crowded.
   However, residents said letters, unsigned and delivered the past
few nights, warn people to stay off the streets starting Wednesday.
Many residents believed the letters came from the guerrilla forces
bearing down on the city.
   The letters have prompted worry that attacks will resume after
the Soviets leave.
   Written in the local Dari language, the letters warn residents to
stay off the streets, close their shops, and keep away from the
airport.
   Some foreign diplomats suggested the letters might be the work of
Khadd, the Najib government's secret police.
   A U.N. airlift of food to Kabul, where food and fuel are in short
supply, has been suspended because transport crews fear for their
safety.
   Guerrilla attacks and heavy show have delayed Soviet convoys
carrying food, fuel and other supplies into the capital. There have
been long lines at bakeries and gasoline stations in Kabul.
   One Soviet convoy arrived overnight after traveling down the
Salang Highway into the city of more than 2 million.
   The Soviet Union also has been airlifting up to 600 tons of flour
and other goods to Kabul in an effort to help ease shortages. But
the supplies are handed out to government workers and members of the
ruling party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
