<SECOND>AM-Stolen Baby,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Thief Takes Sleeping Tot, Drops Her At Gas Station; 13-Year-old
Accused</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PINELLAS PARK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old swiped a car and sped
off with a baby sleeping on the back seat, then dumped the infant on
the pavement 65 miles away, police said.
   The 15-month-old girl suffered a broken ankle and bruises on her
face.
   The teen-ager was arrested in Orlando around midnight Monday,
authorities said Tuesday.
   Investigators say the teen-ager, not identified because of his
age, apparently didn't realize little Ashley Barksdale was in the
car. The boy was a runaway from a nearby state facility.
   ``So far we have a charge of auto theft; but there might be
additional charges,'' said Lee Lerchen, police spokesman.
   Witnesses told police the baby was roughly pulled from the car
when she was dropped at a gas station, and probably suffered the
injuries then, Lerchen said.
   ``You look good; dirty, but good,'' the child's mother, Nellie
Barksdale, 34, of Davenport, whispered at the Polk City service
station when she got her baby back. ``I just wanted my baby back. I
don't care about the car. I got what I wanted back.''
   Mrs. Barksdale's car was taken while she was in a shop with her
sister, Alice Rico, looking for Valentine's Day gifts, Lerchen said.
   Mrs. Barksdale's 16-year-old daughter, Sarah, stayed in the car
to listen to the radio, but then joined her mother and aunt.
