<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Baker-BankStock 3rdLd-Writethru   02-14 0942</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Bank Stock, 3rd Ld-Writethru,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker to Sell Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files a0588-a0591-a0595-a0597-a0550; inserts new
material and deletes redundant material throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III announced today
that he is selling his controversial holdings in a New York bank and
all other publicly traded stocks that have been held in a blind
trust.
   Baker announced the decision through a spokeswoman while on a
tour of Western European capitals.
   His wife Susan is disposing of her stock as well. The trust, set
up when Baker went to work at the White House in 1981 as former
President Reagan's chief of staff, also will sell publicly traded
stock held by their daughter, Mary Bonner Baker.
   ``While I believe this decision goes well beyond what is required
or has been recommended, I think it is the correct decision for
someone committed in meeting the highest ethical standards,''
Baker's statement said.
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Baker made the decision in
London on Saturday after consulting with his lawyers.
   The Washington Post, in a front-page article on Friday, said
White House counsel C. Boyden Gray had pressed Baker to divest
himself of substantial stock holdings in Chemical New York Corp., a
bank holding company that has $4.5 billion in loans to Third World
nations.
   On Friday, while r said he never sought the
waiver and decided instead to get rid of all his publicly owned
stock in the bank and other firms.
   Baker's latest financial disclosure form, filed with the Office
of Government Ethics, puts a value of more than $250,000 on the
assets held in the secretary's qualified blind trust.
   The form shows that the secretary received ``over $100,000'' in
income from the trust during the time that was covered, January
through August of 1988.
   Baker left the Treasury Department last summer help then-Vice
President Bush's campaign for the Oval Office.
   The disclosure form also lists the separate property of Mrs.
Baker, which includes 1,087 shares in Houston Industries, with a
valuation between $15,001 and $50,000.
   The stock listed assets of daughter Mary as including 5,310
shares of Chemical New York Corp., 196 shares of Exxon Corp. with a
value listed between $5,001 and $15,000; 144 share of Houston
Industries with a value listed between $1,001 and $5,000; and 330
shares in Trinity Petroleum Trust, with a value listed between
$5,001 and $15,000.
   The spokeswoman said State Department lawyers had offered Baker a
number of other options, which were not disclosed, but that Baker's
decision went further than any of them. She said the sales will be
completed after details are worked out.
   Baker's portfolio was not disclosed apart from Chemical New York
Corp., in which he acquired holdings after Chemical Bank took over
Texas Commerce Bancshares of Houston, a bank his grandfather helped
found, during Baker's tenure as treasury secretary.
   Baker, who had held news conferences daily since setting out on
his trip last Friday, did not meet with reporters traveling on his
Air Force jet today as he made his way from Bonn, West Germany, to
Ankara, Turkey, then to Athens, Greece, and finally to Rome. A
planned meeting here with Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti was
canceled because the Italian official was ill.
   A U.S. official said Baker received a list of recommended options
while flying to Ankara on Tuesday morning, but Baker ``basically
decided'' to sell his holdings on Saturday.
   The details of divestiture are complicated and must be worked out
with Baker's trustees, said the official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Asked if Baker stood to lose money by selling, the official said,
``I've never asked and I've never heard him mention it.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters in
Washington earlier today that the decision on Baker's stocks
``doesn't require a presidential review. The matter is being worked
out. There will not be a conflict of interest.''
   Fitzwater commented in response to a story in The Washington Post
today that members of two Senate committees were unaware that Baker
held large amounts of bank stock during the process of his
confirmation as treasury secretary four years ago.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman, asked about the
Post report, said, ``You know what the state of play is from the
secretary's own description most recently in Ottawa.'' He said he
had no information on whether Baker had decided to sell the stocks
or seek a waiver.
   While in office, Baker's holdings were in a qualified blind
trust. A trustee was in control of the stocks, but Baker was
informed annually of the general nature of the holdings.
   As treasury secretary, Baker developed the so-called Baker plan,
which called on Third World nations to make good on their debts as
they restructured their sagging economies. It also called for new
public and private lending, and did not seek to force the banks to
forgive the loans.
   The Post said it could reach spokesman for only two other members
of the two committees, John Heinz, R-Pa., and John C. Danforth,
R-Mo. It quoted both senators as saying through their spokesmen that
Baker's bank holdings would have made no difference on his
confirmation as Treasury secretary has they known about them.
   Although Baker had provided information to the Senate Finance
Committee in 1985 as an attachment to letter promising to recuse
himself from any decisions affecting his holdings, the information
was not circulated to the panel's members, the newspaper quoted
congressional aides and senators as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
