<SECOND>AM-Missing Student,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Desperate Father Recruits Marino to Help Find Missing Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The desperate father of a university
student missing since she went for a walk last week is hoping Miami
Dolphin quarterback Don Marino and other NFL players can help find
his daughter.
   Marino promised at a news conference Tuesday to call on his
friends throughout the National Football League to get information
about Tiffany Sessions, 20, to the public.
   A toll-free number has been set up for information about the
disappearance and flyers with the young woman's photo were being
distributed nationally. Officials said several hundred phone calls
had come in already in response to efforts of the woman's father
since her disappearance Thursday.
   The father of the University of Florida student is Patrick
Sessions, president of the Weston division of Arvida, a national
real estate company based in Boca Raton.
   ``I'm not going to apologize that I have a lot of friends,''
Sessions said Tuesday. ``This is not a money effort, but a friend
effort.''
   ``We're more and more convinced there is a possibility that
Tiffany is out of the state,'' said Sessions. ``We haven't found
anything in Gainesville to indicate she is still there.''
   Also at the press conference was John Walsh, who has become a
spokesman for parents of missing children since the disappearance of
his 6-year-old son Adam from a Hollywood shopping mall in 1981. The
boy's severed head was found in a canal near Vero Beach about two
weeks later.
   ``We're trying to take the search for Tiffany national,'' said
Walsh, who added that many children have been found simply because
their picture was made available nationally.
   Miss Sessions was last seen Feb. 9 by her roommate before taking
an evening walk near her apartment in Gainesville. She had taken the
same walking route almost every evening for six months.
</TEXT>
