<HEAD>Danish Squatters Fight Police With Stones</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Squatters occupying a former army
barracks in Copenhagen battled hundreds of police who moved in
Tuesday to close illegal bars and restaurants.
   Five of about 250 policemen involved in the operation were
injured, and three people were detained, according to Danish public
radio. It said the police fought about 150 residents.
   Witnesses said the squatters at Christiania squatter town threw
stones and other objects at the police in a bid to prevent
authorities from removing liquor and furniture from 13 unlicensed
bars.
   Police were forced to retreat under a hail of stones at one point
and regroup, the witnesses said.
   Christiania has been occupied since 1971 by squatters, who
proclaimed it a ``free city'' and refused to pay taxes. About 500
people usually live there at this time of year.
   It was the first time police had entered the area in force.
