<DOCNO> AP890214-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1618EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Crime 1stLd-Writethru a0599 02-14 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crime, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0599,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Lift Lid on Crime Statistics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to make verb ``printing'' sted ``hearing.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of printing official complaints about
rampant lawlessness in the West, a Soviet newspaper on Tuesday
published what it called shocking statistics showing a dramatic rise
in crime.
   The government daily Izvestia, publishing the kind of figures
that have been secret since 1933, said the overall rate of
registered crimes rose 3.8 percent last year and that the rate of
all crimes soared 17.8 percent.
   ``Probably the figures published in the newspaper would shock
many,'' Izvestia said. ``But it's better to know the true state of
affairs so that our safety _ and the police's concerns and problems
_ will become clear.''
   Some of the figures were released last month, but Tuesday's
report was the most detailed yet.
   The report, quoting the Interior Ministry, said 1,867,223 crimes
were registered last year, 68,700 more than in 1987. The country's
population is about 285 million.
   On the last page of Izvestia was a table that listed among the
most shocking statistics the number of premeditated murders. They
soared 14.1 percent, from 14,651 in 1987 to 16,710 last year.
   The higest increase among different categories of crimes was
registered in break-ins and holdups, which rose 44.4 percent, from
46,485 in 1987 to 67,114 last year. In 1988, 17,658 rapes were
reported, a rise of 5.3 percent over the 1987 level of 16,765.
   Some progress was reported in tackling economic crime. Izvestia
said there were 96,986 cases of misappropriation of government and
public property through embezzlement, theft and abuse of office in
1987. The number fell 9.8 percent in 1988, to 87,450.
   Economic crime is so widespread in the Soviet Union that many
Soviets believe a ``second economy'' that is based on a black market
is thriving.
   Interior Ministry official M. Yegorov told the Tass news agency
that speculators have been taking advantage of the shortages that
plague Soviet society. Twenty years ago, he said, only 17,000 cases
of speculation were reported. Izvestia said there were 45,235 of
speculation last year.
   Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin told the Communist Party
newspaper Pravda last month that President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reforms have let loose not only more democracy but also thieves and
attackers.
   Under Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness, officials and
the state-run media have detailed drug abuse, prostitution, murders
and other crimes. The Kremlin's long-running attempt to blame such
problems on the West and to claim that they had not crossed Soviet
borders has been largely abandoned. The media often has painted a
picture of the United States as a country where it was unsafe to
walk on the streets at night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Saudi-US     02-14 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Saudi-US,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ambassador to Saudi Arabia Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. ambassador to Saudi Arabia,
Walter L. Cutler, has sent his resignation to Washington after six
months in the post, well-informed sources said Tuesday.
   Cutler, 57, arrived in August for his second posting in the
kingdom, replacing ambassador Hume Horan.
   The sources said on condition of anonymity that Cutler will leave
in late March. He will take over in April as head of Meridian House,
a nonprofit Washington-based group that deals with international
educational exchanges, according to Joseph John Jova, the current
head of Meridian House.
   Other sources said Cutler was prepared to assume duties at
Meridian House last year when he was asked by President Reagan to go
to Saudi Arabia. He went there with the understanding that his stay
in Riyadh would be brief, they said.
   No reason for Horan's abrupt departure last year was disclosed at
the time, but sources later said King Fahd asked the ambassador to
leave. They said Fahd was angry because Horan officially complained
to him about the kingdom's purchase of Chinese ballistic missiles,
an issue that the Riyadh government regards as an internal affair.
   Israel had complained that the deployment of such projectiles in
an Arab country could endanger its security.
   Cutler, a career diplomat since 1957, previously had served in
Saudi Arabia for three years, ending in July 1987. He also has
served as ambassador to Tunisia and Zaire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
