<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     02-14 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge to Hear Corruption Charges Against Ousted Leader's Aides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has agreed to try three former
ministers and the private secretary of deposed President Alfredo
Stroessner on charges of corruption, officials said Tuesday.
   The accusations stem from a lawsuit filed last week by Pedro
Abilio Rolon, an attorney with no known connection to the new
government.
   His suit calls for investigation of ``ill-gotten goods''
allegedly accumulated by the four defendants, including ``sumptuous
apartments on foreign beaches, luxurious mansions built on expensive
property ... planes, yachts and luxury cars.''
   In his complaint, Rolon alleged the four made fortures by
overcharging public works, selling Paraguayan identity papers and
state property for personal gain, extorting money from private
businesses, and other graft.
   A formal order for the arrest of the four was issued Monday by
criminal court judge Eladio Duarte Carballo. No date was announced
for the trial.
   Two of the accused _ former Health Minister Adan Godoy Jimenez
and private secretary Mario Abdo Benitez _ have been in custody
since shortly after the Feb. 3 coup that toppled Stroessner and
boosted Gen. Andres Rodriguez to power.
   Also named in the suit is former Interior Minister Sabino Augusto
Montanaro, who has taken shelter at the Honduras Embassy in
Asuncion; and former Labor and Justice Minister Jose Eugenio
Jacquet, who is believed to be out of the country.
</TEXT>
