<HEAD>Afghans Protest U.S. Decision on Aid to Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Miagol is correct; the envoy uses only one name</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Afghan government has sent a note to the
State Department protesting President Bush's decision to continue
providing aid to anti-communist rebels so long as the Soviet-backed
government remains in power, an Afghan diplomat said Tuesday.
   ``We think that this decision will just bring more bloodshed and
more war to our country,'' said the top Afghan envoy in Washington,
Miagol, in an interview with Associated Press Radio.
   ``We asked for the administration of Bush to change this decision
for peaceful solution of our conflict,'' said Miagol, who does not
use a second name. The envoy said that all involved ``in the Afghan
conflict have to sit down and they have to negotiate this matter.''
   Transport planes carried the last Soviet soldiers home from Kabul
on Tuesday, a day ahead of the deadline the Soviets agreed to last
spring for ending their military involvement in Afghanistan.
   The departure of the Soviets raised doubts about the ability of
the Afghan government to survive the challenge posed by the
U.S.-backed guerrillas.
   Bush decided last week to continue aiding the rebels even after
the Soviets completed their withdrawal, partly because of the large
amounts of military hardware the Soviets left behind.
</TEXT>
