<FIRST>r i AM-PLO-US     02-14 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO-US,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Meets With U.S. Congressman on Human Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat met with Rep. Wayne
Owens, D-Utah, to discuss human rights and other issues in the
Israeli-occupied territories, congressional and Palestinian sources
said Tuesday.
   Owens, temporary chairman of the human rights subcommittee of the
House Foreign Affairs Committee, and Arafat discussed peace efforts,
ways of establishing communications among all parties, and human
rights violations in a meeting Monday that lasted more than four
hours, the reports said.
   Art Kingdom, a spokesman in Owens' office in Washington, said the
congressman talked to Arafat about the concerns of members of
Congress regarding policies and actions of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   He said Owens told Arafat that relations between the U.S. and the
PLO depend on how such concerns are addressed.
   Their meeting was also reported by the official Palestinian news
agency WAFA.
   Owens plans to make another trip to Tunisia in March and may meet
with Arafat again, his office said.
   In its annual report on human rights practices around the world
issued last week, the U.S. State Department said Israel's response
to the Palestinian uprising led to a substantial increase in
human-rights violations in the territories last year.
   The U.S. ambassador to Tunisia, Robert Pelletreau, is the
officially designated U.S. contact with the PLO, which makes its
headquarters in Tunis.
</TEXT>
