<FIRST>r a AM-ArchbishopSchulte     02-14 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Archbishop Schulte,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bishop Schulte Becomes 12th Archbishop Of New Orleans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Francis Bible Schulte on Tuesday became the
12th archbishop of New Orleans, the nation's second-oldest Roman
Catholic archdiocese.
   ``Who are the defenseless, the vulnerable?'' Schulte asked in a
homily prepared for the occasion. ``The most vulnerable of all are
those babies who are about to be aborted and gasping for life with
the final silent scream; the battered, abused and addicted women and
men; the unemployed, all too numerous in our state today; the gunned
down and the blown-up.
   ``Who are the vulnerable? All of us who live a fragile peace
under the threat of nuclear destruction, while we know that there
can be no true peace without justice.''
   Seventy-five bishops and archbishops attended the installation of
Schulte in the St. Louis Cathedral in the French Quarter. Prayers
were offered in French, English and Spanish.
   Schulte's homily was rich with praise for his predecessor, Philip
Hannan, who retired at age 75 after 24 years as head of the
archdiocese. He noted Hannan's work on behalf of the poor and his
dedication to Catholic schools, and he called Hannan ``a model of
religious dedication and civic responsibility.''
   Archbishop Pio Laghi, the Vatican's ambassador or pro-nuncio to
the United States, installed Schulte.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer was among state and local officials attending
the ceremony. Also attending were five American cardinals: John Krol
of Philadelphia, John O'Connor of New York, James Hickey of
Washington, Bernard Law of Boston and Edmund Szoka of Detroit.
   Schulte, 61, a native of Philadelphia, has been bishop of the
Wheeling-Charleston diocese in West Virginia since 1985. As
archbishop he will serve the Archdiocese of New Orleans as well as
six other Louisiana dioceses, all of which have a total of 1.4
million Roman Catholics. The oldest Roman Catholic Archdiocese is
that of Baltimore.
   He was named to succeed Hannan in December, after Hannan reached
the mandatory retirement age of 75 in May.
</TEXT>
