<FIRST>r a AM-Firefighters-Drugs     02-14 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Firefighters-Drugs,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minneapolis Fire Department Has Drug Problem, Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Fire Department has a ``significant
problem with chemical use and abuse'' and some firefighters have
reportedly battled blazes while under the influence of drugs, the
fire chief said.
   At least 20 of the city's 450 firefighters are using cocaine and
30 others are alcoholics, Fire Chief Tom Dickenson said Monday. His
remarks were prompted by the weekend arrest of a veteran firefighter
on cocaine charges.
   The chief said his figures are based on experiences with
disciplinary actions and complaints he's had from firefighters, as
well as the arrested man's statements to police. He added that he
had also heard reports of firefighters fighting fires while under
the influence.
   The president of the firefighters' union and a city drug
dependency coordinator said they don't believe there is a major drug
problem in the department. However, neither had any estimate of how
many cocaine users there were.
   Minneapolis Firefighters Union President Dick Will said Monday he
didn't know the source of Dickinson's chemical abuse figures and
that the union was unaware of firefighters under the influence while
on the job. He blamed the city for failing to develop an acceptable
drug policy.
   Dickinson said the city has been unable to negotiate a
drug-testing policy with the union that would allow testing when
there are ``reasonable suspicions.''
   ``We are not against a reasonable form of drug testing,'' said
Will. ``And we certainly don't condone anyone showing up for work
under the influence of any controlled substance.''
   He said the city is unwilling to define ``reasonable suspicion.''
   Ken Voltin, an alcohol and drug dependency coordinator for the
city, said it would be hard to determine if there are 20 cocaine
users in the department. ``I don't believe there is a major cocaine
problem,'' he said.
   A 45-year-old firefighter was arrested Friday on a felony charge
of selling 2.2 grams of cocaine for $40 to an undercover St. Paul
police officer in a bar.
   ``We have information that there are other firefighters that are
involved in drugs,'' said Sgt. Phil Van Tassel, administrative
assistant to Minneapolis Police Chief John Laux.
   Dickinson said the arrested firefighter told police lots of
firefighters used cocaine. Asked if there were more than 20, the
firefighter said yes, the chief said. Van Tassel confirmed the
remarks.
   Twenty cocaine users would represent a conservative figure, said
Dickinson.
   Steven Fredrickson, an assistant city attorney, said Minneapolis
has reached agreement with about 12 unions on the drug testing
issue, but not with firefighters.
   ``We have taken the position that the testing should be based on
reasonable suspicion of drug usage,'' said Fredrickson. ``The union
has asked that it be based on probable cause, which is a higher
standard.''
</TEXT>
