<HEAD>Playwright to be Tried Apart From Other Activists</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with four grafs to ADD that Havel's trial date also set
for Feb. 21. Pick up 5th pvs, `The 52-year-old...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prominent playwright Vaclav Havel will be
tried separately from eight other activists arrested with him last
month during a rally in Prague, an emigre publication said Tuesday.
   The trial of the eight civil rights and peace activists, arrested
at the peaceful protest on Jan. 16, will start Feb. 21 in Prague,
said Palach Press, a London-based newsletter monitoring events in
Czechoslovakia.
   Havel is to be tried separately starting the same day at a
district court in the capital, a relative said in a telephone
interview from Prague.
   Six of the eight were freed pending trial, it said.
   The 52-year-old playwright is in custody, charged with sedition
and obstructing public officials. The more serious charge of
sedition can carry a penalty of up to two years in prison.
   The nine were detained after trying to lay flowers in memory of
Jan Palach, a student who burned himself alive 20 years ago. He was
protesting the 1968 Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia, which
crushed the country's liberal reforms.
