<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria-Union     02-14 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria-Union,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intellectuals Form Trade Union in Bulgaria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small group of Bulgarians has formed the
communist nation's first independent trade union _ for artists and
intellectuals _ and applied for official status, emigre sources in
the West reported.
   Documents for official registration of the union, bearing the
names of seven founding members, were delivered to authorities
Saturday, said Eduard Genov, an exiled Bulgarian dissident now
living in the United States.
   Genov, reached by telephone from Vienna on Monday, said Diana
Boyagshieva was the group's spokeswoman and some of the members also
belonged to the independent Association for the Defense of Human
Rights. He said the union would be based in Plovdiv, an industrial
town.
   The human rights group, to which Genov belonged before he was
exiled last year, has been suppressed and several members have been
subject to arrest.
   A Bulgarian exile source in Vienna confirmed that intellectuals
were seeking official permission for the union and apparently were
not trying to enroll blue-collar members.
   The West German radio Deutsche Welle said Tuesday the union was
named Podkrepa, or Support.
   It said the group's purpose was to oppose ``arbitrariness and
encroachments by unscrupulous colleagues, firms and state
enterprises.''
   The station quoted an informant, who was not identified, as
saying the union qualified for legal status under Article 52 of
Bulgaria's constitution, which deals with the right of association.
</TEXT>
