<FIRST>r w AM-SleepingEngineer     02-14 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sleeping Engineer,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Board Blames Sleeping Crew, Work Rules in Train Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators on Tuesday blamed work
arrangements that deprived a train crew of sleep for the head-on
collision of two Conrail freight trains in Pennsylvania that killed
both trains' engineers and brakemen a year ago.
   The National Transportation Safety Board recommended that
Consolidated Rail Corp. and other railroads look for ways to change
work cycles that put crewmen on trains without adequate sleep.
   The board said the Jan. 14, 1988, collision at Thompsontown
occurred because the engineer and brakeman of a 105-car coal train
were asleep. It was made worse, the board said, because the engineer
of the other train did not slow down quickly enough and a
computer-based traffic control system was not working properly.
Damage in the crash was estimated at $6 million.
   The report said none of the men on the coal train, which was en
route from Baltimore to Altoona, Pa., had had more than two hours
sleep in the previous 22 to 24 hours, and they had not eaten in over
13 hours. The men had reported for work at 11:30 p.m. and the crash
was at 7:45 a.m. the next day.
   Conrail spokeswoman Pat Linsky said the company could not comment
in detail until officials had reviewed the board report. But the
railroad issued a statement saying that the engineer and brakeman on
the coal train had signed off their previous runs 37.5 hours earlier
and the conductor 50 hours before boarding the Baltimore-Altoona
train.
   ``The probable cause of this accident was the sleep-deprived
condition of the engineer and other crewmembers of train UBT-506,
which resulted in their inability to stay awake and alert,'' the
board said. It said the engineer did not attempt to stop the train
after warning signals went off and suggested he may have pushed a
pedal in his sleep that acknowledged the warning but deactivated
automatic braking of the train.
   Drug tests on the four dead crewmen and two conductors who
survived the crash were negative for use of alcohol or illicit
drugs, except for a minuscule indication of marijuana in one
conductor's urine.
   The board said the railroad industry has long had unpredictable
work schedules but the problem has worsened with the elimination of
many regularly scheduled freight and passenger trains, a cutback in
yard operations, agreements protecting employee seniority, longer
freight runs and relocations of work assignments.
</TEXT>
