<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     02-14 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spokesman Warns Of Pressuring By Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government expressed cautious optimism
Tuesday about talks in their second week with Solidarity, but it
warned the banned independent union to ``stop pressing us against
the wall.''
   A spokesman for the union, responding to the statement by
government spokesman Jerzy Urban, denied Solidarity had such
intentions.
   ``We want to reform the country, and if this requires the
government's withdrawal from its hitherto policy, that's something
else,'' said Janusz Onyszkiewicz, Solidarity spokesman.
   The exchange came as Solidarity leader Lech Walesa traveled to
Jastrzebie in the coal-mining region of Silesia, his second campaign
swing in five days to seek rank-and-file backing for the
negotiations.
   Talks continued in Warsaw as part of the broad series of ``round
table'' negotiations, aimed at reinstating Solidarity's legal
status, bringing about opposition participation in Parliament and
forming a broad social agreement on economic and political reforms.
   Two teams meeting Tuesday discussed environmental protection and
an opposition proposal for a nationwide system of indexing wages to
inflation.
   Urban, at his weekly news conference, said Solidarity's proposal
that the military and police budgets be cut by 20 percent is an
example of pressuring.
   Urban characterized the proposal as ``political'' and irrelevant
to a discussion on improving the economy.
   ``Stop pressing us against the wall,'' he said. ``We are putting
forward a program of changes which are already so deep and brave .
.. that a general pressing of us may turn into adventurism
destroying the chance for agreement.'' Even so, Urban said he could
express ``cautious optimism'' about the talks. ``Please do not
interpret my remarks as negative ones,'' he said.
   But Onyszkiewicz said the tone of Urban's comments was
unexpected. ``I am a bit surprised that Minister Urban presented it
in such a drastic way. ... Such a reaction seems completely
unjustified.''
   Solidarity's National Executive Commission, with about 20
members, also convened Tuesday and issued a statement in Warsaw
urging a ``decrease of social tensions'' for the next six weeks
while talks with the goverment continue.
   The panel suggested a freeze on prices during the six weeks and
said that managers discuss any ``wage decisions'' in advance with
Solidarity and other trade unions.
   In southern Poland, Walesa stressed to miners the importance of
the talks.
   ``We must agree. ... We have to use all our wisdom and strength
to make something out of Poland,'' he said. ``We have no choice.''
   Walesa addressed 500 miners at a social club in front of the
Manifest Lipcowy mine, where a nationwide wave of strikes began last
August, prompting the government to propose the talks.
   ``Nobody is going to build Poland for us as a present,'' Walesa
said. But referring to the government, he added: ``We were badly
led. This system has led to absurdities.''
   Walesa received an enthusiastic welcome at the club filled with
Solidarity songs and banners. It appeared to be the warmest meeting
so far during his travels to brief followers on the talks.
   After attending Mass with more than 2,000 people at a church,
Walesa held an hour-long meeting with Silesia Solidarity activists
in the church basement.

</TEXT>
