<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     02-14 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Supporter Meets with Israeli Leftists; 4 Palestinians Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faisal Husseini, a leading supporter of the PLO
in the occupied territories, met with left-wing Israeli legislators
Tuesday in the first such contact since the Palestinian uprising
began 14 months ago.
   ``It was a general meeting and we discussed personal subjects,''
Husseini said after the two-hour session at a guest house in Arab
east Jerusalem. He would say no more and members of the Israeli
delegation declined comment.
   Among the Israelis were Labor Party legislator Chaim Ramon; Chaim
Tzadok, a former Labor justice minister; legislator Yair Tzaban of
the socialist party Mapam, and Mapam's general secretary, Elazar
Granot.
   Government policy prohibits contacts with the Palestine
Liberation Organization, but leftist legislators want that changed
on grounds the PLO is Israel's inevitable partner in peace
negotiations. The government considers the PLO a terrorist
organization.
   Husseini, who has spent 18 of the past 22 months in Israeli
prisons under ``administrative detention'' without trial, has
expressed willingness to meet with Israelis of all political
viewpoints.
   ``I would like to spend more and more time ... talking with
different groups of Israelis, not only groups that support my aims
but those who are not supporting our aims,'' he said in an interview
earlier Tuesday.
   Asked about talking with Israeli leaders, Husseini said: ``If
it's the right place, the right timing, the right person, I will not
say no. If it's the wrong time, the wrong place, the wrong person, I
will say no.''
   While in prison, Husseini met with Shmuel Goren, coordinator of
Israeli policy in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, which
Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
Goren arranged the meeting.
   Soldiers shot and wounded four Palestinians in the occupied lands
Tuesday, ranging in age from 9 to 16, Arab hospital officials
reported. An army official confirmed a 9-year-old was wounded in the
West Bank city of Nablus.
   At least 380 Palestinians and 15 Israelis have been killed since
the uprising began, and more than 7,000 Palestinians have been
wounded.
   Merchants closed their shops in Bethlehem, a Christian town in
the West Bank, to protest raids by Israeli tax authorities, an Arab
reporter said. Tax boycotts have been a regular feature of the
uprising.
   In the Golan Heights, captured from Syrian in 1967, Druse Arabs
held a general strike to protest Israeli annexation of the area
seven years ago. Hundreds of extra riot police were deployed to
prevent violence.
   ``The Druse don't accept it (the annexation) because this is
Syrian territory,'' a villager identified as Arab Zafadi said on
Israeli army radio.
   About 150 Syrians, some shouting anti-Israeli slogans through
loudspeakers, approached the border to support the Druse, Israel
radio said.
   Israel extended its law to the Golan Heights on Dec. 14, 1981.
The Druse began a campaign against it two months later but have not
held regular protests in solidarity with the Palestinian uprising.
The Druse sect is an offshoot of Islam.
</TEXT>
