<FIRST>r w AM-NavyContracts     02-14 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Contracts,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wisconsin, Virginia Firms Win Navy Contracts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy said Tuesday it had awarded a $185.1
million contract to a Wisconsin shipbuilder for three additional
ocean-going mine-sweeping ships.
   The service also announced a separate, $35 million award to the
Newport News Shipbuilding &amp; Drydock Co. to inactivate and defuel two
old, nuclear-powered attack submarines.
   The two submarines are the Skipjack, which was commissioned in
1959, and the Sculpin, commissioned in 1961. The Navy described the
deactivations as long-planned and routine and based on the age of
the vessels.
   The larger contract was awarded to Peterson Builders Inc. of
Sturgeon Bay, Wis. Peterson is the lead contractor for the so-called
Avenger class of mine-sweepers.
   Two weeks ago, the Navy announced it had settled a dispute with
another Wisconsin shipyard that is building the vessels. In that
case, the Navy said it was providing additional money to ensure that
the Marinette Marine Corp., which has been struggling financially,
completed work on the three ships it has under contract.
   Construction of the vessels at both yards was delayed for two
years because of hundreds of design changes. The ships are unusual
in that they must be made with glass-reinforced plastic sheathing on
a wooden hull _ and use low-metal engines _ in order to maintain the
``low magnetic signature'' essential to hunting and clearing mines.
   Peterson has delivered the first ship in the class, the Avenger,
and has four others under contract besides the three awarded
Tuesday. The Navy has not said how the settlement with Marinette
will affect that firm's participation in the program.
</TEXT>
