<FIRST>r i AM-CostaRica-Hull     02-14 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Costa Rica-Hull,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hull Moved from Hospital to Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARLOS A. SANDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-born John Hull, a supporter of
Nicaraguan rebels who is under arrest on drug and weapons charges,
has been moved from a hospital to a jail, his lawyer, Elda Zuniga,
said Tuesday.
   Hull, 69, had been in custody in a Costa Rican hospital where he
was taken on Jan. 24 after suffering a heart attack in his jail cell.
   He was taken to a prison near the capital on Monday for transfer
to the prison in San Carlos, 105 miles northwest of San Jose near
the border with Nicaragua, Ms. Zuniga said. She explained that San
Carlos ``is where his case will be processed because it is where the
supposed law violations occurred.''
   A native of Indiana, Hull moved to Costa Rica 20 years ago and
has a ranch in Los Chiles, near San Carlos. His lawyer says he
became a Costa Rican citizen eight years ago.
   Hull was arrested on Jan. 13 on charges of drug trafficking and
violating Costa Rican security. Ms. Zuniga refiled a petition
Tuesday asking that he be released on bail. A similar request was
denied earlier.
   ``We hope this request is resolved favorably because John's
health is not completely stable,'' Ms. Zuniga said.
   She holds that the government's case is unfounded because the
drug law Hull was accused of violating in 1984 was not passed until
1987 and is not retroactive.
   Costa Rican authorities said Hull was arrested for investigation
of drug trafficking and spying for the anti-Sandinista rebels after
complaints by residents near his farm.
   Witnesses testifying before the U.S. Congress on illegal arms
shipments to the Contras have said Hull's ranch was used by gun
smugglers and cocaine traffickers.
   Hull strongly denied any connection to drug trafficking.
</TEXT>
