<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--TankerAdrift 1stLd-Writethru a0549 02-14 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Tanker Adrift, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0549,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drifting Tanker Taken Into Tow While Headed for Oil Rigs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with tanker in tow, CORRECTING that
oil rig, not tanker was evacuated. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IJMUIDEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch tugs Tuesday reached a
drifting tanker that was floating toward a cluster of oil rigs in
the central North Sea, and the danger of a collision was averted, a
Dutch coast guard spokesman said.
   He said two tugs reached the rudderless, Bahamas-registered
Alexandros when it was still nearly 20 miles from the Dutch-owned
oil rig toward which the ship was heading.
   The spokesman, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said ``the
situation is under control.''
   Earlier Tuesday, a British Navy helicopter evacuated 19 of the
rig's crew as the Alexandros, carrying 71,000 tons of crude oil,
drifted toward the structure, about 100 miles northwest of Ijmuiden.
   The Dutch and British navies and coast guards had been on
stand-by since early Tuesday, when the tanker radioed a distress
call saying it lost its rudder, the spokesman said.
   How the Alexandros became disabled was not clear, but the
spokesman said a gale was raging in the area early Tuesday.
   The Alexandros was not damaged and no injuries were reported
among its crew of 28.
   The rigs are operated by Nederlandse Aardolie Maatschappij, which
is jointly owned by Esso and Shell.
</TEXT>
