<FIRST>u a AM-IncentiveAward     02-14 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Incentive Award,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civilian Rewarded For Saving The Government $6.3 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian who saved the military $6.3
million was finally paid back Tuesday with a government check for
$18,375.
   John Ledoux, a sergeant with the Vermont Army National Guard,
created a device two years ago that detects whether the infrared
lights on a helicopter work. His $8.70 creation replaced a $4,500
pair of special goggles.
   During a ceremony in the Burlington building where he built the
device, Ledoux finally received an incentive award from the federal
Office of Personnel Management. After taxes, the $25,000 reward came
to $18,375.50.
   Ledoux said he was glad to finally get the award, which was held
up for several months because the White House apparently lost the
letter authorizing the payment.
   ``I feel like it's been put off for so long it's lost its glow.
But I'm glad it's finally coming to a head,'' said the soft-spoken
father of five, who accepted the check with his family by his side.
   ``My wife and I have a big family so of course, the money is
nice,'' he said.
   The award is the maximum allowed by law and the largest given to
a federal employee, said Joseph Jamele, press secretary for Sen.
Patrick Leahy, D-Vt. He said 20 such awards have been granted.
   Ledoux, 33, is a former military technician who worked full time
at the National Guard base in Burlington before taking a job with
the Federal Aviation Administration last year. He developed his
device in 1986 after watching engineers with the Lockheed Aircraft
Corp. test infrared lights on helicopters.
   Ledoux was concerned the engineers had to perch in precarious
positions to test the lights, particularly while standing on the
choppers or on ramps outside the helicopter hanger.
   ``It was more for the safety of individuals _ that was his
concern,'' said Maj. George Bergeron, Ledoux's former boss.
``Vermont ramps are pretty cold and icy.''
   Ledoux built the hand-held infrared sensor from $8.70 worth of
parts from the local hardware store. ``When he first came up with
this, he stayed up late after work in the shop. Quite a few nights
he did that to improve his idea,'' Bergeron said.
   The Army embraced the device after Ledoux sent one down.
According to Bergeron's estimates, it has saved the military 987,000
hours of labor a year, for a total $6.85 million. Bergeron estimated
net savings of $6.3 million after subtracting the costs of materials
and of implementing the device.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HandicappedAccess 1stLd-Writethru a0633 02-14 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Handicapped Access, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0633,0876</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruling Won't End Access Quandary For Mass Transit Agencies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 6 grafs after 12th graf, `A transport...' to UPDATE
with reaction from Boston, Philadelphia, Chicago and Houston; picks up
13th graf, `The appeals...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the disabled on Tuesday hailed
a federal court ruling requiring wheelchair lifts on new public
buses, but a spokesman for transit agencies said the ruling doesn't
address vexing problems.
   ``We've been grappling with this for a long time,'' said Albert
Engelken, deputy executive director of the Washington-based American
Public Transit Association.
   He said wheelchair lifts receive limited use where they exist and
are an added expense to transit agencies at a time when federal
subsidies have been dwindling.
   On Monday a 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals panel ruled 2-1
that Congress has made its wishes on accessibility clear and that
lift-equipped buses are part of that mandate.
   The court ordered the U.S. Transportation Department to rewrite a
regulation allowing communities to offer alternative ``paratransit''
service, such as van rides, to the disabled. It said the 24-hour
reservations that riders need to make for such services hinder
spontaneous use of mass transit.
   James D. Fornari, a New York City attorney for a group of
veterans with spinal cord injuries, said the ruling will force
transit systems to look for the most efficient means of serving
disabled people.
   He said the ruling also could influence Transportation Department
regulations being drafted on light rail and commuter rail systems.
   ``We are quite pleased with this decision and I see it as a
springboard for making other transit systems which have buses
accessible to the mobility impaired, so they can be mainstreamed
into American life and society,'' Fornari said.
   Transportation Department spokesman Bob Marx declined comment on
the ruling. He said attorneys for the department had not yet seen
the decision.
   Engelken said his association's board, which comprises the heads
of transit agencies across the nation, believes agencies should be
able to decide on a local basis how best to serve disabled people.
   ``Up until now, the courts have ruled that it was local option,''
he said. ``This evidently is a new twist.''
   A transit association task force is studying the issue of
handicapped access and is scheduled to report by the end of the
year, he said.
   Many local transportation officials declined comment on the
ruling because they had not seen it.
   But Peter Dimond, a spokesman for Massachusetts Bay
Transportation Authority in Boston, said, ``We have made a pledge
that all buses we purchase in the future will be lift-equipped.''
The Boston authority operates 800 buses daily, of which about a
third are lift-equipped, Dimond said. A new batch of 200 buses is on
order, all equipped with lifts. The agency also provides
door-to-door van service.
   Carol Boudreaux, a spokeswoman for Metropolitan Transit Authority
in Houston, said none of the authority's more than 900 buses are
equipped with lifts. But she said the authority has always complied
with Transportation Department regulations in the past and expected
it would with any new regulations mandated by the ruling.
   The Houston authority offers a service with vans or cabs, in
which the handicapped pay a portion.
   Donna Alston, a spokeswoman for Southeastern Pennsylvania
Transportation Authority, said 568 of the authority's 1,510 buses
are lift-equipped. She said the authority provides 1,200 rides on
its alternative paratransit service on an average weekday.
   A Chicago Transit Authority spokeswoman, who asked that her name
not be used, said that the CTA has more than 2,000 buses and none
have wheelchair lifts.
   The appeals court also upheld a lower court order that the
Transportation Department rewrite regulations that relieve transit
authorities of their obligations to ensure accessibility if they
spend 3 percent of their budget on services to the handicapped.
   ``Given the clear congressional mandate of accessibility, the
DOT's choice of the cost cap exceeded its discretion,'' wrote Judge
Carol Los Mansmann in the majority ruling.
   But Judge Morton I. Greenberg dissented, saying he felt the
majority went too far. ``To the extent that money is spent for
adding lifts to regular transit coaches it will not be available for
paratransit services unless general services are curtailed, fares
raised or more aid obtained,'' he wrote.
   Fornari, who represented the Eastern Paralyzed Veterans
Association in the case, said cost was not a major factor in transit
agencies' failure to install wheelchair lifts.
   ``The cost of paratransit is far in excess of what this will
cost,'' he said.
   Rather, the ruling will require transit operators ``to meet
service criteria instead of just throwing money at it,'' Fornari
said.
   It costs $15,000 to equip a bus with a wheelchair lift, and buses
cost about $200,000, according to Joaquin Bowman, a spokesman for
the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority, which serves
the Philadelphia metropolitan area.
   The ruling came in connection with suits filed in 1986 by the
veterans group and a coalition called Americans Disabled for
Accessible Public Transportation, which has chapters in 25 cities
and whose members have been arrested at demonstrations around the
country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
