<FIRST>r a AM-HarrisAunt     02-14 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Harris Aunt,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Governor Pallbearer at Slain Aunt's Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARTERSVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Joe Frank Harris was among the
pallbearers as about 350 people paid their last respects Tuesday to
his slain 74-year-old aunt.
   The blue-robed choir left a space at the usual seat of Allie
Morrow Roper as the mourners assembled at Faith United Methodist
Church for a service in which she was eulogized as a devout
Christian who cared and prayed for her fellow man.
   There still were no suspects in her strangulation, authorities
said.
   The sanctuary of the small, red brick church, where ``Miss
Allie'' was a long-time member, could not hold all the mourners.
About 50 listened to a speaker in a church courtyard.
   The sanctuary, which usually included flowers arranged by Mrs.
Roper for Sunday services, was lined with floral arrangements.
   The governor did not speak at the service, at which his brother,
Fred Harris, eulogized their aunt as ``mischievous'' but a source of
strength for their family.
   He said he had been told the oven in her home was on when her
body was found Sunday. He said she apparently was preparing to bake
``and I believe that was for Joe Frank's birthday (Thursday).''
   Authorities have speculated Mrs. Roper was killed by an intruder
Saturday. Her body was discovered when she did not show up for
church Sunday.
   Cartersville police have begun circulating a composite drawing of
a man seen near Mrs. Roper's home, but Public Safety Director Otis
Chupp said, ``There is still nothing concrete.''
   A reward fund organized by the Cartersville-Bartow County Chamber
of Commerce had reached more than $6,000 Tuesday.
   Relatives of Mrs. Roper issued a statement through Tommy Lewis,
an aide to the governor.
   ``The family deeply appreciates the many prayers and all the
support they have felt from the community and the state,'' Lewis
said.
</TEXT>
