<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FamilyPoisonings     02-14 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family Poisonings,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Poisoning 7 Children To Get Clemency Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez said Tuesday a
clemency hearing will be held for a man who says he was framed for
the fatal poisonings of his seven children in 1967.
   Martinez said he and three Cabinet members have agreed to hold
the hearing. A majority of the seven-member Cabinet was needed to
waive rules in order to hold the clemency hearing.
   ``There are a great many questions in this case that demand
answers,'' Martinez said in a statement. ``I am gratified that ...
we can now move forward to reach those answers.''
   Martinez and the six independently elected Cabinet members,
sitting as the Board of Executive Clemency, have the power to pardon
James Richardson, who is serving a life sentence at Tomoka
Correctional Institution in Daytona Beach.
   ``We hope that the Cabinetwill grant immediate clemency and
release James Richardson,'' said Ellis Rubin, a Miami lawyer
representing the former fruit picker. ``This is probably the most
wronged man in the United States. ... Today was a very big step on
the road of freedom for James Richardson.''
   Rubin said Richardson, 53, sobbed when he told him of support for
the clemency hearing and the inmate said his prayers had been
answered.
   ``I want to be free,'' Richardson told Rubin. ``It has been
terrible and when I walk out of this prison, I want to look at these
men who put me here, straight in the eye, and I will then ask God to
forgive them. This is one of the greatest days of my life.''
   Richardson and his wife were picking fruit on Oct. 25, 1967, when
their children, aged 2 to 8, ate a parathion-laced lunch of beans,
rice and grits. The lunch had been prepared ahead of time, but was
served by neighbor Betsy Reese at the family's Arcadia home.
   Prosecutors said Richardson killed all seven children, but he was
convicted of only one first-degree murder count in 1968 for the
death of his 8-year-old stepdaughter, Betty Jean Bryant.
   Martinez said his office will consult with Dade County State
Attorney Janet Reno, whom he asked on Feb. 1 to investigate the
case, before scheduling a hearing.
</TEXT>
