<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Reactor-Tritium     02-14 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reactor-Tritium,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Shows $125 Million Cost For Tritium Conversion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An idle reactor on the Hanford nuclear
reservation could produce tritium for weapons after a three-year,
$125 million conversion, providing a quick fix for the nation's
nuclear arms program, a study says.
   The nation's only supply of tritium, a radioactive isotope of
hydrogen that is a key ingredient in nuclear weapons, has been cut
off since early last year because of reactor safety problems at
South Carolina's Savannah River Plant.
   The $5.5 million study authorized by the U.S. Department of
Energy considered whether Hanford's idle N Reactor could be made
into a short-term tritium producer until new reactors could be
built, a site manager at Westinghouse Hanford said Tuesday.
   ``It would cost $125 million over three years to set the reactor
up for tritium,'' Wallace Ruff, manager of defense reactors at the
south-central Washington site, told The Associated Press.
   Hanford's N Reactor, which manufactured another key nuclear
weapons ingredient, plutonium, has been on ``cold standby'' since
early 1988 because of a surplus of plutonium.
   The plan outlined by the study, which was conducted by
Westinghouse Hanford Co., would be a relatively quick and
inexpensive fix for a U.S. nuclear weapons program that is without a
working reactor producing tritium and faces steep costs in building
new tritium reactors.
   The production and supply of nuclear weapons materials is
classified, but Ruff said the study found the N Reactor could meet
tritium production needs.
   Such a development could ease the impact of the 2,800 layoffs
expected when the N Reactor is completely shut down. About 1,800 of
those layoffs already have occurred.
   The Energy Department is planning tritium reactors in South
Carolina and Idaho, and an experimental method of using a linear
accelerator to produce tritium also has drawn much recent attention.
   The linear accelerator would be at least seven years away from
production and the new reactors about a decade away.
   A third proposal, to convert an unfinished civilian reactor at
Hanford to tritium production, has run into considerable opposition
from anti-nuclear activists who say that would violate international
non-proliferation agreements.
   Tom Bauman, a spokesman for the Energy Department in Richland,
said no decision has been made on restarting the N Reactor for
tritium.
   ``The department is constantly looking at this,'' he said.
   The N Reactor, which began operations in 1963, could operate
about nine years as a tritium producer at about $150 million per
year before the plant was adversely affected by aging, Ruff said.
   The reactor shared some design similarities with the Chernobyl
plant, whose 1986 destruction killed 31 people. Both used graphite
in the reactor core to moderate nuclear fission and lacked a
containment dome to trap accidental emissions.
   Federal officials have repeatedly said the N Reactor is much
safer than the Soviet plant, and $100 million worth of safety
improvements were performed after the N Reactor was closed for
inspections in early 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0165 </DOCNO>
