<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater     02-14 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>`In a Pig's Valise,' A New Musical, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the corner of Neon and Lonely streets in the
bar of the Heartbreak Hotel, dreams don't even have time to die hard.
   That's because someone is stealing them _ drugging the dreamers
and slipping into their subconscious to pilfer their most private
fantasies and thoughts.
   If that sounds like an audacious and unlikely subject for song
and dance, it is. But then ``In a Pig's Valise,'' the new musical
which arrived Tuesday at off-Broadway's Second Stage, may well be
the most audacious and unlikely new musical of the season.
   That's not to say ``perfect,'' but Eric Overmyer, who wrote the
book and lyrics, and August Darnell, who wrote the music, have an
affection for the writings of Raymond Chandler and Dashiell Hammett
and the hard-boiled detective stories they are spoofing. Because of
that, it's easy to overlook a repetitiveness that eventually
sidetracks the show once the novelty of the dialogue begins to wear
off.
   The musical's hero is a pudgy shamus named James Taxi, hired by a
Latin spitfire named Dolores Con Leche _ meaning Sorrows with Milk,
explains Taxi _ to find her missing sister. The search leads to the
Heartbreak Hotel and nefarious doings by a gang of thugs, led by the
notorious Bucket brothers, Shrimp and Gut.
   The gang kidnaps people and makes off with their dreams to sell
as computerized holograms. Their biggest catch is Walt Disney _ his
body frozen, wrapped like a mummy and waiting for the big thaw. But
these criminals will take the minds of just about anyone including
Dolores who goes undercover as an ethnic folk dancer in the hotel's
nightclub.
   The plot is awash in simile, metaphor and enough tough guy double
talk to baffle Bogart. Much of the deliberately purple prose is
relayed directly to the audience by Taxi, and most of it, while not
advancing the plot, is very funny.
   Taxi, played by Nathan Lane, is a loser, a well-meaning
marshmallow masquerading as a hard-edged private eye. Lane fits the
role perfectly. He's a brash performer who moves and sings well.
Forty years ago, he would have worked steadily on Broadway. Today,
he has to be content with occasional forays into musical comedy.
   Ada Maris sizzles as the tempestuous Dolores, and Michael
McCormick is a hilarious foil as the evil and fleet-of-foot Shrimp
Bucket.
   As he demonstrated in his plays ``On the Verge'' and ``In
Perpetuity Throughout the Universe,'' Overmyer revels in language.
He has an ear for pop vernacular of the past but he laces it with an
up-to-date sensibility that makes it funny in 1989.
   Overmyer's lyrics don't have the intricacy and linguistic dazzle
of his dialogue, but they fit the eclectic score by Darnell, best
known as the leader of the band Kid Creole and the Coconuts.
   Darnell's music is not the stuff of typical musical comedy. It's
all over the place with bits and pieces of jazz, rock, pop, salsa,
reggae and even rap stuffed into the score.
   The show, thanks to set designer Bob Shaw and lighting designer
Peggy Eisenhauer, has the feel of one of those smoky 1940s Warner
Bros. detective movies, all shadows and neon signs.
   Graciela Daniele's fast-paced direction and snappy choreography
propel the musical, rushing the actors through the plot when details
try to bog down the evening. But for much of time, ``In a Pig's
Valise'' is as scintillating and seductive as the saxophone wail
that begins the show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2221EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Balloonist 1stLd-Writethru a0648 02-14 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloonist, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Balloonist Begins Solo Flight Across Pacific</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with balloonist saying all OK.
Pick up 5th pvs, `His balloon...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YOKOHAMA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fumio Niwa soared into the night early
Wednesday, hoping his huge orange and blue balloon will find the
easterly jet stream and carry him to San Diego on the first solo
balloon flight across the Pacific.
   San Diego is the sister city of Yokohama, his hometown, but Niwa
may not reach it even if he crosses the ocean successfully. Late
weather reports said the winds in the jet stream, which begins at
about 35,000 feet, had veered to the north and probably would take
the balloon toward Alaska instead.
   Just before setting off for North America, which he hoped to
reach in about four days, Niwa said: ``My long dream of crossing the
Pacific is coming true today. I still wonder if it's really
possible. The jet stream is bending strangely, but America is big so
I think I'll make it, somewhere.
   ``As people say, things that go up must come down, so I'm not
very worried.''
   After nearly five hours of slow climbing in the cold evening sky
, Fumio Niwa reported Wednesday morning ``everything is going
fine,'' a spokesman said.
   In his first radio contact with home, made at 6:21 a.m. (4:21 EST
Tuesday), Niwa said the balloon was about 80 miles southeast of
Yokohama, where he lifted off at 1:47 a.m. (12:47 EST Tuesday),
according to project spokesman Tadakatsu Izumi.
   Izumi said Niwa's balloon, flying at an altitude of 8,200 feet,
would head toward the south ``for some time'' before reaching
high-altitude winds later in the day.
   His balloon has no maneuvering ability, so its direction depends
entirely on the wind. It carries no navigation equipment, and Niwa
must rely on amateur radio reports of his location, based on
satellite trackings.
   Ground equipment used to receive the satellite data malfunctioned
and a standby unit was installed, delaying his takeoff for several
hours.
   Niwa, 38, says he never outgrew his childhood love of playing and
is making what he hopes will be a 5,000-mile flight to test the
balloon and gondola, both of which he designed.
   ``If just flying were my purpose, I'd buy a ready-made balloon,''
he said, ``but I like to design and make my own equipment and then
try it out.''
   The gondola, the fifth Niwa has designed, is a globe six feet in
diameter, too small inside for a passenger to stand, and made of a
plastic stronger than the type used for bulletproof vests. It is
pressurized because of the high altitudes at which he plans to
travel.
   Unlike most, Niwa's helium balloon is completely sealed and
filled with pressurized gas. High winds Monday and Tuesday delayed
the filling process and tore parts of an outer reflective layer of
silver fabric.
   Niwa quit his job at a computer company in November to prepare
for the flight, which he estimates will cost the equivalent of about
$540,000. He hopes to earn most of it back from a book and public
appearances.
   Because of financial constraints, he said, the gondola has no
alarms to warn of a loss of gas or sudden change in altitude. It
also has no heating system and Niwa must rely on electric heating
coils in his flying suit to keep him warm in temperatures expected
to reach 60 below zero.
   He has about 1,000 hours of ballooning experience, most in
hot-air balloons and none outside Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2228EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0637 02-14 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0637,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lankans Vote After Hundreds Die in Bloody Campaigning</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with voting starting, new violence.
No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 80,000 Sri Lankan soldiers
and police stood guard as this island nation voted on Wednesday for
a new Parliament after a violent campaign left hundreds dead,
including 14 candidates.
   Sinhalese and Tamil militants demanded an election boycott and
threatened to kill anyone who went to the 8,070 polling booths to
vote.
   Buses were set afire on election eve, and at least 25 people were
killed in attacks by Sinhalese trying to enforce the boycott,
authorities said.
   In the north and east of this Indian Ocean island, 40,000 Indian
troops, here under a peace accord, were told ``to be very strict
with any attempts to disrupt the polls,'' an Indian diplomat said on
condition of anonymity.
   Polls opened for nine hours at 7 a.m. Significant returns were
not expected until Thursday.
   One hour before voting began, a policeman guarding the polling
center at Ananda College in Colombo was shot and badly wounded by
two men in a car.
   A police official at nearby Maradana police station said the
gunmen were Sinhalese extremists.
   The 225 seats in Parliament are being contested by nine political
parties and 10 independent groups. More than 9.3 million people are
eligible to vote.
   Favored to win was the governing United National Party headed by
President Ranasinghe Premadasa, who won the presidency in a bloody
election in December.
   United National's strongest foe was the Sri Lanka Freedom Party,
led by former Prime Minister Sirimavo Bandaranaike.
   Sinhalese militants oppose the election as part of their
anti-government campaign launched in July 1987. They accuse the
government of conceding too much to rebels of the minority Tamil
community in a largely unsuccessful attempt to end a 6-year-old
insurrection.
   The government says the militants have killed at least 800 people
since Jan. 1 and at least 1,500 since they started their campaign.
   The election also is opposed by Tamil guerrillas fighting for an
independent homeland in the north and east.
   A rebel statement issued Tuesday said Tamils objected to the
polls because voting was being held ``under conditions of war and
violence with continuing military repression.''
   In one incident Tuesday, three bus passengers and a driver were
killed when Sinhalese fired on buses operating in defiance of a
strike call aimed at disrupting the elections, officials said.
   Sinhalese with revolvers ordered passengers to get off, then
poured kerosene on the vehicles and set them on fire, said a police
official.
   Shops in Colombo and towns in the south stayed closed Tuesday in
response to a Sinhalese call for a two-day strike, residents said.
   Government officials insisted that the violence would only
marginally affect voter turnout.
   Indian soldiers in the Tamil-dominated north and east are trying
to put down the Tamil insurrection.
   India initially became involved in the ethnic crisis in Sri
Lanka, just off India's southern tip, because of the 60 million
Tamils in India who sympathize with the rebel cause.
   Tamils form 18 percent of Sri lanka's 16 million people and say
they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up 75
percent of the population and control the government and the
military.
   The parliamentary elections are being held for the first time on
the basis of proportional representation.
   Voters will cast ballots for parties and the percentage of votes
received will determine the number of seats each party will gain in
Parliament. Candidates will be chosen by preferential votes, but the
choices will be restricted to party nominees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
