<FIRST>r a AM-HonoraryOscars     02-14 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honorary Oscars,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada's National Film Board Wins Honorary Award</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oscar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Film Board of Canada
has won an honorary Oscar and the animation director of ``Who Framed
Roger Rabbit'' will receive an achievement award, the motion picture
academy said Tuesday.
   The Canadian film board's Oscar, to be presented at the 61st
annual Academy Awards show on March 29, recognizes the board's 50th
anniversary and cites a commitment to artistic, creative and
technological excellence.
   The board has been nominated for Oscars 52 times and won eight.
Its first award was in 1941 for ``Churchill's Island,'' which was
the first documentary.
   The award was voted by the Board of Governors of the Academy of
Motion Picture Arts and Science.
   The governors voted a special achievement award to Richard
Williams, director of animation and creator of all the new
characters in the animated feature ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,''
including Roger, Jessica and Baby Herman.
   The academy cited Williams' ``unique accomplishment'' in awarding
him his second Oscar. The first was for his short production of
Charles Dickens' ``A Christmas Carol'' in 1972.
   The Board of Governors decided not to present Irving G. Thalberg
and Jean Hersholt Humanitarian special awards this year.
   The Thalberg award is presented to ``a creative producer whose
body of work reflects a consistently high quality of motion picture
production.''
   The Hersholt award recognizes ``individuals in the motion picture
industry whose humanitarian efforts have brought credit to the
industry.''
   The awards show will be broadcast by ABC from the Shrine
Auditorium in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
