<FIRST>r i AM-NIreland-Shooting 1stLd-Writethru a0727 02-14 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NIreland-Shooting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0727,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Sinn Fein Councilman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs with British envoy to make fact-finding trip on
direct rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a councilman
belonging to Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the IRA, in the
second slaying of a Roman Catholic public figure this week, police
said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility, but suspicion fell
on Protestant paramilitaries opposed to the outlawed Irish
Republican Army, a mainly Roman Catholic group fighting British rule
of the province.
   John Joe Davey, who was in his late 50s, was gunned down as he
approached his home near Gulladuff, about 30 miles northwest of
Belfast, said a spokesman at police headquarters in Belfast.
   Police said several bullets hit him in the chest. They said his
wife ran down the lane from their home when she heard the shots but
found her husband already dead.
   Davey was returning from a town council in nearby Magherafelt,
police said. Davey was one of three members of Sinn Fein who sat in
the predominantly Protestant council.
   The attack followed the killing Sunday of Catholic attorney
Patrick Finucane, who had acted for clients in the IRA.
   Finucane was slain by three gunmen at his home in north Belfast.
A outlawed Protestant paramilitary group, the Ulster Freedom
Fighters, claimed responsibility for his death.
   Almost exactly a year ago, Davey survived a killing attempt in
exactly the same spot. Sinn Fein said in a statement that he had
survived three other assassination attempts.
   The IRA wants to unite predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland
with the 95 percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist
rule.
   Also Tuesday, the British government said it is sending an envoy
to Northern Ireland to discuss how to form a government that would
replace direct rule from London.
   Tom King, Northern Ireland secretary, said one of his four junior
ministers, Dr. Brian Mawhinney, will make the fact-finding trip to
Belfast.
   King, apparently referring to secret talks between the main
Northern Ireland parties that started in Duisburg, West Germany,
late last year, said: ``The question now is whether the
constitutional political parties and those who support them wish to
make progress.
   ``If they do, then I want to ensure that the government is ready
to play its part in whatever way is appropriate and helpful,'' King
said.
   Mawhinney, 48, who is a House of Commons legislator for an
English electoral district, was born in Northern Ireland.
   The province has been ruled from London since March 1972.
</TEXT>
