<DOCNO> AP890214-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     02-14 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peronist Candidate Demands Argentine Sovereignty over Falklands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICENTE L. PANETTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Carlos
Menem of the opposition Peronist Party was quoted on Tuesday as
saying the Falkland Islands belong to Argentina and will be
recovered ``even if we must suffer the spilling of blood.''
   ``Argentina will not give in,'' Menem said during a campaign
swing Monday night, according to Argentina's two independent news
agencies, Diarios y Noticias and Noticias Argentinas.
   The Malvinas _ Argentina's name for the territory off its south
coast that it has claimed since 1810 _ ``will return to form part of
the national territory even if we must suffer the spilling of
blood,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Menem was on a visit to Ushuaia, 2,045 miles south of the capital
city of Buenos Aires.
   Argentina and Britain went to war over the sparsely populated,
windswept and virtually treeless islands in 1982. Argentine troops
invaded on April 2. A British expeditionary force recovered the
islands after a counterattack in which 712 Argentine and 255 British
soldiers died.
   The war lasted 74 days. Argentina surrendered but refused to
formally declare an end to hostilities. Neither side resumed
diplomatic relations.
   Britain's claim dates to 1833. It has since fortified the islands
and enforced a 200-mile zone of exclusion around them. Argentina has
tried to isolate the islands commercially by prohibiting direct
flights or ships from the mainland.
   It has tried to apply international pressure to force Britain to
negotiate the islands' sovereignty. British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher has refused.
   The two agencies also quoted Menem as saying: ``I don't know how
much time will pass or how much blood we will have to spill to see
that the Malvinas return to Argentine territory.''
   President Raul Alfonsin and Foreign Minister Dante Caputo, who
also is president of the U.N. General Assembly, have said Argentina
inherited the islands upon declaring independence from Spain, and
the government will try to recover them peacefully through
negotiation.
   Ownership is an article of faith here. Argentine maps identify
the islands as the Malvinas, and schoolchildren are taught they were
stolen by Britain.
   Recovering the Falklands is a main foreign policy theme of
political groups from both left and right, along with the 4
million-member General Labor Confederation which backs Menem.
   Menem in the past said he would seek the islands' recovery by
diplomacy if he wins election on May 14. It was not known whether he
was speaking rhetorically in Ushuaia, or shifting and hardening his
position.
   A telephone call seeking comment from the British Interests
Section at the Swiss Embassy rang repeatedly but was not answered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
