<FIRST>u p AM-TulsaCharter 1stLd-Writethru a0662 02-14 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tulsa Charter, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0662,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tulsa Voters Approve New City Charter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with charter passing, quotes,
details. Picks up 11th graf, `Under the...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tulsa voters, who have refused to change the
city's government four times in 35 years, overwhelmingly approved a
new city charter Tuesday that could end a legal challenge by black
residents.
   A strong mayor-council form of government was approved by 33,373
votes, or 71 percent, to 14,213 votes, or 29 percent.
   ``This makes a very special Valentine's Day for all of us,'' said
Mayor Rodger Randle, who along with the city's four other elected
commissioners campaigned in support of the new charter.
   Tulsa has had a commission form of government elected at large
since 1908. Under the new charter, the mayor gains power and
continues to be elected at large, while nine councilmen will be
elected by districts.
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
has sued Tulsa, contending the at-large balloting for commissioners
unconstitutionally dilutes the minority black vote concentrated in
north Tulsa.
   Similar lawsuits in other cities have resulted in judges ordering
cities to change to a more representative government. A federal
judge has set a March 9 hearing on the Tulsa lawsuit to determine
whether the new charter makes the claims of the lawsuit moot.
   Election board officials said rain kept voter turnout under the
predicted 50,000 of the city's 225,000 registered voters.
   A 1969 proposal that would have changed Tulsa's form of
government failed by 63 votes out of more than 23,000 cast. The most
recent, a 1973 proposal, was defeated by a wide margin.
   City officials say the commission government is expensive and
inefficient.
   Supporters of Tuesday's measure said better representation for
black voters would be one of the benefits of changing the charter.
   Under the proposal, a part-time council would pass laws and
control the budget, while the mayor would have administrative power
and propose a budget. The mayor would be responsible for city
departments now divided among six full-time commissioners.
   Opponents said the charter change would give the mayor too much
power.
</TEXT>
