<FIRST>u p AM-DinkinsCandidacy 1stLd-Writethru a0638 02-14 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dinkins Candidacy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0638,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manhattan Borough President Announces for Mayor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 11th graf, ``I welcome' to UPDATE with
GOP congressman saying Guiliani is likely to run. Picks up 12th graf, `Several
polls...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins
announced Tuesday that he was running for mayor, saying 12 years
under Mayor Edward I. Koch had polarized the city and left it
desperate for new direction.
   ``I am running because I believe this city needs a different
direction, new ideas and a fresh perspective,'' Dinkins said.
   The announcement at a crowded news conference followed months of
speculation and recent obvious hints that Dinkins would take on Koch
in the September primary for the Democratic nomination in an effort
to become the city's first black mayor. Several polls have indicated
Dinkins could beat Koch.
   ``I am running because our city has become sharply polarized,''
he said. ``We need a mayor who can transcend differences so we can
work together to solve our problems.''
   Dinkins, 61, is a lawyer who served as state legislator, Board of
Elections president and city clerk before being elected in 1985 on
his third try for borough president. Each of New York's five
boroughs has a president who has a seat on the Board of Estimate,
which passes on budget and planning matters for the entire city.
   ``I am prepared to lead this city in the new direction we so
desperately need,'' Dinkins said. ``New Yorkers are tired of
politicians who talk tough but act only after problems reach crisis
proportions.''
   Koch and Dinkins are publicly respectful to each other, but the
relationship frosted a bit when Koch strongly criticized Democratic
presidential candidate Jesse Jackson during last year's race.
   Dinkins supported Jackson and said he expects Jackson to
participate in the campaign.
   ``The mayor clearly has on occasion contributed to the
polarization of our city,'' Dinkins said.
   Koch said he considers Dinkins ``to be a very formidable
candidate. I perceive myself as the underdog. That's not just
rhetoric. I think the polls show that. I hope to turn them around.
   ``I welcome him into the race,'' Koch said. ``I think that he is
a very decent guy. I know that both he and I will conduct the
election battle in a responsible way.''
   While Democrats make up a strong majority of the city's voters,
Republicans may also have a primary featuring well-known candidates
this year. Former federal prosecutor Rudolph Giuliani will likely
announce his candidacy for mayor ``sometime in March,'' said U.S.
Rep. Guy Molinari, R-N.Y. Molinari said he had had five meetings
with Giuliani to discuss a mayoral run.
   Republican Ronald Lauder, heir to the Estee Lauder cosmetics
fortune and a former ambassador to Austria, has already announced
his candidacy.
   Several polls have shown that Dinkins would defeat Koch and other
potential Democratic candidates, such as City Council President
Andrew Stein, special state prosecutor Charles J. Hynes, City
Councilwoman Ruth W. Messinger and former U.S. Rep. Herman Badillo.
   Though he downplayed the importance of polls, Dinkins said, ``I'd
rather be me than them, if you'll accept that grammar.''
   In contrast with the combative Koch, Dinkins has a courtly
manner, raising the question of what tone the campaign would have.
   ``I've been described as a nice guy, as a gentleman,'' Dinkins
said. Some of my close friends might dispute that.
   ``But let me tell you. ... I'm also an ex-Marine. And I don't
intend for a second to get shoved around in this or any other
campaign. So let's be clear on that.''
</TEXT>
