<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Scandal     02-14 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Business Executives Reportedly Arrested In Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors on Wednesday arrested two more
executives of two firms at the center of a major stock trading
scandal, bringing to seven the number of people arrested in the
case, a Japanese news report said.
   Shunjiro Mamiya, managing director of Recruit Co., and Seiichi
Tateoka, director of a real estate subsidiary Recruit-Cosmos Co.,
were arrested on charges of violating the Securities and Exchange
Law, the Kyodo New Service said.
   The parent company is a fast-growing business information
conglomerate that sold hundreds of thousands of shares in the
subsidiary to dozens of politicians, their aides and influential
businessmen and journalists before the company went public.
   The stocks soared in value after being made available for
over-the-counter trading, bringing huge profits to the purchasers.
   Mamiya played a central role in the sale of Recruit-Cosmos
stocks, while Tateoka looked after the financial aspect of the
transactions, Kyodo said.
   Prosecution officials refused to confirm the report of
Wednesday's arrests, saying they would talk only to reporters
belonging to a limited-membership press club affiliated with the
Tokyo District Public Prosecutors Office.
   The reported arrests came only two days after prosecutors
arrested Recruit founder Hiromasa Ezoe, an executive of a
Recruit-affiliated finance firm and two former directors of Nippon
Telephone and Telegraph Co., Japan's largest company.
   The four were held on suspicion of bribery involving resale of
U.S.-made supercomputers by NTT to Recruit and leasing telephone
lines to Recruit at discount prices.
   The only previous arrest was of a Recruit official accused of
trying to bribe an opposition member of Parliament to soft-pedal an
investigation into the affair.
   Thirty officers from the prosecutors office searched NTT's
downtown Tokyo offices for more than eight hours Tuesday,
confiscating documents that filled 70 boxes.
   The stock sales were not illegal under Japanese law but raised
public outcries as well as in Parliament about political
fund-raising and ethics in government.
   More than a dozen members of Parliament _ including three Cabinet
ministers, former top bureaucrats and senior businessmen _ have
stepped down from public positions because of their link to the
scandal.
   Opposition parties have repeatedly insisted that Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita and his Cabinet resign over the affair, but
Takeshita has rejected the calls.
</TEXT>
