<FIRST>r a AM-MailHoard     02-14 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mail Hoard,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Carrier Gets 1 Year, 1 Day For Hoarding `Mountain Of Mail'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Quote in 3rd graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former rural-route postal carrier was
sentenced Tuesday to a year and a day in prison for failing to
deliver two of the first-class pieces found among tons of so-called
junk mail he was hoarding.
   William Ryan, 59, of Milton, told U.S. District Judge Roger
Vinson that he felt he couldn't possibly deliver all the mail on his
Florida Panhandle route, so about three years ago he started leaving
a few pieces in his car every day.
   ``Things just seemed to snowball once it started,'' Ryan said.
``I'm very sorry for what happened. ... It's been a bad year last
year for me.''
   After receiving a tip last August, postal inspectors found what
Assistant U.S. Attorney Samuel Alter termed a ``mountain of mail''
heaped in Ryan's home, a shed and surrounding woods about 30 miles
northeast of Pensacola.
   Nearly 500,000 pieces were discovered, almost all of them
advertising circulars, sweepstakes offers, give-aways and other
third-class bulk mail.
   Alter conceded most of Ryan's customers probably were satisfied
with his service. But he said the companies that paid to mail the
material also are postal customers.
   ``The actual victim-impact on the mailers is incalculable,'' the
prosecutor said.
   The judge also placed Ryan on probation for three years once his
prison sentence is completed and ordered him to pay $2,991.94 in
restitution to the Postal Service and a $100 special assessment.
   The restitution will cover the cost of maintenance personnel, use
of a bulldozer, forklift and trucks and other expenses of
recovering, sorting and delivering, returning or destroying the tons
of mail he failed to deliver.
   The judge, however, disallowed $10,974 in restitution for the
salaries of postal supvervisory personnel assigned to the case.
   Ryan, a 15-year postal employee, for the past three years had
been working a rural route in Escambia County out of the main post
office in Pensacola. He was fired after his arrest.
   Postal inspectors said about 500 pieces of first class mail were
among the hoard of mainly third-class items. Ryan was charged with
failing to deliver 10 of the first-class items. Five of them were
tax notices from the Escambia property appraiser and the other five
were voter registration renewal cards from the county elections
supervisor.
   Ryan was allowed to plead guilty to two counts and, in exchange,
Alter dropped the other eight. Ryan could have received up to 10
years in prison and fines totaling $500,000 for the two charges he
admitted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
