<FIRST>u w AM-UraniumExposure 2ndLd-Writethru a0723 02-14 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uranium Exposure, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0723,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, State EPA Ban Personnel From Uranium Processing Plant</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 4 grafs new to UPDATE with state EPA also banning visits
to plant; Picks up 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``But the ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON (A) _ The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and its
counterpart at the state level have barred employees from visiting
the government's uranium processing facility in Ohio because of the
risk of exposure to radioactivity, officials said Tuesday.
   EPA Regional Administrator Valdas Adamkus, in a letter last week,
said tests showed agency personnel were exposed to uranium oxide
when they went to the Feed Materials Production Center at Fernald
and that no federal EPA personnel would go to the site ``until this
health risk can be satisfactorily addressed.''
   The Ohio EPA followed suit Tuesday, said spokesman Allan Franks.
   After meeting with federal officials, state EPA Director Richard
Shank ``as a precautionary measure ... ordered our people who do
routine work to stay away from the site until a regular monitoring
system is set up,'' Franks said.
   But the plant's operator said Tuesday the plant is safe and that
routine urine tests to detect exposure ensure that the workers are
protected.
   ``We don't know what lab EPA is using, but we have the utmost
confidence in our program,'' said William H. Kelley, spokesman for
Westinghouse Materials of Ohio, the contractor running the plant for
the Energy Department.
   ``We have no reason to doubt the reliability of our program,''
Kelley said. ``We think the plant is safe.''
   Spokeswoman Ann Rowan said Adamkus discussed the issue Tuesday
with Joseph La Grone, Oak Ridge Operations Manager for the Energy
Department, which is in charge of the plant. The two agreed to meet
again on the subject but no date was set.
   ``What we said in the letter still holds,'' Rowan said.
   La Grone has offered to have the Energy Department finance new
urine tests ``to determine whether there is truly a potential
personnel exposure problem or in fact a laboratory problem.''
   Adamkus' letter was obtained Tuesday by the investigative staff
of Rep. Tom Luken, D-Ohio, who said he was upset that the EPA didn't
notify Fernald workers about the uranium oxide exposure threat.
   ``The public is totally unprotected when the monitor bars its own
inspectors from the premises,'' he said.
   The plant in southwest Ohio, about 18 miles from Cincinnati, is a
deteriorating foundry that processes uranium for use in the
government's nuclear weapons or as fuel for reactors.
   The plant is the subject of a lawsuit on behalf of 14,000 people
who live or work near the plant and believe their health has been
threatened by radioactive discharges into the air and water.
   Stanley Chesley, an attorney in the $300 million class-action
lawsuit against former plant operator NLO, Inc., said the EPA letter
demonstrates the need to proceed with the suit.
   ``I think it's an example of the ongoing trauma that continues to
plague this plant,'' Chesley said from Cincinnati.
</TEXT>
