<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-48Hours Adv15   02-14 0849</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-48 Hours, Adv 15,0864</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, Feb. 15, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>`48 Hours' Turns Its Cameras on Homelessness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The genesis of the weekly CBS News program ``48
Hours'' was a riveting documentary called ``48 Hours on Crack
Street.''
   After a season on the air, ``48 Hours'' has fine-tuned its
unique, spot-documentary style and on Thursday takes on an equally
compelling subject _ homelessness. This installment of ``48 Hours''
produces some of its best reporting, camera work and editing yet.
   Correspondents Bernard Goldberg, Betsy Aaron, Harold Dow and
Harry Smith spent two days covering various aspects of the problem.
Their report is often touching, often enlightening, sometimes
depressing and ultimately inspiring. If this doesn't make you want
to go out and do something _ or at least lend a hand to the people
who do _ not much will.
   The story was covered in New York City, where a huge homeless
population finds it can live under the feet of a hardened populace
long accustomed to ducking beggars and stepping over derelicts.
   Goldberg spent his 48 hours with those with whom the rest of us
come into daily contact _ panhandlers and street people. ``Shorty''
takes Goldberg on a sometimes amusing trip through the subway
system, where he hops cars and announces to jaded passengers that he
is collecting funds to help the homeless. ``You gotta sell, and I'm
sellin' 'em,'' he tells Goldberg. On one train, Shorty is chagrined
to find he's competing with a guy in a monk's robe with a megaphone.
   But an hour of working the subway nets more than $22. As the
camera rolls, Goldberg asks Shorty _ ``just between you, me and the
people listening'' _ if he is really collecting money for the
homeless. Shorty, well aware of the camera, admits he's collecting
the money for himself.
   Cut to needy beggars. But also to a public that is suffering what
Goldberg calls ``compassion fatigue.'' A pathetic young, pregnant
woman begs coins from passers-by in Grand Central Terminal with
little luck. One well-to-do young woman buying a magazine walks
hurriedly away.
   ``Like you weren't even there,'' Goldberg whispers to the
pregnant woman.
   ``It don't feel too good,'' she says softly.
   Dow followed the final, sad journey of a young Polish immigrant,
from the street in Brooklyn where he succumbed to alcoholism and
froze to death, to his burial in a mass paupers' grave.
   Aaron went into the harrowing welfare hotels and produced some
heart-rending interviews with children who live in tiny rooms with
desperate parents and face possible death at the hands of strangers
outside. Aaron asks one young girl what she most fears most.
``Killing,'' the girl says.
   Aaron took a group of the children to a coffee shop and asked
them to tell her about their dream homes. The kids conjure up
poignant visions of big houses with swimming pools and backyards
filled with animals.
   Barry, a 13-year-old, left the hotels, he said, because his
mother and aunt did drugs. He lives on the streets, occasionally
bunking at the home of a friend. He writes poetry, but, he says,
trudging the streets with a small suitcase, ``There's a time when
you have to wonder which is better, life or death.''
   Before you're so depressed that your face hits the carpet, Harry
Smith provides a more uplifting report on a successful halfway
house, jointly operated by the government and a millionaire
businessman, Leonard Stern. There, 400 lucky families get shelter,
assistance and child care. Mary Scott had been living in a flophouse
near Times Square before getting a spot in the halfway house. Smith
took Mrs. Scott back to Times Square at night to talk about what it
had been like living there. Walking down the street, they encounter
a young, homeless woman. Mrs. Scott tries to tell the woman that
she, too, had been homeless and things could get better. Then, she
unexpectedly bursts into tears and hugs the woman. It's a subtle
testimonial that the only real solution is caring.
   Dan Rather concludes the broadcast with the results of a CBS-New
York Times poll in which 65 percent of those surveyed said they
thought government should do more to help the homeless.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   UNLESS THEY'VE BEEN SITTING TOO CLOSE TO THE TELEVISION _ Why are
grisly, true-life dramas so popular as made-for-TV movie fare? NBC
Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff says it's because
``reality is the most identifiable commodity for the mass
audience.'' ...
   SO, EDDIE, YOU'VE COME CRAWLING BACK? _ Hardly. Big-time movie
star Eddie Murphy returns to the small screen Feb. 27 in a cameo
appearance on a CBS special, ``What's Alan Watching?'' produced by
Murphy's company. Corin ``Corky'' Nemec, Barbara and Peter Michael
Goetz star in the satire on television, as seen through the eyes of
a 17-year-old. George Carlin, the Smothers Brothers and Shelley
Berman guest star. The special was written and directed by some of
Murphy's old ``Saturday Night Live'' chums.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Feb. 15</NOTE>
