<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks betwen the Episcopal Church and the
Evangelical Lutheran Church in America have passed a milestone in
their work toward full communion, participants say.
   The Lutheran co-chairman, retired Illinois Bishop Paul E.
Eirckson, said the talks passed their midpoint with recent issuance
of an agreed report, ``Implications of the Gospel.''
   Episcopal Bishop William G. Weinhauer of Western North Carolina,
Episcopal co-chairman, said accords must now be sought about the
ministry and bishops.
   ``What we're doing is rolling up our sleeves to get going on
those two points.''
   The two denominations now have a compact on ``interim
communion,'' allowing for it on special occasions.
