<FIRST>r f PM-ToyBoxintheSky Bjt   02-14 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toy Box in the Sky, Bjt,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Inhumanoids: Victims Of The Toy Wars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbie turns 30 years old this week. G.I. Joe
marches on at 25. But Mr. Game Show? The Inhumanoids?
   Flops.
   ``There are a lot of flops,'' toy company analyst Walter
Kirchberger said Monday, the start of the industry's weeklong Toy
Fair. ``Something like 80 percent of the new-toy introductions turn
out to be flops.''
   That makes this Flop Week in the toy business. Manufacturers have
packed their Manhattan showrooms with an estimated 5,000 new games
and toys, all clamoring for slices of a nearly $13 billion pie.
   Most won't last. ``You'll see a lot of products at the Toy Fair
this week that you won't see next year,'' said Harold Vogel, an
analyst for Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. ``Most toys do not make it into a
second season.''
   One reason, said Vogel: ``There's lots of junk.''
   Quality's not the sole criterion; some entries are undone by
outrageous circumstance alone. ``The Evel Knievel doll did very well
when it came out. Then it just fell apart,'' said Vogel. He guessed
that the real Knievel's conviction of a baseball-bat assault did not
help the toy.
   Other casualties are harder to explain. Barbie dances on the
grave of a pretender named Gem. G.I. Joe's tough as ever. But the
Inhumanoids _ a toady group from the center of the Earth _ withered
in the light of day.
   No one knows why.
   ``That is the $64 million question in the toy industry. And in
most other industries,'' said Kirchberger, of Paine Webber Group.
``Nobody sets out to make a bad movie. It just happens. It's the
same thing with toys.''
   Toy makers trim losses by making models of most new items,
holding back on production until orders come in. ``The weeding-out
process starts early,'' said Jodi Levin, of the Toy Manufacturers of
America. ``Sometimes the kids don't even get to pass judgment.''
   But there have been some epic bombs. Mr. Game Show, a big hit at
last year's Toy Fair, is a goner now. Kirchberger gave the eulogy:
   ``It was modeled after a TV game show; there was a figure of a
host, he spoke, he'd ask you questions, you'd push buttons to
indicate your answer, he'd tell you if you were right or wrong and
how much you won. Very clever. Wrong price point, wrong
I-don't-know-what. Mr. Game Show didn't make it.''
   Then there was Michael Jackson's Zoo from View-Master Ideal, a
menagerie of stuffed animals inspired by the rock star's
predilection for offbeat pets.
   ``He even went on tour with his chimp. So we tried,'' said
View-Master's Jeremy Jacobs. ``We had the chimp appearing in stores
in Southern California. We had quite a few good promotions, but we
just couldn't move the product.''
   Or consider Golden Girl and the Guardian of the Gemstones. ``The
concept was action figures for little girls. There were 12 beautiful
female warriors with shields and swords,'' said David Galoob, of
Lewis Galoob Toys Inc.
   ``The trade bought in very, very heavily. And what we discovered
was that little girls didn't want to play with warrior figurines,''
Galoob recalled. ``It was a tremendous stiff.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 0121EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-EmerySale Bjt   02-14 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emery Sale, Bjt,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emery Sale Follows Company's Long Decline, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lary in 16th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts say Consolidated Freightways Inc.
faces a major challenge in trying to turn around troubled Emery Air
Freight Corp., which it is acquiring in a deal worth an estimated
$230 million.
   ``They have their work cut out for them,'' David Guthrie, an
analyst with Morgan Keegan Co., said Monday after the announcement.
``It's possible they made a good investment; it's possible they made
a big mistake.''
   Consolidated announced it had agreed to buy all outstanding Emery
common stock for $7.75 a share in cash and all outstanding Emery
preferred stock for $21.10 a share in cash. Emery has about 24
million common shares and 1.1 million preferred shares outstanding.
   The agreement has been approved by the boards of directors of
both companies, said Consolidated, based in Menlo Park, Calif.
   The combination will make Consolidated one of the nation's
largest air-freight operators.
   Analysts said Emery never regained its competitive edge after a
series of strategic miscalculations over the past decade.
   The company, which lost $9.95 million on revenue of $318.8
million in the third quarter of 1988, took on more than $300 million
in debt to buy rival Purolator Courier Corp. in 1987.
   Although analysts roundly criticized the $348 million Purolator
purchase, Emery's problems really began when it waited until 1982 to
purchase its own planes and adopt the hub-and-spoke distribution
system used by industry leader Federal Express Corp., Guthrie said.
   Before then, Emery shipped freight on commercial airlines.
   ``Essentially they waited too long and let Federal Express steal
a substantial part of the market,'' Guthrie said. ``From that point
on, they were never able to catch up.''
   Consolidated and Emery specialize in shipping large packages and
freight that Federal Express, an overnight package-delivery service,
generally does not handle.
   Paul Schlesinger, an analyst with Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette,
said he thought Consolidated paid too much for Emery, ``because
there's so little in the way of hard assets that Emery still owns.''
He noted that Emery sold its fleet of planes on a lease-back
arrangement in order to raise cash.
   ``It's going to be complicated to turn that thing around,''
Schlesinger said.
   Emery, based in Wilton, Conn., was founded in 1946 by John Emery
Sr. When his son, John C. Emery Jr., who started as a truck driver
with the company, suddenly announced his retirement as chairman and
chief executive officer in December 1987, analysts saw it as an
indication that the company was positioning itself to be sold.
   Emery Jr. was replaced by William F. Souders, a board member who
had no previous experience in the air freight industry.
   The combined company will operate under the name ``Emery
Worldwide, a CF Company,'' said Lary Scott, president of
Consolidated.
   ``We have every confidence that this business combination will
offer customers the best service available,'' Souders said in a
statement.
   Consolidated does business in long-haul trucking, air freight,
regional trucking, and rail piggyback and ocean intermodal services.
Its 1988 revenues totaled $2.7 billion.
   Emery provides air courier and cargo service and has 17,000
employees worldwide.
   Consolidated said it plans to centralize operations in Dayton,
Ohio, where Emery operates its ``superhub.'' About 1,700 people are
employed at the hub.
   Emery spokeswoman Jennifer Davis said Consolidated plans business
as usual at the hub, with no changes in job levels at this time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 0133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;L-InterestRates Bjt   02-14 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;L-Interest Rates, Bjt,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Higher Interest Rates Will Raise Cost Of S&amp;L Bailout</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY36 of Feb. 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The savings and loan industry, hypersensitive to
high interest rates, is being squeezed by a rise in rates that is
likely to drive more thrifts into insolvency and raise the cost to
taxpayers of the Bush administration's proposed $90 billion federal
bailout.
   `Increases in interest rates will have a substantial impact on
the number of savings and loans which will fall into the category of
either weakened or insolvent thrifts,'' Kevin Gottlieb, staff
director of the Senate Banking Committee, said Monday.
   When interest rates rise, thrifts have to pay higher rates to
hold and attract deposits. The money they earn on their
variable-rate mortgage loans also rises, but not as much or as
quickly.
   Each percentage point rise in interest rates will add about $6
billion to the cost of the S&amp;L bailout, according to estimates by
SNL Securities of Hoboken, N.J.
   That estimate includes the higher rates the government will have
to pay on the bonds it plans to issue to fund the bailouts.
   The estimate does not include the likelihood that higher rates
will push more S&amp;Ls into insolvency, the firm says. Thrifts with
more red ink on their books also will cost more to bail out.
   ``Taxpayers will foot a much larger proportion of the bill than
what's being announced. It may be double, even,'' said Jim Marks,
publisher of SNL Quarterly Thrift Digest.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills _ an alternative to S&amp;L
certificates of deposit for big investors _ have shot up to 8.8
percent from 5.6 percent a year ago.
   Edward J. Kane, a professor at Arizona State University, said
Monday that according to a stricter accounting standard than the one
used by the government, 750 thrifts were insolvent by last
September. Since then, rising interest rates have helped push
another 50 to 100 into their ranks, he said.
   Higher interest rates have caused a hemorrhage of thrift
deposits. Net deposit withdrawals rose in December to a record of
more than $8 billion, the Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Friday.
Total deposits were about $972 billion.
   Some thrifts have concluded it is not financially worthwhile to
raise their rates on deposits high enough to keep all their
depositors.
   With fewer deposits, the thrifts have less money available to
make new mortgage loans, but they would rather shrink and remain
profitable.
   Because deposits are counted as liabilities on the books, thrifts
can actually improve their net worth by allowing deposits to bleed
away, said Edwin Gray, president of Chase Federal Bank in Miami and
former chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   A silver lining in the S&amp;L crisis is that thrifts are somewhat
better prepared to cope with high interest rates now than they were
in the early 1980s, the last time interest rates soared. Most
mortgages in their portfolios have adjustable rates, so mortgage
payments rise when rates rise.
   In September 1981, only about 29 percent of thrifts' mortgages
had adjustable rates. As of this past September, the proportion was
74 percent, according to James Barth, chief economist of the Federal
Home Loan Bank Board.
   Stuck with fixed-rate mortgages and soaring short-term interest
rates, 85 percent of thrifts were unprofitable in 1981, Barth said.
As of September, the proportion of unprofitable thrifts was 30
percent, he said.
   Some thrifts also have taken steps to protect themselves from
interest-rate fluctuations by raising some of their money through
issuing bonds instead of taking in deposits.
   When interest rates rise, the thrifts don't have to raise
payments on their bonds, while they do have to raise payments on
their deposits. As of last September, about 11 percent of thrifts'
capital came from borrowings such as bond issues, up from 3 percent
in 1980, Barth said.
   Troubled thrifts have a harder time using such defensive
strategies. It costs more for them to issue bonds and they have to
have them fully backed with collateral.
   Also, troubled thrifts cannot easily afford to offer the
incentives that would cause customers to choose adjustable-rate
mortgages instead of fixed-rate mortgages, Gray said.
   Troubled institutions, which have the highest proportion of
mortgage loans that aren't being paid, are squeezed the worst by
rising rates. Their cost of funds is rising along with everyone
else's but they have less of an offsetting gain on their loan
portfolios.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 0139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-FarmScene     02-14 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bergland Says Bush Playing Reagan on Farm Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is jeopardizing the quality of
life in rural America by following the ``failed ideological
policies'' of his predecessor, says co-op leader and former
agriculture secretary Bob Bergland.
   ``He follows an incredibly popular president _ one who cut taxes,
talked frugally but spent freely, and who then placed all the blame
on either Jimmy Carter or the Congress,'' Bergland said Monday.
   ``Today's unconscionable and unnecessary savings and loan crisis,
which one way or the other will cost American consumers $100
billion, could have been averted had the Reagan administration
approached deregulation more thoughtfully,'' he said.
   Rural areas have problems, too, including ``strangulation of our
air transportation options, thousands of miles of roads and bridges
that are crumbling,'' and huge gaps in television service, Bergland
said.
   ``We, too, live with illiteracy, the homeless, rising health care
costs,'' he said. ``We share many of the challenges of city life.''
   Bergland is executive vice president and general manager of the
National Rural Electric Cooperative Association. More than 11,000
representatives of local cooperatives are attending an annual
meeting here through Wednesday.
   Plans of recent years to overhaul the federal power program,
including the possible sale of some large facilities to private
interests, also came in for criticism.
   Bergland, who spoke at the opening day's session, is a former
member of Congress and was secretary of agriculture during the
Carter administration.
   The delegates represent 1,000 consumer-owned rural electric
systems which serve an estimated 25 million people in 46 states. The
co-op system was started in the 1930s and used federal loans from
the Rural Electrification Administration, or REA, to put electricity
on the nation's farms.
   Critics have contended for years that the job is done and that
it's time to abolish REA and put rural power co-ops into the private
domain. However, advocates contend the task continues and federal
support is needed to maintain, upgrade and expand facilities.
   Bergland said Bush has ``rubber stamped Ronald Reagan's last
budget proposals for REA,'' an agency of the Agriculture Department.
The plan would shift from loan guarantees by the Federal Financing
Bank to REA guarantees for private loans.
   ``REA is a lending program, not a spending program,'' he said.
``The truth of the matter is that nowhere in the federal budget for
REA or the U.S. Department of Agriculture are you given any credit
for the money you pay back on your loans each year. What does show
up, as spending, are the loan levels for the fiscal year.''
   Bergland said that last fiscal year the U.S. Treasury ``realized
$4 billion more than it advanced'' to the nation's rural electric
systems.
   ``And once again, the forces that have sought to dismantle the
federal power system and drive up rates on power generated from
federal projects have triumphed,'' he said. ``There is little
difference, if any, between the Bush administration proposals and
those of the Reagan administration.''
   Bergland said he is not convinced that the United States would be
better served ``by turning federal power over to profit-driven
private interests.''
   He added: ``There is no basis, except for an ideological one, for
dismantling the power marketing agencies and artificially boosting
federal power rates to so-called `market levels,' and we will oppose
any such moves with all our strength.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
