<FIRST>r f PM-ToyFair Bjt   02-14 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toy Fair, Bjt,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toymakers Reveal How They Will Tempt Kids, Frustrate Parents This
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Caution: Letting children read this may be
hazardous to household budgets. It contains pocketbook-sensitive toy
information.
   Thousands of toys are debuting this week at the industry's annual
bash in Manhattan and loads of old favorites are keeping them
company.
   From ultra-sophisticated computer gizmos to things as basic as
the abacus, the spotlight is shining on toys of every type
imaginable. Expensive toys that generous parents prefer to think of
as investments are on display along with low-priced items to please
more frugal gift-givers.
   Not all of the toys introduced with much fanfare at the American
International Toy Fair will earn a place for themselves on store
shelves.
   Their fate depends on how good an impression they make on the
throng of previewers attending the trade show during its 10-day
engagement.
   But the store buyers and industry analysts who traditionalIy
crowd into the Toy Center on Fifth Avenue each year don't always
perceive the potential popularity of new toys. The final arbiters
are customers, particularly children _ the ficklest consumers of all.
   Here's a selection of just a few new toys and games and
enhancements of existing ones being touted at Toy Fair:
   _To capitalize on the current video game craze, several
manufacturers have developed accessories for the Nintendo
Entertainment System. Broderbund Software Inc. has come up with
something called U-Force, which recalls paraphernalia in Flash
Gordon films. It allows Nintendo game players to control activity on
the screen through motion of their bodies within a ``force field.''
   _The doll category has numerous competitors, including ones with
attributes such as speech or motion. Some have hair that changes
color in the sun.
   Mattel Inc.'s Barbie is embedded in the bedrock of the toy
business and is going strong in her 30th year. In her 1989
incarnation, she boasts more glamorous outfits and hair with a
memory so that even the most intricate coiffeurs will endure until
the next styling.
   Tyco Toys Inc.'s Oopsie Daisy doll has been a big hit in Canada,
so the company thinks it stands a good chance in the United States.
Modeled after a 9-month-old infant, she crawls on her hands and
knees and can turn her head.
   People with athletic aspirations may be interested in the Flo-Jo
doll, inspired by Olympic champion Florence Griffith Joyner, from
LJN Toys Ltd. The doll comes with applique fingernails; long,
painted nails are one of the athlete's trademarks.
   _Militaristic toys have supporters. Despite a 25 percent decline
in sales of action figures last year, G.I. Joe proved to be a sturdy
fellow and will be promoted again in 1989, his 25th year of
make-believe missions.
   Hasbro Inc. says Pentagon experts gave guidance in the
development of the company's new Flying Fighters. These hand-held
mock jets, modeled after the F-14 Tomcat and other military
aircraft, make realistic engine, radar lock-up and gunfire sounds.
Each Flying Fighter comes with pictures of the actual members of the
squadrons flying the genuine jets.
   _Radio-controled vehicles have had a large following. Tyco says
its Turbo Typhoon Hovercraft is the first vehicle to operate both on
land and water. The craft can travel at speeds up to 17 miles per
hour on a cushion of air-inflated pontoons.
   _The games class has numerous new entrants, many for grown-ups.
   Several educational games are being introduced, including Suntex
International Inc.'s Twenty-Four, which takes a fun approach to
improving players' mathematical skills.
   A game called Adverteasing from Cadaco, a division of Rapid
Mounting &amp; Finishing Co., should appeal to anyone with a knack for
remembering slogans and jingles, while the Headlines Game, from U.S.
Playing Card Co., tests players' abilities to come up with concise,
catchy summaries of subjects.
   Billionaire developer Donald Trump is pitching a real estate
board game on behalf of Milton Bradley. But if the ups and downs of
real financial markets get too confusing, people can take a quick
remedial course by playing Bulls and Bears, a game developed by
economist Mario Fischel.
   If the wide selection of toys and games hitting the market each
year depresses those who feel they can't afford to keep up with
what's new, they can turn to It's Only Money. Created by
Lobsenz-Stevens Inc., the game takes players on a shopping spree
through a mall and it offers them a real-life opportunity to win
$400,000 in actual prizes.
</TEXT>
