<FIRST>r f PM-MissingStockbroker     02-14 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Stockbroker,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stockbroker Reported Missing with Millions in Clients' Funds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators are searching for a Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. stockbroker who allegedly disappeared with
millions of dollars after going on a golfing trip earlier this
month, according to a report published today.
   Unidentified brokerage sources said Walter F. Curran, 45, of
Wellesley, convinced clients to invest between $5 million and $10
million directly with him, rather than with the firm, The Boston
Globe reported today.
   Curran reportedly told his colleagues he was going on an
out-of-state golfing trip and has not contacted his wife since.
   Jack Cloherty, a spokesman for the FBI, said federal
investigators have been working to trace Curran's steps since last
week.
   In the weeks leading up to his disappearance, Curran reportedly
stopped making payments on $475,000 in personal loans from the Bank
of Boston and apparently made a series of deposits and withdrawals
to his account that investigators are studying.
   Marty Meehan of the state Securities Division said Dean Witter
Reynolds may have violated a state law by not notifying state
officials of the case until Monday.
   ``They were aware of the situation a week ago,'' he said. ``We're
concerned about the failure of a major brokerage firm to promptly
notify us of a potential violation of the law by one of their
registered brokers,'' he said.
   Fellow brokers described Curran as one of the office's top money
makers. He joined the Boston office in February 1981.
</TEXT>
