<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-USX-Kobe     02-14 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USX-Kobe,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>USX, Kobe of Japan Join Hands At Lorain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. said today it plans to establish a
joint venture with Kobe Steel Ltd. of Japan to operate the U.S.
company's specialty bar and tubular products plant at Lorain, Ohio.
   Each partner will own 50 percent of the joint venture, which will
buy the Lorain plant and become the new employer of the
approximately 3,000 workers who operate the plant.
   USX withheld the proposed purchase price in a printed statement.
   The deal will be the first investment in the U.S. steel industry
for Kobe, Japan's leading producer of steel bar products.
   A Kobe official in Tokyo said the partnership will help the
company adjust to steel product requirements of Japanese vehicle
makers in the United States.
   Steel bar is used to produce a variety of heavy components for
cars, trucks and machinery.
   ``This brings together the premier integrated bar producers of
the United States and Japan to create a business second to none in
the world's quality bar industry,'' said Thomas C. Graham, president
of the USS division of USX, the nation's largest steelmaker.
   ``The venture will continue and expand current modernization
activities at the plant to enhance quality and service to bar
customers,'' he said. ``A major thrust will be to increase the
plant's sales to the automotive industry, including the Japanese and
other foreign-owned automotive plants around the nation.''
   USX said further improvements at Lorain could include the
installation of a continuous bloom caster, a machine that molds
molten steel for further processing. Casters are considered almost
essential equipment for the efficient production of consistently
high-quality steel.
   The Lorain plant's two seamless pipe mills and a blast furnace
are now undergoing improvements worth $50 million.
   USX will continue to market Lorain's tubular products, while the
joint venture company will market the bar products.
   The Lorain Works has been the only bar making operation at USX
since the company reorganized its steel division in 1987. Lorain's
seamless tube production is considered part of the three-plant
Pittsburgh Works.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
