<HEAD>ConAgra-Holly Farms Set New Dates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ConAgra Inc. and Holly Farms Corp. have set
new record dates for shareholders' meetings in connection with the
proposed $1 billion merger of the two companies.
   Only stockholders owning stock in the two companies on or before
Feb. 23 can vote and attend special meetings on the merger, the
companies said Monday.
   The companies said their respective meetings would be sometime in
late March.
   Earlier, the companies had set Jan. 23 as the record date, but
they changed it because of what they said were delays.
   The boards of Omaha-based ConAgra and Holly Farms of Memphis,
Tenn., have agreed to merge the two companies to form the nation's
largest poultry producer.
   Tyson Foods Inc. of Springdale, Ark., now the nation's largest
poultry company, also has been trying to purchase Holly Farms.
   Tyson said it has extended until 4 p.m. Friday its $60-per-share
cash tender offer for Holly Farms.
   Tyson also said it has made Holly another offer, this one in the
form of a proposal to the Holly Farms board, of $63.50 per share.
   The Holly Farms board has recommended its shareholders accept the
ConAgra offer, under which the Omaha company would swap ConAgra
stock for Holly Farm stock.
