<FIRST>r f PM-Carlyle-Fairchild     02-14 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carlyle-Fairchild,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fairchild To Conduct Internal Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHANTILLY, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fairchild Industries Inc. said today was
conducting its own investigation of allegations of non-compliance
with required testing procedures at one of its aerospace fasteners
plants.
   The defense contracting firm said the allegations against its
Vol-Shan-Chatsworth aerospace division located in Culver City,
Calif., were made by a former employee who claimed substandard work
was being done at the facility.
   Last week the FBI announced it was investigating Vol-Shan for
what it called possible falsification of quality control records at
the California plant.
   Despite the investigation, Carlyle Group, a Washington-based
investment group, said Monday it was not abandoning its unsolicited
$230 million takeover bid for the Chantilly, Va., company.
   ``We're still interested in Fairchild, but we're putting the
market on notice that we have to evaluate all of our options in
light of recent events,'' Carlyle managing partner Stephen L. Norris
told The Washington Times.
   Carlyle currently owns nearly 10 percent of Fairchild's
outstanding stock, making it the company's largest public
shareholder.
</TEXT>
