<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean, Corn Futures Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for soybeans and corn were higher
while wheat prices fell slightly in early trading today on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Supporting soybeans were talk of renewed demand in Europe and a
feeling that the futures market has been oversold lately, analysts
said.
   Recent export figures were encouraging buying in the corn pit,
traders said. Monday's U.S. Agriculture Department report of exports
for last week listed 45.8 million bushels of corn _ on the high side
of expectations.
   Meanwhile, analysts said recent rains in Midwest growing areas
held down wheat prices.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.24 a bushel; corn was { cent to
1{ cents higher, with March at $2.66{ a bushel; oats were 2 cents to
3\ cents, with March at $2.06\ a bushel; and soybeans were 2 cents
to 4 cents higher, with March at $7.27{ a bushel.
   Cattle prices were steady to slightly lower but pork complex
futures mostly rose on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, cattle were .20 cent lower to .10 cent higher,
with the contract for delivery in February at 74.70 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were unchanged to .30 cent lower, with March at 82.55
cents a pound; live hogs were .13 cent to .75 cent higher, with
February at 42.17 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .62
cent lower to .55 cent higher, with February at 38.60 cents a pound.
   On Monday, feeder cattle prices were higher and other livestock
and meat futures mixed.
</TEXT>
