<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Bush-Budget 1stLd-Writethru   02-14 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Resists Call for More Specifics on Spending</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New 6th graf, In an ..., with Bush quotes from interview.
A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administration held fast today against
demands from congressional Democrats that it come up with more
specifics to cover gaps in President Bush's new $1.16 trillion
budget.
   Bush's press secretary, Marlin Fitzwater, said spending cuts
would have to be the product of negotiations with Congress. ``This
budget is alive and is an active force subject to change in
negotiation and discussion,'' he said.
   Fitzwater indicated that the administration did not plan to issue
proposals for more specific cuts beyond those proposed in the
blueprint for the 1990 fiscal year unveiled last week.
   Some congressional Democrats have contended that Bush's budget
enables him to get credit for proposing more spending on social
programs like child care, education and environmental cleanup _
while making sure Congress shares the responsibility for cuts to
help pay for these programs.
   Bush's budget, apart from proposing a freeze on defense spending
at the rate of inflation, was vague on where other specific areas of
spending would be restrained to meet deficit targets.
   In an interview published in today's editions of The Wall Street
Journal, the president said ``what we tried to do is simply put
forward in a broad sense, in a short period of time, priorities. ...
And now there's two approaches _ one is the Congress can say here's
what we'll do, or two, they can have negotiations with the White
House.''
   The president generally called for freezing most domestic
programs at 1989 levels. However, that would leave a $9.6 billon to
$11 billion gap in the fiscal year that begins Oct. 1 if the
programs are merely allowed to keep pace with inflation and
population growth.
   ``The numbers speak for themselves,'' Fitzwater told reporters.
``Nothing is final and we'll be negotiating all of these programs.''
   Budget director Richard G. Darman and White House Chief of Staff
John Sununu were to meet this afternoon with congressional budget
leaders to work out ground rules for more intensive talks to come in
the days ahead.
   ``We'll be providing details as we go along ... Everybody knows
cuts have to be made,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said today's meeting, following one Monday between Darman and
leaders of the House and Senate Budget committees, was part of a
process of ``clearing away the underbrush.''
   Although the budget has already stirred controversy in the
Democratic-controlled Congress, Fitzwater said ``we don't want the
budget to be confrontational'' and that the administration would
retain ``an open mind'' on spending cuts.
   Bush on Monday opened a series of talks around the country to
promote his budget plan. He travels to Columbia, S.C., on Wednesday
to highlight his budget goals before a joint session of the state
legislature.
   Fitzwater denied that Bush's budget travels were an effort to
make an end-run around Congress, as former President Reagan had done
in building public support for some of his initiatives.
   Rather, the spokesman said, said the trips were just ``an
opportunity for the president to discuss his priorities'' and an
attempt to stress his intention ``to work with Congress.''
   Bush won initial plaudits from Democrats and Republicans alike
for the budget plan he outlined last week in his maiden speech to a
joint session of Congress last Thursday.
   But some of the warmth of that reception cooled as budget
analysts combed through the document itself and found details were
scarce on how the new social programs highlighted by the president
would be financed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
