<DOCNO> AP890214-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1253EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Goodyear     02-14 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Goodyear,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goodyear Reports Earnings Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Competitive pressure in domestic tire markets
contributed to a 66 percent drop in Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co.'s
fourth-quarter income, the company reported Tuesday.
   Goodyear reported after-tax earnings of $56.4 million, or 98
cents a share, on sales of $2.8 billion. In the corresponding 1987
quarter, Goodyear earned $167 million, or $2.92 per share, on sales
of $2.6 billion.
   The 1987 income included $47.6 million from discontinued
operations. In 1988's final quarter, the company took $26.8 million
in charges against earnings to cover the costs of voluntary employee
separations, a pension settlement and asset reversion.
   Goodyear's income for all of last year came to $350.1 million, or
$6.11 a share, down 55 percent from 1987's $770.9 million, or $12.73
a share. Sales amounted to $10.8 billion vs. $9.9 billion in the
same respective years. The 1987 total included $257 million in
income from discontinued Goodyear Aerospace, Motor Wheel and Celeron
Oil and Gas subsidiaries.
   Tom H. Barrett, Goodyear chief executive officer and president,
said the company experienced a 28.8 percent decline in operating
income in the United States in 1988, while its operating income in
its foreign businesses was up 40.8 percent.
</TEXT>
