<FIRST>r f AM-FiatStock     02-14 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fiat Stock,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fiat Listed On New York Stock Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian auto manufacturer Fiat SpA, which
recently entered a joint marketing agreement with Chrysler Corp.,
began trading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Fiat Chairman Giovanni Agnelli said his company, Italy's largest
private-sector corporation, is sizing up further deals in North
America and hopes to gain stature by being listed on the largest
U.S. exchange.
   ``The U.S. consumer market is of particular interest and
importance to us, as evidenced by the recent commercial agreement
concluded between Alfa Romeo and Chrysler,'' Agnelli said at an NYSE
ceremony.
   Fiat has entered a joint venture agreement with the No. 3 three
U.S. carmaker to market the Alfa Romeo 164 model in the United
States.
   Agnelli said he expects the New York listing to have a ``slightly
positive effect'' on Fiat stock. Company shares already are traded
in Milan, London, Frankfurt, Berlin and Paris, but Agnelli said he
has no current plans for a listing in Tokyo.
   Fiat last year reported a 23 percent earnings jump to $2.9
billion on revenue of $33.5 billion. Fiat sells automobiles,
tractors, commercial vehicles, earthmoving equipment and other
products in more than 150 countries, and operates 60 manufacturing
plants in 50 countries.
   Fiat shares are traded in New York in the form of American
Depository Receipts, with one ADR representing five original Fiat
ordinary shares. Preferred and non-voting stock also are listed.
</TEXT>
