million for the 1984 gas leak in Bhopal that killed more than 3,300
people. The sum was less than many investors had expected.
   Coleman soared 20} to 69~. The company said Sheldon Coleman, its
chief executive, proposed a buyout for $64 a share in cash and
preferred stock, and traders immediately began to speculate about
the chances for a higher bid.
   General Motors dropped 1} to 90. Analysts said it appeared that
traders who had bought the stock anticipating the company's strong
fourth-quarter earnings report sold after the numbers were issued
this morning.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.48 to 164.63. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.55 at 323.31.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 106.02 million shares with two
