<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-MovieAttendance     02-14 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Movie Attendance,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Box Office Revenues Gain 5 Percent in 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Box office revenues hit a record $4.46 billion
last year although movie attendance dropped slightly, the president
of the Motion Picture Association of America told theater owners
Tuesday.
   ``In spite of competition for the eye and ear of the American
consumer, in spite of an avalanche of visual options, the movie
theater has not only refused to die, it has held firm,'' Jack
Valenti told the opening session of SHOWEST.
   Theater admissions totaled 1.085 billion in 1988, Valenti said,
the 12th straight year attendance topped the one billion. The
attendance figure was down 0.03 percent from 1987, Valenti said,
while revenues rose 5 percent.
   Valenti told theater owners they are in a ``watching war'' with
90 million television households across America that tune in an
average of 49 hours a week.
   ``In the last 10 years, there has grown a veritable new nation
with 49 million homes wired to cable, 37 million pay cable
subscriptions and some 19 million homes capable of receiving pay per
view,'' he said. ``There are over 56 million VCR households and one
out of five has more than one VCR.
   ``As alternate delivery systems invade the American living room,
the conventional wisdom was and is `the cinema is bound to die.'''
   But the movie industry has held firm despite predictions of its
demise, Valenti said.
   The United States recorded a per capita movie attendance of 4.4
last year, compared to Canada with 2.8, France and West Germany 1.9,
Italy 1.6 and Great Britain 1.4.
   Valenti said the over-40 age group represents a growing portion
of theater attendance. Two years ago, the over-40 market accounted
for 14 percent of theater admissions. In 1988, that share rose to
22.3 percent.
   Valenti said he is not concerned about the dwindling number of
theater chains that own a growing number of movie houses.
   ``That only becomes a problem when competition is being
starved,'' Valenti said. ``The exhibition business is highly
competitive.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
