<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0204</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for soybeans and corn rose sharply
while wheat prices were mixed at the close Tuesday on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
   Soybean prices climbed at least 12 cents for the three contracts
pegged for delivery in March, May and July.
   Supporting soybeans were talk of renewed demand for soy products
in Europe, and a feeling that the futures market has been oversold
lately, analysts said.
   Decent export figures were encouraging buying in the corn pit,
traders said.
   ``There also were rumors of new Russian interest in the corn
market,'' said Steve Freed, grain analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   Recent rains in Midwest growing areas held down prices on wheat,
said research director Jerry Gidel of LIT America Inc.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents lower to 1{ cents higher, with
the contract for delivery in March at $4.23\ a bushel; corn was }
cent to 4\ cents higher, with March at $2.69{ a bushel; oats were 4\
cents to 5\ cents, with March at $2.09\ a bushel; and soybeans were
7 cents to 12{ cents higher, with March at $7.36{ a bushel.
