<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0191</SECOND>
<UNK>London Shares Close Higher, But Off Peak</UNK>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed higher but below their session
peaks Tuesday, lifted by some heavy futures-related buying and a
strong early trend on Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 16.4
points, or 0.8 percent, higher at 2,049.1, having traded as much as
21 points higher during the afternoon. But the index recovered
strongly from the morning low of 6.1 points down, which came soon
after the market opening.
   Volume was a moderate 534.1 million shares, up from 474.5 million
shares a day earlier.
   The trend in New York helped the London market recover its poise
following a heavy drop Monday prompted by worries about high British
interest rates and inflationary pressures on the British and world
economy.
   Analysts cautioned that the overall market is still vulnerable to
further bad news on the inflation front.
   The London market was likely to remain ``a bit directionless''
until it has firm evidence that British interest rates are heading
lower again, said Kevin Gardiner, an analyst at the London
investment firm Warburg Securities.
