<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     02-14 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early February Sales Fall; Chrysler Cars Down Most</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of cars made in the United States by the
nation's Big Three automakers slumped 20.2 percent in early February
compared with the same period last year, when sales were unusually
strong, the companies said Tuesday.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. said they
sold cars at an average daily rate of 16,112 during the Feb. 1-10
period, compared with a rate of 20,182 during the same 1988 period.
   Trucks made in the United States by the Big Three sold at a daily
rate of 10,034, down 10.6 percent from 11,223 last year.
   Combined car and truck sales were off 16.8 percent during the
period. There were nine selling days in the 1988 and 1989 periods.
   During the early part of 1988, sales were abnormally high, due in
part to manufacturers returning to heavy use of incentives partly
because of fear that the stock market crash of October 1987 may have
kept car buyers out of showrooms.
   But that was an unnecessary concern, as the 1988 model year
proved to be the third best on record.
   Since the beginning of this year, the Big Three have sold cars
and trucks at a daily rate of 29,243, compared with a rate of 31,032
during the same period last year, a 5.8 percent decline. There were
34 selling days in both periods.
   Chrysler said its car sales skidded 30.9 percent during early
February, falling to a daily rate of 2,200 this year from a rate of
3,185 last year. Chrysler's truck sales suffered the least among the
Big Three, dropping 5.1 percent to a daily rate of 2,398 compared
with a rate of 2,528.
   So far this year, Chrysler's car sales are 13.6 percent lower
than they were in 1988, but truck sales are 7.7 percent ahead of
last year's pace.
   GM car sales fell 23 percent during early February, dropping to a
daily rate of 8,355 from a rate of 10,856. Trucks made by GM in the
United States sold at a rate of 4,040 during the first 10 days of
the month, down 13 percent from 4,643.
   For the year, GM has sold 14.3 percent fewer cars this year, and
2.3 percent fewer trucks.
   Ford said its early February car sales slipped 9.5 percent, to a
daily rate of 5,557 compared with a rate of 6,143. Truck sales by
Ford were off 11.3 percent, falling to a rate of 3,596 compared with
a rate of 4,053.
   Ford has sold 0.2 percent more cars and 0.7 percent more trucks
so far this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
