<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1854EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Reuters     02-14 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Reuters,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reuters Reports 22.4 Percent Gain In 1988 Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reuters Holdings PLC, the news and information
services group, said Tuesday its income rose 22.4 percent last year
despite weakness in world financial markets.
   The company said after-tax earnings totaled $242.8 million in
1988, or $1.74 for each outstanding American depositary share, up
from 1987's $198.4 million, or $1.41 per ADS. One Reuters' ADS
represents three class B ordinary shares of the company's stock.
   Last year's profit did not include $13.3 million set aside to
cover the cost of closing Reuters' Long Island, N.Y.-based
manufacturing subsidiary, IDR Inc. There were no extraordinary items
in 1987.
   Revenue increased 15.7 percent to $1.82 billion in 1988 from
$1.57 billion in 1987. Growth in revenue was restrained by the
strong pound, cancellation of subcription services and a decline in
the sales of trading room systems, a company statement said.
   Before taxes, Reuters said its profit rose 20.5 percent to $390
million from $324 million.
   Reuters Managing Director Glen Renfrew said the company had
healthy profit growth despite the problems of world financial
markets in 1988 which ``remained nervous'' in the aftermath of the
October 1987 stock market crash.
   Gross new orders for core information and dealing products
remained near record levels, Renfrew said, and large numbers of new
subscribers were signed up. On the other hand, cancellations were
heavy, he said.
   Net new orders, after cancellations, ``remained below the peaks
of 1987 throughout the year but high enough to produce good revenue
growth,'' Renfrew said.
   The company said it slashed 550 jobs in its cost-cutting efforts
last year, bringing the total number of employees to 10,064. Forty
to 50 job cuts were in the editorial division, it said.
   Reuters released the results at its corporate headquarters in
London and at the New York office of the company's U.S. subsidiary,
Reuters America Inc. The company does not break out quarterly or
half-year figures. It isn't required to under British law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
