<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1912EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-NorthropSuit     02-14 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northrop Suit,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northrop Sues Over Payments To South Koreans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. is suing a Honolulu businessman to
recover $6.25 million allegedly paid to him and several South Korean
associates to finance a hotel and office complex in Seoul that was
never built.
   According to the suit filed Friday in U.S. District Court, the
money was paid to James Shin from 1984-86 to assist ``Northrop's
business activities in Korea.''
   The aircraft manufacturer also has filed a civil lawsuit in South
Korea to recover the money, which Northrop says was paid into a
Korea Exchange Bank account in Hong Kong and disappeared.
   U.S. government investigators say the money may be part of about
$7.75 million allegedly paid by Northrop to help sell its ill-fated
F-20 fighter jet.
   The payments are being investigated by a federal grand jury in
Los Angeles, where Northrop is based, by a U.S. congressional
committee and by the government of South Korea. The government is
trying to determine if the Northrop payments violated the U.S.
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.
   Shin, 51, the former operator of a Honolulu nightclub, has been
unreachable for comment.
   Northrop's suit alleges that Shin secretly received a $1 million
check fron the Hong Kong bank account in August 1984. At the time
Shin allegedly was employed as an overseas aircraft sales consultant
for Northrop at a salary of $8,500 per month, plus expenses.
</TEXT>
