<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1720EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-USX-Kobe Bjt   02-14 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX-Kobe, Bjt,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint Venture Rounds Out U.S. Links For Japan Steelmakers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. and Kobe Steel Ltd. of Japan
announced a joint venture Tuesday, the latest in a series of
partnerships combining the best of two worlds to solve the problems
of both.
   Kobe, the last of Japan's big integrated steelmakers to join with
a comparable U.S. producer, will pay an undisclosed sum to buy half
of USX's Lorain, Ohio, plant.
   The deal is at least the 11th joint venture completed or under
consideration. It leaves only Bethlehem Steel Corp., the
third-largest U.S. producer, without a partner from the Far East.
   ``The U.S. market is probably more attractive than it ever has
been,'' said John Jacobson of AUS Consultants of Philadelphia.
   Analysts said the Japanese are entering joint ventures because
steel import quotas and unfavorable currency exchange rates have
made it difficult for foreigners to penetrate American markets.
   ``It's either lose it or buy into it,'' said Donald Barnett, an
independent analyst.
   The Japanese also face increased competition at home from
low-cost steelmakers in Korea, Taiwan and other developing countries.
   In the United States, companies view the well-financed Japanese
as a source of capital _ the perfect tonic for mills that were
staved of cash during the industry's 1982-86 depression. The
Japanese also bring expertise in producing high-quality steel for
the autos, the biggest single end use of the metal.
   ``I'd have to say it's a win-win situation,'' said Jacobson.
   Both countries see the joint ventures as improving the chances of
selling steel to Japanese automakers that have transplanted
operations to America.
   ``When the transplants came over here almost everything was
produced in Japan. Anything sophisticated was even assembled in
Japan. Now a lot of that is being done in the U.S,'' said Charles
Bradford, an industry analyst for Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
   The partnership with Kobe gives USX an opportunity to pump money
into the Lorain Works and to possibly hedge its bets in the bar
market, analysts said. The Lorain plant, with 3,000 workers,
produces seamless pipe and high quality bar for vehicles and
machinery.
   Kobe may have been persuaded to gamble on the deal because
Lorain's bar is recognized as high quality, and bar prices have
surged 32 percent from $386 in the third quarter of 1986 to $510 in
the comparable 1988 period, Jacobson said.
   Kobe also owns Midrex Corp., the world's largest producer of
plants that produce iron by the short-cut direct reduction process.
   In other joint ventures in steel:
   _Nisshin Steel owns a 10 percent stake in Wheeling-Pittsburgh and
has a joint venture with Wheeling-Pitt in a sheet steel coating
plant.
   _NKK owns half of the flat-rolled producer National Steel Corp.
and is negotiating with National Intergroup to buy the other half.
   _Nippon and Inland are building a joint cold-rolling mill and say
they are considering a joint galvanizing line.
   _Sumitomo and LTV are partners in an electrogalvanizing line and
say they are considering a second line.
   _Kawasaki entered a joint venture with a Brazilian steelmaker in
buying California Steel, a West Coast flat roller. The Japanese
company also has agreed to buy 40 percent of Armco's eastern steel
division.
   _Pohang of Korea and USX jointly own a West Coast sheet steel
plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
