<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-14 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Declince</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures declined in light, uneventful
trading Tuesday as the market awaited fresh news to give it
direction.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the March contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, closed 17
cents lower at $17.42 a barrel after surging 48 cents on Monday.
Other contract months also settled lower.
   Among refined oil products traded on the exchange, unleaded
gasoline scheduled for March delivery ended down 0.82 cent at 47.33
cents a gallon. Domestic heating oil for March declined 0.79 cent to
end the day at 47.38 cents a gallon. Other contract months also
ended on the down side.
   Most energy prices opened firm but turned lower during the
session with little news to stir investors. Observers said volume
was light with many traders away this week for an international
petroleum conference in London.
   ``There was no news on either side of the market that I could see
all day,'' said Bob Baker, an analyst with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   Since Feb. 1, crude prices have fluctuated in the $17 trading
range, reflecting what analysts say are technical factors and
uncertainty among traders about the future of oil prices.
   Analysts said prices could remain volatile in the absence of
fresh news to give the market guidance and as investors await the
outcome of next week's meeting of non-OPEC oil producers. The group
has said it supports production cuts by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries but has not given any definitive
indication that it plans to reduce its own production to help
stabilize world oil prices.
   The group met last month without producing an agreement to cut
output.
</TEXT>
