<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     02-14 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Sharply, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped against most major currencies
Tuesday in a sell-off inspired in part by speculation the White
House may be at odds with the Federal Reserve Board over interest
rate policy.
   Gold prices were mixed. The Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a gold bid of $384.40 a troy ounce at 4 p.m. EST, down from
$385.20 an ounce late Monday.
   Dealers dumped dollars in favor of West German marks, reasoning
that evidence of rising inflation in that country might induce the
government to drive interest rates higher. Higher West German rates
would enhance returns on mark-denominated holdings.
   As trading wound down in New York, the dollar was reported at
1.84325 marks compared with 1.8677 late Monday.
   The dollar came under additional selling pressure as dealers
reacted to comments by President Bush in a Wall Street Journal
interview.
   Bush said he opposes further tightening in credit conditions to
combat inflation.
   Fred Barth, a first vice president at Prudential Bache Securities
Inc., said Bush's position seemed to differ with that of the central
bank even though the president said in the interview that he and Fed
Chairman Alan Greenspan are not ``far apart at all.''
   ``Some people were disturbed by President Bush's comments,''
Barth said. ``There may be a little friction between the White House
and the Federal Reserve.''
   The dollar selling snowballed. The currency's downward movement
triggered additional declines as it fell to levels at which dealers
had previously determined they would sell to avoid losses.
   News of a better than expected 0.6 percent rise in U.S. retail
sales in January did not affect the markets because the previously
reported figures for December showing a 0.2 percent rise were
revised to an 0.1 percent decline.
   In London, one British pound closed at $1.7588, more expensive
for buyers than Monday's late $1.7495.
   Later, in New York, a pound fetched $1.77375 vs. $1.7525 Monday.
   Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar closed at 127.20 Japanese yen, down
from 128.30 yen. In London late Tuesday the dollar traded higher at
127.37 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with levels late
Monday included: 126.305 Japanese yen, down from 128.07; 1.56325
Swiss francs, down from 1.58775; 1.1835 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1860; and 6.2715 French francs, down from 6.2855-85
   Other late rates for the dollar in Europe compared with Monday's
late rates: 1.8615 West German marks, down from 1.8705; 1.5815 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5895; 6.3325 French francs, down from 6.3650;
2.1015 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1120; 1,355.05 Italian lire, down
from 1,362.50; and, 1.1835 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1868.
   Gold bullion prices gained around $2 an ounce in European
dealings but fell in the United States.
   In London, gold closed at a bid $386.25 a troy ounce, up from
$384.25 late Monday. The late bid price in Zurich was $385.50, up
from $383.75.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
declined to $385.40 a troy ounce from $386.20 an ounce late Monday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $387.66 bid, down from
$388.68.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.83 bid a troy ounce,
up from $5.79. On New York's Comex, silver for current delivery
settled at $5.828 a troy ounce, up from $5.826 Monday.

</TEXT>
