<HEAD>Soybean, Corn Futures Up Sharply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean and corn futures rose sharply Tuesday on the Chicago
Board of Trade, bolstered by talk of overseas demand for both
commodities.
   In other markets, cattle futures mostly were lower, pork mostly
was higher, precious metals were mixed and energy futures mostly
were lower.
   Soybean futures soared at least 12 cents higher during the
session for the three contracts pegged for delivery in March, May
and July, then settled about 11 cents higher.
   Prices were supported by talk of renewed demand for soy products
in Europe and a feeling that the futures market has been oversold
lately, said Jerry Gidel, reserach director in Chicago of LIT
America Inc.
   Export figures Monday that were on the high side of expectations
encouraged buying in the CBOT corn pit, Gidel said.
   ``There also were rumors of new Russian interest in the corn
market,'' said Steve Freed, grain analyst in Chicago with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Recent rains in Midwest growing areas weighed on wheat futures
trading, traders said.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents lower to 1} cents higher, with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.23{ a bushel; corn was } cent
to 4\ cents higher, with March at $2.69} a bushel; oats were 4\
cents to 5{ cents higher, with March at $2.09 a bushel; and soybeans
were 6{ cents to 11\ cents higher, with March at $7.35\ a bushel.
   Cattle prices mostly were lower while pork complex futures mostly
were higher at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle prices were depressed by some profit talking following
gains on Monday and traders were under selling pressure due to
concerns of oversupply, said Paul Hare, an analyst with Linnco
Futures Inc.
   Higher than expected cash hog prices sent prices higher in the
pork complex, traders said.
   Cattle settled .88 cent lower to .05 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in February at 74.65 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .25 cent to .63 cent lower, with March at 82.25 cents a
pound; live hogs were unchanged to .75 cent higher, with February at
42.17 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .60 cent lower to
.25 cent higher, with February at 37.82 cents a pound.
   Gold prices slipped, but silver futures were up slightly on the
Commodity Exchange in New York.
   ``The dollar was down sharply today but that doesn't move the
precious metals. This indicates to me there is not a whole lot of
enthusiasm to own precious metals now,'' said John O'Connell,
manager of futures research in New York for Refco Inc.
   Gold settled 70 cents to 80 cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in February at $385.40 a troy ounce; and silver was .2
cents to .4 cents higher, with February at $5.82.8 a troy ounce.
   Energy prices fell on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Crude oil settled .17 cent to .27 cent lower, with the contract
for delivery in March at $17.42 a barrel; heating oil was .74 cent
to .79 cent lower, with March at 47.38 cents a gallon; and unleaded
gasoline was .30 cent higher to .82 cent lower, with March at 47.33
cents a gallon.
