<FIRST>r f AM-Pepperell     02-14 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepperell Stock Soars After Board Says It Talking With Several Suitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile giant West Point-Pepperell Inc. said
Tuesday it has had discussions with several parties but has received
no competing bids to Farley Inc.'s $1.53 billion tender offer.
   The hint of other offers and a possible extension of Wednesday's
bidding deadline, contained in a letter filed with the Securities
and Exchange Commission, sent Pepperell stock climbing for the
second straight day.
   Pepperell closed Tuesday at $58.25, up $1.25, in New York Stock
Exchange trading. On Monday, Pepperell stock rose $2 on rumors of a
possible $1.82 billion offer from Dominion Textile Inc., a Canadian
company.
   There also have been reports that Milliken &amp; Co., a closely held
Spartanburg, S.C., firm, and Pepperell management are considering
bids for the nation's largest publicly held textile company.
Pepperell manufactures such brands as Martex, Lady Pepperell, Utica
sheets and towels and Arrow shirts.
   The West Point-based company's SEC filing said it could get a
better deal than Farley's $52-per-share offer.
   Pepperell's board put the company up for sale Feb. 3, saying it
believed Farley's offer was too low. A Wednesday noon deadline for
offers ``may be changed, depending on events at the time,'' the
company said.
   Pepperell also said it would reveal the outcome of the auction
``only after an agreement in principle or definitive agreement is
entered into between the company and a prospective purchaser.''
   Pepperell has fought the bid by Chicago-based Farley, which
controls underwear manufacturer Fruit of the Loom Inc. and Acme Boot
Co.
   Farley bid $48 per share for Pepperell last October and most
recently increased the offer to $52 per share Feb. 1. The offer is
to expire at midnight Wednesday.
