<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1823EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SuperconductivityPatent     02-14 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Superconductivity Patent,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Netherlands' Akzo Claims First U.S. Superconductivity Patent To Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Akzo NV, a Dutch chemical company, Tuesday became
the first company from any nation to receive a U.S. patent in the
field of high-temperature superconductivity.
   Akzo upset a wide range of U.S., Japanese and European companies
that have been working in the field.
   Superconductors carry electricity without any loss of energy and
could some day permit tiny computers that run at unprecedented
speeds, batteries that last forever and other technological marvels.
   Although Akzo is based in Arnhem, Netherlands, it said its
research was done at its laboratory in Dobbs Ferry, N.Y., by Fawzy
A. Sherif.
   The patent is for a process of making a superconducting powder of
uniform characteristics that contains three metallic elements,
yttrium, barium and copper, Akzo said.
   The new superconductors retain their special conducting
properties at much higher temperatures than earlier versions,
although they still must be kept very cold.
   In spite of Akzo's coup, other researchers may still receive
patents that are more fundamental and far-reaching than Akzo's. For
example, International Business Machines Corp. has applied for
patents for work done by scientists at its Zurich Research Lab in
Switzerland that led to a major breakthrough in early 1986.
   Akzo received a patent last August that also related to a process
useful for the formation of superconducting powders, but the company
said it considered the patent issued Tuesday as the first U.S.
superconductor patent to a company.
   Akzo's news release containing its claim was approved by the
Patent Office, according to Marge Waterstreet, a spokesman at the
Chicago headquarters of Akzo Chemicals Inc., a U.S. subsidiary.
   William O. Craig, a spokesman for the Patent Office, said the
federal Energy Department, which is not a company, received a patent
last August. He said it is being re-examined because of a challenge
to its validity.
   Electronic Business magazine reported last month that Japanese
researchers are leaders in the filing of patent applications in
superconductivity.
   Of 75 patent applications made public in Britain and West
Germany, where the information is disclosed earlier than in the
United States, Japan originated 59 and the United States 10, the
magazine said.
   The University of Houston expects to receive a patent for a
promising new superconducting material and in fact is getting $1.5
million from Du Pont Co. immediately and $3 million later for rights
to use the as yet unissued patent.
   The Massachusetts Institute of Technology said it has been told
by the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office that a patent would be
granted on a technique for manufacturing wires and other useful
shapes from the new materials.
   MIT has licensed rights on that forthcoming patent to American
Superconductor Corp. of Cambridge, Mass., which was founded by some
of the MIT professors who invented the process.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890214-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-FarmSupplies     02-14 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Farm Supplies,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fertilizer Use Rise Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fertilizer use by U.S. farmers is expected to
rise 9 percent this year because of larger crop plantings and higher
crop prices, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   The greater demand also will drive up fertilizer prices, the
department's Economic Research Service said in a report. By spring
planting, prices are expected to average about 7 percent more than a
year ago.
   World use of commercial fertilizers also is climbing, a trend
expected to continue at least for several more years.
   ``By the early 1990s, world growth in nitrogen demand could
exceed supply, leading to higher prices,'' the report said. ``The
developed countries will likely have excess phosphate supplies,
while the Soviet Union, Asia and Eastern Europe will be deficit
areas.''
   The greatest surplus of potash is expected to be in North
America, while Western Europe, Asia, Afria and Latin America are
projected to be in short supply, the report said.
   Some other farm production items are likely to be more costly
this spring, including pesticides, up 2 percent to 5 percent; crop
seeds, 10 percent to 15 percent; and farm energy costs.
   ``Despite the drought, 1988 farm machinery expenditures rose an
estimated 5 percent to 10 percent over 1987,'' the report said. ``A
similar increase is likely in 1989, when expenditures could reach
$6.4 billion to $7.1 billion.''
   Last year's sales of most types of machinery remained stable or
increased, except for a 16 percent drop in combine sales, the report
said. Barring poor weather, sales of all major kinds of machinery
are expected to increase in 1989.
</TEXT>
