<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2026EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-ITT     02-14 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-ITT,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>ITT Profit Down For Quarter, Year Due To One-Time Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ITT Corp. reported lower fourth-quarter and
full-year earnings for 1988 on Tuesday, blaming the results on
one-time charges and reduced tax benefits.
   Profit for the quarter totaled $180 million, or $1.26 per share,
compared with a restated profit of $421 million, or $2.84 a share,
for the fourth quarter of 1987.
   Revenue for 1988's fourth quarter totaled $5.2 billion, a 7.5
percent increase over the restated $4.8 billion in the same period a
year earlier.
   For the full year, ITT earned $817 million, or $5.70 per share,
compared with a restated $965 million, or $6.41 per share, in 1987.
   Excluding major unusual or one-time items in both years, 1988
earnings per share rose 25 percent over 1987 on a comparative basis,
the company said.
   Full-year sales for 1988 totaled $19.4 billion, a 6.2 percent
increase over the restated $18.2 billion for 1987.
   ``Both the 1988 and 1987 full-year and fourth-quarter periods
include non-recurring items that distort the performance picture of
the company during 1988,'' said Rand V. Araskog, ITT's chairman and
chief executive officer.
   The 1988 results were reduced by a $41 million after-tax
provision for ``discontinued operations'' in the fourth quarter,
primarily for several environmental clean-up operations at the
company's Southern Wood Piedmont subsidiary, ITT said.
   Profit for 1988 included tax benefits at The Hartford, ITT's
insurance company, of $52 million, compared with $100.5 million from
the same ``fresh start'' tax benefit in 1987, the company said.
   The 1987 figures were restated due to a change in accouting rules
that lowered revenues from ITT's insurance and finance operations,
the company said. ``All of our business segments with the exception
of our electronic components operation posted higher operating
income in 1988,'' Araskog said.
   ITT is involved in the manufacture and sale of automotive
components, fluid technology, defense technology and wood products;
has operations in insurance, finance and communcations; and owns the
Sheraton Hotels chain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
