<DOCNO> AP890214-0242 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 2027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Phone-Ruling     02-14 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone-Ruling,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Says Decision Important For Company, Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge's decision allowing Pacific
Telesis Group to invest in Japan's growing long-distance market is
an important step for the company and the U.S. telecommunications
industry, company officials said Tuesday.
   ``This is going to position us, and is positioning the company,
as a telecommunications player in Japan,'' said Jan Neels, president
and chief executive of Pacific Telesis International, PacTel's
international subsidiary.
   On Monday, U.S. District Judge Harold H. Greene in Washington,
D.C., allowed PacTel to buy about 8.5 percent of a Japanese
consortium that will own and operate the western end of a
fiber-optic cable between the United States and Japan.
   Greene's decision makes PacTel the first American regional phone
company to enter the $1 billion Japanese long-distance market and
the first to provide long-distance service between the U.S. and a
foreign country, said PacTel spokeswoman Susan Rosenberg.
   ``It's a very important (decision), specifically for us. ... And
I think it will encourage other companies to focus on the Japanese
market and follow our example,'' Neels said.
   The consortium, International Digital Co. Inc., plans to start
providing long-distance service using satellite connections and
other cables in May. The new cable, which will run from Honshu in
Japan to Pacific City, Ore., should be ready in late 1990, Neels
said.
   ``Our target is to finally get around 15 percent of the market
share in the initial five- or six-year period,'' Neels said. It was
too soon to tell how large a share the consortium might have
afterward, said Neels, who declined to say how the project could
affect PacTel's earnings.
   One analyst, however, believed the company's entry into the
Japanese market, growing at about 20 percent a year, would have
little effect on profits.
   ``It's a nonevent as far as their earnings will go ... given the
size of the company,'' said Edward M. Greenberg, an analyst with
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. Inc. in New York.
   American companies, supported by U.S. trade policy
representatives, have aggressively sought entrance into Japan's
telecommunications industry for the past decade.
   Major shareholders in the consortium, which received the Japanese
government's permission in late 1987, include Cable &amp; Wireless Co.
of Britain, Toyota Motor Corp. and C. Itoh and Co. of Japan.
   Pacific Telecom Cable, which has no association with PacTel, will
own the eastern end of the cable, estimated to cost between $300
million and $350 million.
   PacTel needed judicial approval before it could join the
consortium because the split-up of AT&amp;T in 1984 barred regional
phone companies from entering the long-distance telephone business.
PacTel's Pacific Bell, the leading provider of phone service in
California, is one of the seven so-called ``Baby Bells.''
   AT&amp;T and MCI Communications Corp. both objected to PacTel's
entering the Japanese market, arguing the venture would constitute
an antitrust abuse of its monopoly status as a local telephone
utility.
   But Greene, who said he based his ruling on commercial and trade
policy implications, dismissed their objections.
   The investment ``serves positive American purposes,'' Greene
wrote. Without PacTel's participation, the United States ``could
also lose a long-term opportunity to influence policies that could
open more Japanese markets,'' the judge said.
   Greene, however, refused a separate request by Nynex Corp.,
another of the regional phone companies, to take a 50 percent stake
in a trans-Atlantic fiber-optic cable with Britain's Cable &amp;
Wireless Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
