<FIRST>r f AM-Rockwell-Baker     02-14 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rockwell-Baker,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockwell To Buy British Printing Press Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwell International Corp. has agreed
to buy the printing press-manufacturing operations of Baker Perkins,
a British company, for the equivalent of about $150 million,
officials said Tuesday.
   The El Segundo-based aerospace and industrial conglomerate said
it had signed a definitive agreement for the purchase with APV PLC,
parent of Baker Perkins. The press-making operations will become
part of Rockwell's graphic systems division, which is based in
Chicago and makes the Goss presses in wide use in the U.S. newspaper
industry.
   Baker Perkins, which is based in Peterborough, England, and has
offices in Shaumburg, Ill., Toronto and Offenbach, West Germany,
makes newspaper and magazine presses and sells them primarily in
Europe.
   Rockwell, maker of the B-1B bomber, the space shuttle and a host
of military and civilian industrial products, said it had agreed to
pay 85.3 million British pounds for the printing operations, or
about $150 million at current exchange rates. The deal must be
approved by regulators in both countries and by the stockholders of
APV.
   The acquisition would help Rockwell's graphics division expand
overseas, said Donald Beall, Rockwell's chairman and chief executive
officer. Beall said last week the company was considering
acquisitions within its current lines of business.
   Baker Perkins has 1,100 employees and in 1988 had sales of $120
million.
</TEXT>
