<FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-EconomyRdp     02-14 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy Rdp,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retail Sales Rise Strongly; Bonds, Stocks, Dollar Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans increased their retail spending 0.6
percent in January, a stronger-than-expected boost that raised
concerns about inflation Tuesday.
   The inflation fears, coupled with a sharp decline in the dollar,
drove down bond prices. Stocks, up in early trading, finished the
day lower. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks closed with
a 1.25 loss at 2,281.25.
   In one measure of the bond market's weakness, the yield on the
Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond rose to 9.11 percent from
9.06 percent late Monday.
   Retail sales rose 0.6 percent in January, the Commerce Department
said. That followed a revised 0.1 percent decrease in December and a
1.3 percent increase in November.
   Retail spending is seen as a key barometer of economic health
because it represents about one-third of the gross national product.
   ``Consumers were in a pretty good mood when they started
January,'' said economist Bruce Steinberg of Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. in
New York. ``Good weather got them into shopping malls and they were
spending money. Despite higher interest rates, they did not feel
pinched.''
   Some analysts said the latest retail sales report, coupled with
other evidence of strong economic growth at the start of the year,
could lead the Federal Reserve Board to continue to nudge up
interest rates in its ongoing effort to slow the economy and keep
inflation in check.
   ``The economy will continue to exceed the speed limit, on
average, in the quarter ahead,'' said Robert G. Dederick, chief
economist for Northern Trust Co. in Chicago. ``The Federal Reserve
will have to move toward further restraint.''
   Sales of durable goods, ``big ticket'' items intended to last
three or more years, edged up 0.1 percent in January after an
identical rise in December. Non-durable goods surged 0.8 percent
after dropping 0.2 percent during the previous month.
   In other economic news Tuesday:
   _Sales of North American-made cars and light trucks fell 15.2
percent in early February from the same time last year, when
automakers were offering a larger and more varied group of
incentives.
   Incentives are available now but only on a smaller number of cars
than in early February a year ago. Also, interest rates have risen.
   _Home prices skyrocketed in California last year and continued to
command top dollar in the Northeast while sales picked up in the
lower-cost South and Midwest, a real estate trade group reported.
   The National Association of Realtors said prices of existing
homes rose 3.4 percent to a national median of $87,900 in the last
three months of 1988 compared with the same period a year earlier.
   _Interest rates on 52-week Treasury bills rose in Tuesday's
action to the highest level in nearly four years.
</TEXT>
