<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Autos 3rdLd-Writethru   02-14 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Autos, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Posts Record Earnings, Making Profit Sharing Payment To Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 7th graf to CORRECT to 1988 sted 1987; picks up 8th graf
pvs bg'ng, GM's previous ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. said Tuesday its fourth
quarter profit soared by 67.5 percent from a year earlier and the
nation's biggest automaker posted record earnings for all of 1988.
   GM's earnings mean the company will issue $114 million in
profit-sharing checks to some 470,000 hourly employees, the first
such payments since fiscal 1985.
   In the three months ended Dec. 31, GM had net income of $1.4
billion, or $4.25 a share, up from $835.8 million, or $2.36 a share,
in the same period of in 1987. Revenue during the quarter rose to
$32.4 billion from $29.7 billion a year earlier.
   For the full year, GM's earnings rose 36.9 percent to $4.86
billion, or $14.34 a share, from $3.55 billion, or $10.06 a share,
in 1987. Annual revenue rose to $123.6 billion from $114.9 billion a
year earlier.
   The per-share earnings do not reflect a 2-for-1 stock split GM
announced last week payable March 31 for shareholders of record Feb.
17.
   The 1988 results include revenue and profits for the company's
Electronic Data Systems, GM Hughes Electronics and General Motors
Acceptance Corp. subsidiaries, which reported their results
separately on Monday.
   The 1988 figures for GM included a one time gain of $224.2
million from a first-quarter accounting change.
   GM's previous record annual profit was $4.5 billion in 1984.
   The annual profits announced so far by GM and Chrysler Corp.
combined with the nine-month results from Ford Motor Co., which was
expected to announce its annual earnings on Thursday, totaled about
$10.05 billion for 1988. The previous annual record for the Big
Three was $9.79 billion in 1984.
   ``In the big picture, it's quite a bit better than it was in
'87,'' said auto analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
of New York. However, he said the figures showed stiff competition
in the marketplace, and the costs of sales incentives may affect
future profits.
   GM Chairman Roger Smith and President Robert Stempel said the
corporation's overall earnings were higher because of solid vehicle
sales overseas and a resurgence of North American operations.
   The company said it was issuing profit-sharing checks to about
470,000 employees, with the typical check amounting to about $254
per eligible employee.
   GM did not issue profit-sharing checks for the past two years
because of slumping North American performance. Profit sharing for
workers represented by the United Auto Workers union is tied to the
company's U.S. revenue.
   Healy and another analyst, Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co.,
said GM earned about $500 million in North America during 1988
following a year in which those operations pretty much broke even.
   While Brady was upbeat about the North American performance,
Healy said: ``If they earned $5 billion and only $500 million was on
the North American side. It's still disproportionate with overseas
and GMAC.''
   GM's operations overseas last year earned $2.7 billion, compared
with the $1.9 billion they earned outside North America during 1987.
   ``Although still below desired levels of profitability, GM's
North American operations achieved substantial profit improvement
and made significant progress in terms of both product
competitiveness and improved operating efficiency,'' they said.
   Part of the increase in earnings, analysts said, was due to GM's
cost-cutting program, especially in North America.
   GM said it cut $4.8 billion in costs last year, bringing its
total cost savings to $8.5 billion since its expense-reduction
program began two years ago.
</TEXT>
