<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-StockScandal 1stLd-Writethru f0273 02-14 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Stock Scandal, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0273,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dozens Of Brokers Questioned In Mexican Stock Scandal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf pvs, `The alleged ...,' to ADD
comment from stock exchange president; SUBS 14th graf, `Market prices ...,'
with 2 grafs to UPDATE with market closing price Tuesday.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government prosecutors questioned dozens of
stock brokerage officers and employees Tuesday in a probe into a
multimillion dollar illegal trading scandal, an attorney general's
office source said.
   Four top officers from Mexico's two biggest brokerage firms were
arrested Monday on fraud charges. The source, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said up to 150 more arrests may follow.
   The investigation followed complaints filed by at least 200
investors against all but one of Mexico's 24 registered brokerage
firms after stockholders lost about $7 million in the October 1987
crash.
   The alleged violations ranged from insider trading in both stocks
and foreign currencies to the sale of nonexistent Treasury
certificates and trading in securities without the consent of their
clients.
   Alfredo Harp Helu, president of the Mexican Stock Exchange, said
the National Securities Commission had determined that the brokers
and employees ``only could be given administrative sanctions because
not one case of the activities (under investigation) can be
considered criminal.''
   Harp Helu said he did not know the identities of the brokers
under investigation or what charges they could face.
   Roberto Hoyo D'Addona, the Treasury's general prosecutor, told
reporters Monday the department began receiving complaints of fraud
after the stock market index plunged 74 percent in 28 trading days.
   He said Treasury agents also are investigating possible tax
evasion.
   Spokesmen for both the attorney general's office and the Treasury
Department, which is responsible for enforcing securities trading
and tax laws, declined to comment on Tuesday's interviews.
   Among those arrested were Eduardo Legorreta, board chairman and
one of the founders of Operadora de Bolsa, one of the Mexico's two
leading trading firms, and Jaime Ceballos Cervantes, the company's
director of investment promotions.
   Legorreta, 44, is a member of one of Mexico's wealthiest
families. His arrest at a Mexico City restaurant Monday night shook
the country's business community.
   Also arrested were Juan Carlos Fernandez Cuevo and Jose Francisco
Rodriguez Dupont of Mexicana de Valores e Inversiones, the other
major brokerage firm.
   Gustavo Diaz, president of an association formed by the wronged
investors, has estimated the brokerage firms netted $43.5 million in
profits from the alleged illegal dealing.
   Market prices started dropping at the close of business on the
stock exchange Monday before the arrests, amid rumors of impending
action by the government. The 52-stock price index dropped by a
little less than 1 percent as sales increased.
   Tuesday opened with another spurt of sales, but at the close of
business the market recovered and the 52-stock price index was
slightly up by 40 points to 211,841.
   The Mexican securities and exchange commission announced it was
implanting a series of regulations, effective immediately, to
prevent future fraud.
   In a statement, the commission said the new regulations include
an automatic system to monitor daily trading and mandatory outside
auditing for all brokerage firms.
</TEXT>
